                    <h2 scrollto-destination=16661631 id="16661631" class="abstract-title js-splitscreen-abstract-title" >Abstract</h2>
<section class="abstract"><p class="chapter-para">The coming few years are likely to witness a dramatic increase in high-quality supernova data as current surveys add more high-redshift supernovae to their inventory and as newer and deeper supernova experiments become operational. Given the current variety in dark energy models and the expected improvement in observational data, an accurate and versatile diagnostic of dark energy is the need of the hour. This paper examines the statefinder diagnostic in the light of the proposed <em>SuperNova Acceleration Probe</em> (<em>SNAP</em>) satellite, which is expected to observe about 2000 supernovae per year. We show that the statefinder is versatile enough to differentiate between dark energy models as varied as the cosmological constant on one hand, and quintessence, the Chaplygin gas and braneworld models, on the other. Using <em>SNAP</em> data, the statefinder can distinguish a cosmological constant (<em>w</em>=−1) from quintessence models with <em>w</em>≥−0.9 and Chaplygin gas models with κ≤ 15 at the 3σ level if the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known exactly. The statefinder gives reasonable results even when the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known to only ∼20 per cent accuracy. In this case, marginalizing over Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> and assuming a fiducial Λ-cold dark matter (LCDM) model allows us to rule out quintessence with <em>w</em>≥−0.85 and the Chaplygin gas with κ≤ 7 (both at 3σ). These constraints can be made even tighter if we use the statefinders in conjunction with the deceleration parameter. The statefinder is very sensitive to the total pressure exerted by all forms of matter and radiation in the Universe. It can therefore differentiate between dark energy models at moderately high redshifts of <em>z</em>≲ 10.</p></section>                    <div class="article-metadata-panel clearfix at-ArticleMetadata"></div>
<div class="kwd-group"><a class="kwd-part kwd-main" href="javascript:;" data-keyword="&quot;cosmological parameters&quot;">cosmological parameters</a>, <a class="kwd-part kwd-main" href="javascript:;" data-keyword="&quot;cosmology: theory&quot;">cosmology: theory</a></div>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=16661633 id="16661633" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss1>1 Introduction</h2>
<div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">Supernova observations (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib39"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib39" data-open="bib39" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Riess et al. 1998</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib38"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib38" data-open="bib38" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Perlmutter et al. 1999</a>), when combined with those of the cosmic microwave background (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib9"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib9" data-open="bib9" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Benoit et al. 2003</a>) and gravitational clustering (Percival et al. 2002), suggest that our Universe is (approximately) spatially flat and that an exotic form of negative-pressure matter called ‘dark energy’ (DE) causes it to accelerate by contributing as much as two-thirds to the closure density of the Universe — the remaining third consisting of non-relativistic dark matter and baryons. The simplest example of dark energy is the cosmological constant (Λ), with associated mass density <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m1" content-id="m1"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq001.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq001.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=GnlOe2I~vvSWsIxZKHBxn1rOVl5cjPwkVg-XjTC2Cw9FlU1QNnc83LpzRnntMu3ZgUqig98XGQN2GrqxRDlMDcAjOxf5hWjf8ZzaCzHLJNu4TnuMacUztTHABfR8NtO4g1wkSEGWzcsBtcfJrQhCulB5CQ3zbr-y0pf9KVNz7mvc7ZI0lvLQhPBMb2KWmXvS0RZaZXHYLkOJ~FQ95Su84BzKwcbHJWxz3PsE4PCp5Fo5GitejHPpge2Btc0kXHDkrrwVZCIusU6Lr-DMIGFblt8GW~dxZ-ZVIeZamKs84ga4WiErfRV-bT~5FEfvrtvhEX0wtCW9hxTQULqxiVy5aA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq001.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(1)</span></div> where <em>h</em> is the Hubble constant <em>H</em><sub>0</sub> in terms of 100 km s<sup>−1</sup> Mpc<sup>−1</sup> and Ω<sub>Λ</sub>= 0.7 ± 0.1, <em>h</em>= 0.7 ± 0.1. Although the cold dark matter model with a cosmological constant (hereafter LCDM) provides an excellent explanation for the acceleration phenomenon and other existing observational data, it remains entirely plausible that the dark energy density is weakly time dependent (see the reviews by <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib45"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib45" data-open="bib45" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Starobinsky 2000</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib36"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib36" data-open="bib36" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Peebles &amp; Ratra 2003</a>). Moreover, it is natural to suggest (in complete analogy with what has been done in the case of another type of ‘dark energy’ responsible for driving the expansion of the Universe during an inflationary stage in the early Universe) that the dark energy that we observe today might really be dynamical in nature and origin. This means that a completely new form of matter is responsible for giving rise to the second inflationary regime, which we are entering now.</div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">Many models of dark energy have been proposed; in fact, any inflationary model [even a ‘bad’ one, i.e. without a ‘graceful exit’ to the subsequent radiation-dominated Friedmann–Robertson–Walker (FRW) stage] may be used for this purpose if one assumes different values for its microscopic parameters. The simplest of these models rely on a scalar field minimally interacting with Einstein gravity — quintessence (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib41"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib41" data-open="bib41" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Peebles &amp; Ratra 1988</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib41"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib41" data-open="bib41" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Ratra &amp; Peebles 1988</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib22"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib22" data-open="bib22" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Frieman et al. 1995</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib13"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib13" data-open="bib13" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Caldwell, Dave &amp; Steinhardt 1998</a>), and bear an obvious similarity with the simplest variants of the inflationary scenario. Inclusion of a non-minimal coupling to gravity in these models together with further generalization leads to models of dark energy in a scalar–tensor theory of gravity (see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib11"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib11" data-open="bib11" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Boisseau et al. 2000</a> and references therein). Other models invoke matter with unusual properties such as the Chaplygin gas (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib28"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib28" data-open="bib28" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Kamenshchik, Moschella &amp; Pasquier 2001</a>) or <em>k</em>-essence (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib4"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib4" data-open="bib4" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Armendariz-Picon, Mukhanov &amp; Steinhardt 2000</a>). Still others generate cosmic acceleration through topological defects (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib12"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib12" data-open="bib12" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Bucher &amp; Spergel 1999</a>) or quantum vacuum polarization and particle production (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib43"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib43" data-open="bib43" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Habib 1998</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib34"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib34" data-open="bib34" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Parker &amp; Raval 1999</a>). Lately it has been noticed that higher-dimensional ‘braneworld’ models could account for a late-time accelerating phase even in the absence of matter violating the strong energy condition (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib20"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib20" data-open="bib20" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Dvali, Gabadadze &amp; Porrati 2000</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib1"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib1" data-open="bib1" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Alam &amp; Sahni 2002</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib18"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib18" data-open="bib18" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Deffayet, Dvali &amp; Gabadadze 2002a</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib19"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib19" data-open="bib19" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Deffayet et al. 2002b</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib42"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib42" data-open="bib42" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Shtanov 2002</a>; see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib42"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib42" data-open="bib42" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni 2002</a> for a recent review of dark energy models). It is especially interesting that in the latter class of models ‘dark energy’ need not be an energy of some form of matter at all, but can have an entirely geometrical origin. Moreover, in these models the basic gravitational field equations do not have the Einstein form <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m2" content-id="m2"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq002.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq002.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=Ms6Jfh8FHgA12YS0~bc2xqrPnzSAbFfrJnidAFCDGNWV56rYcajZ9MACEKIlUpIlleUKLjTgWog9aW3Cref9at6KVbvm2AgRCpBh4oaVk5X~EPSoeLpYS74kXJ~r5qTCW9UrjLGYtqbl0VzG~VfxqyFHkwKy4~wiVPdtqyy3YyeMLSFpWbvCTupq14Fq9elBKyKGkFcZeZ9rop72RlCfFveu3hfp-HG9DKiHTfozbS~cmPmM4P8Ueth8e0yOyQnhPZuEBU7wtLI8XrStVH47Yusj-4Ti08YMQ5dGP1Kb87VKGv-I599DUuuCJUnIeFJmDrGxwjTpodOeZ8MgfWJexg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq002.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(2)</span></div> (<em>c =ħ</em>= 1 is assumed here and below), and therefore the notions of ‘energy density’ and ‘pressure’ of DE lose their exact fundamental sense and become ambiguous and convention-dependent. A major ambiguity arises in models of scalar–tensor gravity as well as in braneworld models, both of which contain interaction terms between dark energy and non-relativistic matter. Interpreting such models within the Einstein framework <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m2"></span><a href="#m2" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(2)</a> leads to the following dilemma: should these interaction terms be ascribed to dark matter (hence to <em>T</em><sub>αβ</sub>|<sub>matter</sub> in equation 2) or to dark energy (to <em>T</em><sub>αβ</sub>|<sub>DE</sub>)? Our answer to this question has the potential to alter the properties of dark energy including its density and pressure and hence also its equation of state. In marked contrast to such ambiguities which could arise if we are not careful with our usage of the term ‘equation of state’, the expansion factor of the universe in the physical frame <em>a</em>(<em>t</em>), when expressed through the Hubble parameter <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq003.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=qzYYXvQJR9EgRN7IVgAK8kc27DChKWe-kcbBGZ~KgX43ALhv4KplfNoYZo-LrUrUWImErpi05scarGCnflryjrqMSfhNZlq6zEIZ2g2VtqS6ylT4A2VHWt3oLIcTvVi~dzvUHpVcedSizWoXFkbPjEJHF8eL9u6CjJWUp9DPkgd-zptD34xzWXKNbgyPUGE~OKrma2~3uMmj-urp9zjI9e1W3bg~Ad6ZUXMJbFC2Fato1mZwYDkWdH8WsOnimMouBUR41Wwm4vyj4clMly1I4vUv6iEnzQaB3AWPa5y5VwAwDu-FfWOuhXCl94JVxmr-~JPmP3~WUpnUlhsf8DvGjg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq003.jpeg" />, is an unambiguous, fundamental and readily measurable quantity.</div><p class="chapter-para">Given the rapidly improving quality of observational data and also the abundance of different theoretical models of dark energy, the need of the hour clearly is a robust and sensitive statistic that can succeed in differentiating cosmological models with various kinds of dark energy both from each other and, even more importantly, from an exact cosmological constant. In view of the non-fundamental nature of the notions of DE density and pressure pointed out above, we prefer to work with purely geometric quantities. Then such a sensitive diagnostic of the present acceleration epoch and of dark energy could be the statefinder pair {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>}, recently introduced in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib46"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib46" data-open="bib46" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni et al. (2003)</a>. The statefinder probes the expansion dynamics of the universe through higher derivatives of the expansion factor <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq004.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=zPllETuyrLS03CFL7qk3cJUWprh29C6jA2ApZ0FQ-FVvxkw~nqd~onXfKNUhxVhWXl01ZcBAi41zIiVZxGk4IbZO3B0ESUJhvTHiz1l7LlMVTTXLyYk4dfur09xFnmaylhdLHSiR~bS0l9Yx49mJZqqDc8LNL6941mCs33cKK7XGv6uv-9xYT81Y3-bWxPI~qiXs5F9QnGDz9-uyGnRGFELqgAa4KN81NUPy8DMPZ0e8GW9TuEk6A6Pu6jeA-MT-FMmPBt3fWQKEjHem08FFZcj9a0Y1XQormwi2bKEuLtFYF3FhzSNpVfq7B1WGYMlGwUSNQIHxku5ZJ2eoLhI0Tg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq004.jpeg" /> and <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq005.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=f2Knrkl8qg~jBmYG-6DHVt47ggliNsXW6RM5WmagTkBIPesTardlwuI5PICUU1VX4Ica2KGVTJlrrOYpbAzyW8RtYl9EN1NNs-tqvVn801~asa6tgXdiQqbQf02AoyZKMTGevjKSzH6dB9F3hBf1JlAUHhedeykfNHJ7kevcaYrQktSs9w8RIo1YWPL7fqXJtHEe1PE-7NjIL7wuAPRpJy7FF3bSHcaN3ql01n9WvQe3M~IORn5VjYwbBLge1fZ9MTVSrkFX1E0Q9TzFn2poVPlSoyXS37kNGVW2HuEV5HOFU8uL3doyZE2nQL-eZXlw1oKzmBqL~Ovyc3JC1Tu1IQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq005.jpeg" />. Its important property is that {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>}={1, 0} is a fixed point for the flat LCDM FRW cosmological model. Departure of a given DE model from this fixed point is a good way of establishing the ‘distance’ of this model from flat LCDM. As we will show in this paper, the statefinder successfully differentiates between rival DE models and, when combined with <em>SuperNova Acceleration Probe</em> (<em>SNAP</em>) supernova data, can serve as a versatile and powerful diagnostic of dark energy.</p><p class="chapter-para">The paper is organized as follows. In the next section we briefly review some theoretical models of dark energy. The behaviour of the statefinder pair for these models is discussed in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss3"></span><a href="#ss3" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 3</a>, while the nature of data expected to become available from the <em>SNAP</em> experiment is the subject of <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss4"></span><a href="#ss4" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 4</a>. <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss4"></span><a href="#ss4" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 4</a> also discusses model-independent parametric reconstructions of dark energy. Our conclusions are presented in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss5"></span><a href="#ss5" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 5</a>.</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=16661638 id="16661638" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss2>2 Dark Energy Models and the Acceleration of the Universe</h2>
<div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The rate of expansion of an FRW universe and its acceleration are described by the pair of equations <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m3" content-id="m3"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq006.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq006.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=0x-Jwsl4~5DbKIIZ2r6CBazND3Xo2oDC8X-D3ZaSv-UndLunW0fbebfIZA0khyzfcH5sJKhn2M-IomQ-mpi3Ekm8b9A13LfcHXakNuPf5FZMvc~WEZCNNu2rM6ZimJEx1ZK6p2KW2aTuS072vlQGhfPn~FXLs6WPG0hesKig2OgedstKFew1U3sfu1Ihi5oIquFUR8biGoF8yZVqSjitHBbidPi2r1lt9gGLigb8cuVfr7Bhm~s-hmGoeny9p0yVet8cTLDFDZDyRBrUjFnZFo0dJxDDsQhnxDYobFqR1J7d~mIYrxdTlfcpagiS1JnoPVJ4Ui7tCAdeAUpTApj1RA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq006.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(3)</span></div> where the summation is over all matter fields contributing to the dynamics of the universe. Clearly, a necessary (but not sufficient) condition for acceleration <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq007.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=nHgkKKL4NDZ0dSXdri9HqYLJFHtUTNTP9eKsMEsmBEQ25HD-ZuDVQT8ObAU1Thhkp5aY2L6J8E5cEMamsSTA-rGx4d~bgnlptKI7hT7GZqcNYNFN6ZlKIswcrzkAmGo-GX6-lX3~u-6Vdici0SMMJkQ5OxUfTd8h32yBoVb3hF41S1WUQbWrvFIZ3wzkAsf0OTYBxmnRDrUGgxRFzfq920ipN-va0BUoPQsn~zCh6dk3qiJMdEUtMS1IHpQG-~Gwsz2jcDkMCYfFio-2xukfQMyKpWXtbAH2hJnoS4YstOvee0~X51Nb0z9OohmPzcXGHJP0DxK4XHw-tDKPKMWMNw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq007.jpeg" /> is that at least one of the matter fields in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m3"></span><a href="#m3" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(3)</a> should violate the strong energy condition ρ+ 3<em>p</em>≥ 0. If for simplicity we assume that the dark energy pressure and density are related by the simple linear relation <em>p</em>=<em>w</em>ρ, then <em>w</em> &lt; −1/3 is a necessary condition for the universe to accelerate. The acceleration of the universe can be quantified through a dimensionless cosmological function known as the ‘deceleration parameter’<img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq008.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=PySXogPz9lZY7WIF0GynSjC5gBbjPNec2iz5wNu8Por0e~3lcFiiigb2GzBOhhlYhG-7PKTMS9E4vrgUs0~V2F6Ivu~xBcES8jb05eszF2fKVznIP1HZnmuMOkxPVLig7Hs5wbhXqW8~LrRMLXG8Mcq4qODBZTri-TlIKx2QNDnbDt8WUZ2T~8do1m9aAlY22Rnsy226Ec~K5V192lss3qft7p0T2cEHilVtotUKSJKmlG4XfB1s7nAYtdt3Q~TYuD24IbSdmOPlul6e5OuhDFym-ZP1hiNAFbs-rxvnXcx6xTrLIoL5cuxBZm~S6DqziJ2WalDEMRjY5R1uN0qFig__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq008.jpeg" />, equivalently <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m4" content-id="m4"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq009.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq009.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=pMXMsRJ2otAzN5YS9ogdianDkdktlQ0BIf0zhD6QUufFl9w3dR9~q4MgZqaFP9yCx23psdhQ-ez~NNDBc7OGEENziMsrHfcutI-qSM2eiX46EgbW6Bj3K7ggy~BdrZOf5JflGf1a4ksBW27~izzR6y0cIdupP0TWzN~1WqrU67Q8nxhZuus0Yf19scKzEqwk-MpR0grfaA41A4iMqISEyVXakIREm4rm~TC9B8HPB--LXxGrrLoczB1AhNVcH4G2vHhGD2C4FQaacaMWY-f2sMupnMk2xX2RRvF0ktj8g0ZJ2jy-3dmo2~dwZFovlVe3YTjovwFXJhC-lBRzkw1vMQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq009.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(4)</span></div> where <em>q</em> &lt; 0 describes an accelerating universe, whereas <em>q</em>≥ 0 for a universe that is either decelerating or expanding at the ‘coasting’ rate <em>a</em>∝<em>t</em>. As will soon be shown, the deceleration parameter on its own does not characterize the current accelerating phase uniquely. The presence of a fairly large degeneracy in <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) is reflected in the fact that rival dark energy models can give rise to one and the same value of <em>q</em><sub>0</sub> at the present time. This degeneracy is easily broken if, as demonstrated in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss3"></span><a href="#ss3" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 3</a>, one combines <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) with one of the statefinders <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>), <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>). The diagnostic pairs {<em>r</em>, <em>q</em>} and {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} provide a very comprehensive description of the dynamics of the universe and consequently of the nature of dark energy.</div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">Now let us come to the issue of defining the energy density and pressure of DE. In view of the ambiguities discussed in the introduction, we shall define ρ<sub>DE</sub> and <em>p</em><sub>DE</sub> by making use of the <em>Einstein interpretation</em> of gravitational field equations (not to be confused with the notion of the Einstein frame, which is used in scalar–tensor and string theories of gravity!). Namely, we assume that the gravitational field equations in a single-metric theory of 3+1 gravity can be formally written in the form <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m2"></span><a href="#m2" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(2)</a> where the Einstein tensor on the left-hand side is defined with respect to the physical space–time metric. <em>All other terms are transferred to the right-hand side.</em> Next, we subtract the energy–momentum tensor of dust (CDM + baryons) from the total energy–momentum tensor of matter and call the remaining part ‘the effective energy–momentum tensor of dark energy’ (in the Einstein interpretation). Combining this prescription with <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m3"></span><a href="#m3" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (3)</a> and in the absence of spatial curvature, the energy density and pressure of dark energy can be defined as <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m5" content-id="m5"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq010.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq010.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=ASjOfBddFmg45pFtdw3ibVC-PG3rAuuoM2TNqhuhVrYsYhAH9Dscww1jqWOHMLtBYi8PwrGIzA5veZsrisqpBnvs9SsQz3VMqP2wzPpfuNul5649WXx-yxZ-zNOykueCCPh4eL~T7y052KUydK7OLNtuWBCmgog8-0OEPREDAfcaD1wFceaTYCzS60SIEKVZsczQm46tRU-RObG2BxQgseihmrH1-ukHl58xf~JL6ZtFEat9-nVtuYdmKGobIHstyaQDaT1ishY4ofo0lUO3Cs~cArztVnDODKlk4xYUQkQJ1K8c3hfyLnL~InYdrWbMY0pBqgJgTpBbuYR6tIJong__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq010.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(5)</span></div> where ρ<sub>critical</sub>= 3<em>H</em><sup>2</sup>/8π<em>G</em> is the critical density associated with an FRW universe. An important consequence of using this approach is that the ratio <em>w</em><sub>DE</sub>≡<em>p</em><sub>DE</sub>/ρ<sub>DE</sub> can be expressed in terms of the deceleration parameter <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m6" content-id="m6"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq011.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq011.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=fCL9P4f5PqqWHDpGY9tsMMoO4KvecI8v5qLwx1z7u~Qxge9VHAgjWmzXltPpA2FrHKfogpuiWeP-oYJyW9B6IK5x6vClb6ZZqEVVckRr80Q0lYPmeX~bEfoNu0hkbEWDGp92E6KGHKEBGF14IeRMhMtastJ8tbkPGLzyvsLPHg0tXqEfyRdeBIfqYmlYHZH3CYZbwMXlsZO33FQOpNDXtaqQRtmaIA6bwO~Djf4SQOwsN5fX87AnSfJisjrVMJG6rpcNapW2M3DmSMBaF7Vga808N0JyB25u1sQckjejy4ODmDsNLQDANcf-AzWSR7YeB~~jHlOkeDrtzun5gFqVOQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq011.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(6)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">Following the above prescription we obtain standard results for the cosmological constant and quintessence (for instance, we recover <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m9"></span><a href="#m9" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation 9</a>). However, the same cannot be said of braneworld models since the Hubble parameter for the latter contains interaction terms between matter and dark energy (see, for instance, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m22"></span><a href="#m22" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equations 22</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">23</a>) and therefore does not subscribe to the Einsteinian format <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m2"></span><a href="#m2" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(2)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m3"></span><a href="#m3" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(3)</a>. One can, however, extend the above definition of <em>w</em><sub>eff</sub> to non-Einsteinian theories by <em>defining</em> dark energy density to be the remainder term after one subtracts the matter density from the critical density in the Einstein equations. It should be emphasized that, according to this prescription all interaction terms between matter and dark energy (such terms arise in scalar–tensor and brane models) are attributed <em>solely</em> to dark energy. Therefore, <em>w</em><sub>eff</sub>(<em>z</em>) defined according to <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m6"></span><a href="#m6" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(6)</a> is an <em>effective equation of state</em> in these models and not a fundamental physical entity (as it is in LCDM, for instance).</p><p class="chapter-para">In this connection we should also stress that the propagation velocity of small inhomogeneities in dark energy is generically neither <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq012.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=XH4Mak8R8narbt3Ag~pehs403WiTqI0znNOtIOhSo6iC8RNvgWt2tJbElrEFNyUAeCAazAmR~K2yLtkV6SdXDzEaghnRr5LKAXY1MvJbCAzys12zMWEBVxYQBiaCDSzjpjOpqX2G78fGeLsgUV6x854hHDWKoWxWnX6KscpIACP6DWjdyT1iWA5BRBEk4bP0DMhRDe3Bg1Dlxur28Y5p-6dWX1ThEHQNzcuhq5xX8j8RZ38r79wkA-r~1HQIbu846c6mCzTuyUCsZ~aHtY6dhtq-uRyWZysp9iB5o06Tbp2XKVXQVypxf1PFhRcxbvPDS6xQ~n5INfHfyeIiRjrkWA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq012.jpeg" />, nor <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq013.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=ge7Mbh1eeq2Ha4q82MR6FfINxB6ugRokVaeELEFc0ejEIN4aaFLWRzXNdCkSKb7NcUHlwvpvKno98hd8Kh9Y-f7DVA208J6JocJNe~Zfq-6WwVcBdyH42qvC2UpEe9JzSuYzBMtJR4gXZZVQczqzTzGmUR8pX1~GUqr30wUPY54xqPpaa-2XGM1KoCNbIQ1LnB0iTCfMyafVaCtu8EslSKQJ~QFHdDyhp8PwS3yuEyNB7IMwCuyg56R2oZap5dPgSAB1vpG9n0g3xAS4pzeM0XtQ0E0BeTqh2NLdbNZFCOCE3LDeNrkj7CQ55r2orvjMFKihAs8FNX99-PxeU6A3VQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq013.jpeg" />. Therefore, although <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>) is an important physical quantity it does not provide us with an exhaustive description of dark energy and its use as a diagnostic should be treated with some caution. (In this paper we will restrict ourselves to a spatially flat FRW model and will not consider inhomogeneous perturbations on this background.)</p><p class="chapter-para">We now highlight a few popular candidates for dark energy, which shall be the focus of our discussion in this paper.</p><p class="chapter-para"></p><ul class="list-simple"><li><span class="label title-label">(i)</span><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            "><strong>Cosmological constant.</strong> Perhaps the simplest model for dark energy is a cosmological constant Λ, for which the energy density remains constant with time ρ<sub>Λ</sub>≡Λ/8π<em>G</em>=−<em>p</em><sub>Λ</sub>, and which has an equation of state <em>w</em><sub>Λ</sub>=−1. A universe consisting of matter in the form of dust and the cosmological constant is popularly known as LCDM, the Hubble parameter for this model has the form <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m7" content-id="m7"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq014.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq014.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=2OQoc5TVsynhHfHoqf4EE0AvztmVioamw9Z3o~~JetGU5Hs5LJUD4g8Jav929Upb1yZ9aG-lG-F63OmAP~GZ6EXZSm4on8rjjExOGPBB7CL1lnxirfGcroWFaDRV1PAVgyQCZpnekGViwgcdG00xO8V9XAM8hFVJV9pPxnLQBZRp-NvK9xIAyoKfPCnMuGFJySQnCSaf6JNKGJDy5mac8kDWy7z0-r4BeV-PWJjLrgzzuF8tlJlA7MdyuRU8j0efAwiz9u3KJ8xUIgAI5RaHw3~xyUfUho2~a3bon4OsDLHu-B3uoZFRd4NwvAwAXwBmfYSzXr20qa1k6e0ZmdsnDg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq014.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(7)</span></div></div></li><li><span class="label title-label">(ii)</span><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            "><strong>Quiessence.</strong> The next simplest form of dark energy after the cosmological constant is provided by models for which the equation of state is a constant <em>w</em>= constant ≠−1. For this form of dark energy, which we call ‘quiessence’, <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m8" content-id="m8"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq015.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq015.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=0Ka0iL12LGwuClIPWjYxu-OqkrhaauUXa-1YmHS301cZU4-U4TAIi0CXs1rD83Q3s6hCbZca4sS~7-qmla9Jm2kiZTI6oaFcEwikDRSoVYxox91~FrYRBB-f180yOiB-loSadec9oNEcYtHDDEO7zWCW9qySOMOWtKmJhFypFZZOphJio9BfwLhbPftvoO422~op2rfb-NXw9v5FjrGod-EDWcG6pWWmaZCO35uFZHUwtgBtvmAioYEzeKmm3eg5sqQjsg6pj1yyDNm0XeSVmiKRTq6fH2YhiRJJDgrsNn1bfwE9~c3USXFLLTgnBQhney2X9LURFxre-RWxDURyiQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq015.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(8)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">For <em>w</em>=−1 we recover the limiting form <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m7"></span><a href="#m7" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(7)</a>. Important examples of quiessence include a network of non-interacting cosmic strings <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq016.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=bo2mMnRudyUDH40rrNwBYWz8xOui2MiqIqV5KIvE8Izz~NVX21vDFoFYh1Cfyj76RMWpIsGx8RqD6x~tskiYvVFoiLbz~BV5ATD1JmwL0o8rgwYbjgFT6rJzkz0nUGmS8VO5Gct2ChVf2rCU80yUUhUd9y71cO-Q5Ij8s2b-TWDVFZrL4A6~akAX8KEydGQhP-9Rj94YuaeyCYESNAS5TJg-vWmitI-pLNBebh1~tDEGTvsFXJLRtvYyAQhjoL8Skq5dCE~KkKasI3VJflky22lTPnDbz2qDL4LxXpyLU40oXdpN4jsUAIFZufDzu6gHxokWYwPYlu20pRb~J-zmMw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq016.jpeg" /> and domain walls <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq017.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=BmIadoLBR-ci~KkDfnAMfG3GY7aHZtXGjXqnudFilLyaru0RrjETra6N-bKkN99HgDZse4xPDX86CJ9cOT7YuqPcSlT~06UAPlzzErbJbdrCOF9~noyIv6cgda-3xHmd2RcgkwkQrxe1b3sA1A6UyT~Vm0fS4mU0LFpiRv1rPJJYHvo8Rz33VeVADh1Lioo5cACYUsIhpmNji54s8j6RAvROTQmWQBE5bvTz0QV-G370Y6kMCWAizalPzWQtcOHV5uM6YFhsxXEt1HQ4fHj1HXowXrRI-Sd8gD6XOdnkO~sQXrnvD3DPtMQ5JfFEgGxG6sxSEF1s1R3VKECSVkipbw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq017.jpeg" />. Quiessence in an FRW universe can also be produced by a scalar field (quintessence), which has the potential <em>V</em>(φ) ∝[sin h(<em>C</em>φ+<em>D</em>)]<sup>−2(1 +<em>w</em>)/<em>w</em></sup>, with appropriately chosen values of <em>C</em> and <em>D</em> (see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib45"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib45" data-open="bib45" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Starobinsky 2000</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib51"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib51" data-open="bib51" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Urena-Lopez &amp; Matos 2000</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib46"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib46" data-open="bib46" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni et al. 2003</a>).</p><p class="chapter-para">Usually the dark energy equation of state depends upon time. We call such more generic models <em>kinessence</em>.</p></li><li><span class="label title-label">(iii)</span><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            "><strong>Quintessence.</strong> The simplest example of kinessence is provided by quintessence — a self-interacting scalar field that couples minimally to gravity. Its density, pressure and equation of state are given by <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m9" content-id="m9"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq018.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq018.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=qX-BrH0VxQIpKVWVY0XpUc1Jm2nv7vkU989a6UN6e8Xgb2XP-WE-04mWOTOJMEzus2mYDIRw2cxMUX20rMQwa1wEWeSGh9Bc-OpyDuez88XKc~TT5VnkP0dgGSHfx4FJ3RJzJtVRHZiBZ4GKDDcdsp~RVPtm1NmVeLXjLexrDNp37vxpChipSf2kOmeq9uCSvmtc6opHe6smGq4v~eT~JTA4Be8W19llwjL5U2ZlbmpHavOmj14-7t3GiwqfLsRwOYWbNlLdrIUO~RwpnEfzLrTtE3JeZKZNlLYx65FSJeNhGW6rEQtIzMzgMp8noHtwGMM1qM-XYIe3idVCbiw4Gw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq018.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(9)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">Scalar field evolution is governed by the equation of motion <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m10" content-id="m10"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq019.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq019.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=yozW-DkpUe4SBQnJ~Krkv2yLcgE--xQB5q6vA4PgIW4sELS7iDcT1aae9PH-erjCU1dX36emaghSEyvHg~xD9zWolPkW2R4m91IdF84Aw9C~ZnsmzvbmD9EnTJo4Kj5J9ox-UDSf~JFKUZfG-pSXQjd5KR4Z7gCgkYoj9MOuui9q9ga6XxZs1x-IgXUleRBWcGRR3MSIknhMyeHFan8~qdghYMPJ~E0E~ZNlkaneIuiAaNkrv1hbyOAFj3yJBhL5Dx8ONTg3EO-SNYV83LuadtShe02v9jROqG5GdUP9Sa3m1Mv--IO~wazU-2gCaq3YTkanjM2DuWFE5-LiLWPo8Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq019.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(10)</span></div> where <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m11" content-id="m11"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq020.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq020.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=fPuyAW1lLiJDkbwwuM8aQdU-5UTTqDG-BxLK0y-P7R1N4yKJjaJiwk4ALEAD-OtN5D8r1-dLOZBPoTf1V0K4KjGyUoIKZu4KVKP9BfclPQy8sWqYcsO3NYO8hEYxNKt-F~7jRLIRSMW25F9jDDjiifG7gVd6pbrmjkR5xeTSa4c2armQj51vvWEb35qmGm5IdCDGoG24tZWsYZhdI1G1XvP60E4eCecKIh4VktOscG1SKiad7-1maxTNU4U65x526TLxygYKUXPhgD~iX97a6nM8-gyV8Pob9uBLHaVSEEyDf0Thtgpb5Q~53PMkWeTMbXrs05AsVb~h6v1-mUHxOQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq020.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(11)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">It is clear from <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m9"></span><a href="#m9" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(9)</a> that <em>w</em> &lt; −1/3 provided <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq021.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=YBk7ziSXGdbVzjnAXdA23pXeyItqhwv2w1-y7cVTETH7T7DPVrnlgFN1Iyhlk6ZFdRd9sVhdmyWQKW33n056l0UkZl8uMDvQogghXEdk9DliNSnRc4x7ToKv5FJ4bzuvALFX4Q3oZ1VJrG85K6Stj4oEX24ZvoCQ3QBGgdZrQPeG3p6txa6ysVWs58jxNN-XSs2ME4uU-VIq2FOb0RuO2Qqv~93UneP0n8wfQhvYzg6DDgmue~0THYg3056e6ySWdjWTa1v7DRLCsSODfpZyso1mqlO3mvH4aj2aaqJxbDFi25yKXdUcf8nkcdp4RA58vU32AGEAicfE-aaJ-jpvIQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq021.jpeg" />. Models with this property can lead to an accelerating universe at late times. An important subclass of quintessence models displays the so-called ‘tracker’ behaviour during which the ratio of the scalar field energy density to that of the matter/radiation background changes very slowly over a substantial period of time. Models belonging to this class satisfy <em>V</em>″<em>V</em>/(<em>V</em>′)<sup>2</sup>≥ 1 and approach a common evolutionary ‘tracker path’ from a wide range of initial conditions. As a result, the present value of dark energy in tracker models is to a large extent (though not entirely) independent of initial conditions and is determined by parameters residing only in its potential — as in the case of the cosmological constant (for a brief review of tracker models see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib42"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib42" data-open="bib42" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni 2002</a>). In this paper we will focus our attention on the tracker potential <em>V</em>(φ) ∝φ<sup>−α</sup>, α≥ 1, which was originally proposed in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib41"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib41" data-open="bib41" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Ratra &amp; Peebles (1988)</a>. For this potential, the region of initial conditions for φ for which the tracker regime has been reached before the end of the matter-dominated stage is <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq022.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=aJ9-G4brvxKl65ufUX97YyeXipit4PP4tVBZCzqLpGnly0iZ3MYD6lBZCT7BMGU9-4Qy1X4bzpaFhlO6y2ydzNTWGiHe7AvC5YC7sfgOvbb8Oa-aE4RJLHYoV~kWLQe6ViNNIek5w9Q~YNrsMZdLYY3B0bc3O8DX-aEeMWDzdyEzlEXizgXo67RSlcbWeCntHsPVEx0k0t0kZUUnl7TRNWHn3UIyxiPuk15i9WaiIk-mqXBVb~FTjhp9d9VfAGUD2hSRSChrRG8GhFdIf~G5Wu6SKaPLqsqof1VEp5HgEZlB1iNi7mE6r-CahXg4dpGQSgGlVvUrlTdJ60nmDLY7Yg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq022.jpeg" />, and the present value of quintessence is φ(<em>t</em><sub>0</sub>) ∼<em>M</em><sub>P</sub>.</p><p class="chapter-para">For all quintessence models <em>w</em>≥−1, and this inequality is saturated only if <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq023.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=U6ntbpPMl7zTPwO~xB0kBb7V9nJQyJIKKyM7vzdku9djflf6tQVKiqAHH6BSmbC5g1EbxrdPttXMiRljjIcoQcBI3-mNwh9Vm92k0VPWOdZwXTL5x8bPJKWAs9EMIxtdWfNBuGohwk89JNK~aetdMuglDYh0RW8ZW67bg6xCiUeiA7JYdK4kCgvEmSa1V74Lod0YJI9TXkpmRgn6XDkYZ9DQ38dzyrg4idMd1AShDFY8A6cy9b2o6E2E8dTufM0QPZjFoPxUe1aEReiVcWuAaGGa0KzoJg9JSe73Fb2mT96ZJ5mY5k-4thdiJeIKLyD6bZ42GgtoxRUzRZ0hKBWuxg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq023.jpeg" />. In order to obtain <em>w</em> &lt; −1 matter must violate the strong energy condition ρ+ 3<em>p</em>≥ 0, for some duration of time. It should be noted that DE with <em>w</em> &lt; −1 is not excluded by observations (see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib32"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib32" data-open="bib32" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Melchiorri et al. 2002</a> for a recent investigation). However, in order to have <em>w</em> &lt; −1 one must look beyond quintessence models. Models based on scalar–tensor gravity (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib11"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib11" data-open="bib11" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Boisseau et al. 2000</a>) can have <em>w</em> &lt; −1, so too can braneworld models (see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib42"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib42" data-open="bib42" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Shtanov 2002</a> for a discussion of this issue and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib1"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib1" data-open="bib1" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Alam &amp; Sahni 2002</a> for a comparison of braneworld models with observational data).</p></li><li><span class="label title-label">(iv)</span><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            "><strong>Chaplygin gas.</strong> An interesting alternate form of dark energy is provided by the Chaplygin gas (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib28"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib28" data-open="bib28" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Kamenshchik et al. 2001</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib10"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib10" data-open="bib10" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Bilic, Tupper &amp; Viollier 2002</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib21"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib21" data-open="bib21" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Fabris, Goncalves &amp; de Souza 2002</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib2"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib2" data-open="bib2" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Alcaniz, Jain &amp; Dev 2003</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib5"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib5" data-open="bib5" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Avelino et al. 2003</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib25"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib25" data-open="bib25" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Gorini, Kamenshchik &amp; Moschella 2003</a>), which obeys the equation of state <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m12" content-id="m12"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq024.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq024.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=l2xkmVmiwZ-3YVQjsPRkLthJLH3naE1oSRKVVYLkLAHFXeCrZLuW9CCTj3nQIF-1a90m0oGogZFxuZH4-9BF7n6Qmyffsjsz0ISNntNGaEsQZm6L~TkQDrPMEm7nbGkYK~LhmSEsqw2wB8N~Q0QTSgt7k8qNyY5rtChBjU6t9tqKBM1HSfY4Ve5I-Xr0wX555aXgvxS-yqXbpyHUB8ctOc~VZCwT~GUVYuAz2-Ck1cYGRwUdIFS0HOVVY5EyJn53C0qiTZcqLZHdq~IDRQ3-uT7R57UAhgal4LgTQMTNfX8YPplxb5WtSmqAcwA9bSa2EnT2gTypBE0dLaKiX-hhSQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq024.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(12)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The energy density of the Chaplygin gas evolves according to <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m13" content-id="m13"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq025.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq025.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=yUCePL59vG26RmdfPVcpkYkI1byGR6kKUiqdVINs~d30ceRwn1arqXOd4he~bshOkRXIcxng1OXqjo5HaHAHuJdRbO0a1AC22MqsmCTp8o62Luafnv4AWFliH2RaV80oaw8igEDAogUVAcxy8Y1OJGxaBZDIPOlWyvJHkLiqutwyL2bc1WftO65JJL1D1yM5JLgoNpYlfgsLkWa82oZCuAregadw8ZoOAkKsEVvSMdeFq26NpuPO39WbeZh4gHK8yk~JxsSLKLX8H5dDkOmkWz-3otjTyFhgVmB6rEr9Kxfv-78mtI2nqDXcX2Vz2OyudqrBRqGan~jLNMGsjfSHyA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq025.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(13)</span></div> from where we see that <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq026.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=G209abwSsEAO3aFMjLJCjYsNkWfKIa9dvYr7luk3RiTb0QOYdyGTOxvLM3Vo2OIvi0UFo5h5FeXHfKnmZ5rIkbXs6F5U48fig05nMohJnoRmDqCKiZClLEmGHAyxpdMeRquvyyFIhQm-dD~hkjIbNwD7fMbotDc~xZf2ILi7Ihbsp9kYjIQYoKa4SOIzsyr~2civhNQhCyow~ajJClZGAH2GAQ-VdvmFswVyhm6babGwHrGBC7vSTPuUIHbgel~0lxylrhthf8kO~AarVAt9pKfWHiirCplS8umgXt7zXP9mzgaxPoRuUfh1vADHPK95n6YPsFN8G-O7dVvrJIkRdQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq026.jpeg" /> as <em>z</em>→−1 and <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq027.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=TNRx0AUPZRUJ0ypZ-gIh0H0K519Dcjcu8caUWfmdA4EeexgCPWYqWz14uvGfer0P9choebYeTObpT0kVDiL4coe0AEORNuQeqa41mDx8y62h93IT7Q-AcE0w6tsUT2eAGDFC9o3zfWjwrQKty~ehf0Afe5SVYClJtrCqQzSrahAhNRhNOCjLaD0x88Ap2bcQc85XY4VNkkKjuAjGdAqV7-kjMHrj55M7HbmAZqOGFTwA5gIHaySeL7LXwmGE3wHBkvolMM7nIweuAVi8fFd5liSB2epJ~Vk0osVSSeSBEFyHgrvWeC4x4UVBnkouraRNHC5CQbMYuC2adfapbVzIRQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq027.jpeg" /> as <em>z</em>≫ 1. Thus, the Chaplygin gas behaves like pressureless dust at early times and like a cosmological constant during very late times. Note, however, that Chaplygin gas at <em>z</em>≫ 1 is not simply a new kind of CDM if we examine its inhomogeneities (i.e. if we apply this hydrodynamical equation of state to the inhomogeneous case, too)! In contrast to CDM and baryons, the sound velocity in the Chaplygin gas <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq028.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=oLjWJWWwLDqXN2QlYtWkhK4oTMVnT2a5LVgFqaQoSuKFQwcT~yzW3KAXt1ZxIPWVRNwA5XZbSGHazuaHuzaNdJSfl7ea3V0izl-96kGW8~t6Fq6JM7GNkIAZdRf7QtI7CtuljFy2Kag52wKAM1rUI7kBMwWz0YX47Puz718Lj67FkB7bWjxqKSayz7aPboWdmSCR5RHYzSM8C8Tm9bEnkX3mrIoxmY3hxgB87UHxNc2N0Kzrd45VZRBin3mouyobxZ8wHuP~9CJNuFyhmo2EcFQrvHRzQp3t2o51mhmHTy3quVBF5tnFGSbNikDe1kxeGNDVuehtabGaWr7zQA8H2g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq028.jpeg" /> quickly grows ∝<em>t</em><sup>2</sup> during the matter-dominated stage and becomes of the order of the velocity of light at present (it approaches light velocity asymptotically in the distant future). Thus, from the point of view of inhomogeneities, the properties of the Chaplygin gas during the matter-dominated epoch are very unusual and resemble those of hot dark matter, which has a large Jeans length, despite the fact that the Chaplygin gas formally carries negative pressure.</div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The Hubble parameter for a universe containing cold dark matter and the Chaplygin gas is given by <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m14" content-id="m14"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq029.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq029.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=jEmTlahxKvViaEGrm6ZuLUG2zcBXtNvzctUWTCYlnj7-xYx5JVJqySUeohYOCJAeR2-vTKizaql06S8WpuDuSKbPlZj6VKm-2dxBixMuYK2I-6JJuoMc5adYYpIDtAB9HIboFglxSJJqVge0AHHPnL3VEzMEqthuq5RCMfn4P16rkjfW0oewCTFIku2wCzludNLUZjf2SUHn9qbZdu1pyTdwlJxZFUPX279tsTnm2srkYD0GJ29h77NXinaWFl~k9ElC7NtQW5Gg77ldcsEt4kyllFexuqrPijZFClMrp9NmXzz90j8FmY0YcIZdC~zKmVwCacfHZCdfgzs3In0udQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq029.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(14)</span></div> where <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq030.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=wyZO78T3Rw4-D9tb1OCNd0tNB04GinGOUFoJye91NxJtIwQ25u8QG~2ZixYWl9ULM1Mda7i-~ne0QMHDVyKgy2R1uXrt-UC7JKsmzZ7yT68imbeN-YVWk0wrZ9f40WnEdiNJWQd0x2x5VoApA9QEI5SOdehlToF~-yjQZqmVCudFvUBj7ha8y6IJX4p7jLbGlUhv7ua2~DISkBCw56VtMgXC2ytk~Weq62NRmPOpEZ0asmS5CbttffOVA523PybXhB1zt81SDQtrpEtggHTUe-wuhhB3WtdpgObJfdJr3lyIF2Dk05wcnRLwr50W~h8lEUjDAWrGqzIlkF2~MLuphA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq030.jpeg" />. It is easy to see from <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m14"></span><a href="#m14" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(14)</a> that <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m15" content-id="m15"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq031.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq031.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=ukR9c-SM~0fCLMapvbGUp1G9Ly3L9nXyAPTgfccp5vMjtO8Ei1IZxCXBlyA5wajBtAa0Bs2QeENju7B2UXcQqU~B2PxHDrrvIL3Sz21spT5d8lnmJH0kjj3MXGKQ89yuH9vei~YZWmh1gM-IxB9Qo1BqNs5Kja8I3giCDplhQs4AINnIwG7jIVVoTBVqFvkQdQkA38b7ZQP8EKrXOGL--vib0RzP1fzn4uxhcDeTDME2aueGyP8-mDgy01P2ykqBq~Zc40wuJDjz-uPcDHeNvPowCS78c0Za6gAjn36TaDyWO9oKFQT-QYLeEDLGtKMJuSZAtOQqnbpsWW82UgiMAg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq031.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(15)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">Thus, κ defines the ratio between CDM and the Chaplygin gas energy densities at the commencement of the matter-dominated stage. It is easy to show that <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m16" content-id="m16"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq032.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq032.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=Ji44FKHg5huQgh-fZ2XXwKg7s4MHopUXe-MQ6VBnZZss0gliuhgft1KOVUXDfIOES8frJnkV8RQFWe1HBKGT4xINjMLiyKtHDU0cfUhnqVI1u~cPiUYCsCrlAdWyUN-Lv-Q91htlcKPnHWfAIWkoZbReCCbG3PXlO~4Gl1S~bxsDi8e8kURqPnceFCx2DPl~kePd~T0XLggau-wfzT0v5JOHO9Cq3S0dFuB2JXRhPsmvWm8CAml8e55m3tTSenMi~VuELAkJnKkBEx5KBj6MV~pJrCbPbybWMKf3zyFvJkG0GNYGZHV-NYQRF~7yJ8hfyIvcr1IoBrBRH1W1Wph1oQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq032.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(16)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">In the limiting case when <em>A</em>= 0, the Chaplygin gas becomes indistinguishable from dust-like matter (if we examine its behaviour in an unperturbed FRW background). This limiting case corresponds to <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m17" content-id="m17"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq033.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq033.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=vHv92u6iXP9rs4y-sA1EQnkQvlc~m-OLO61OBG71emZQcpWQ1bSZ8f5JPxSlqyj3kaJc3n5ezKndX5DqUI56QvtLuKvFNx3fmup2dQgz1Ts0gX0TKPcz7ZqLj-wYCOFdY0StFmtUH5T8ZKcvUykV2n3BfvHEFCMa3gVSQbNXaUqZlQIfLlfqFClE3xXZgFjpLQ16BhRuImE9umaQYhBFeivJhCZeWKO~YH8QKw91Nq4Tdk3QQWqfi9EULHpDf1oprO67uBSeiYJQTZjdnvlo0N--baYkR5-rsCtUMtVKlYCAvlQM~Sx4JmFZtTTOyq2ze6UGmumDADPFhINlzpNXTQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq033.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(17)</span></div> and is shown as the outer envelope (dashed) to the Chaplygin gas models in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig1"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig1" class="link xref-fig">Figs 1(a) and (b)</a>. In the other limiting case <em>B</em>= 0, the Chaplygin gas reduces to the cosmological constant.</div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The fact that the sound velocity in the Chaplygin gas is not small during the matter-dominated stage and becomes very large towards its end suggests that the parameter κ should be large in order to avoid damping of adiabatic perturbations. This requires <em>A</em>≫<em>B</em>. Recent investigations, which look at Chaplygin gas models in the light of galaxy clustering data and CMB anisotropies, show that this observation is correct if the equation of state <em>p</em><sub>c</sub>∝−1/ρ<sub>c</sub> is assumed to be universally valid (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib14"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib14" data-open="bib14" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Carturan &amp; Finelli 2002</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib48"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib48" data-open="bib48" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sandvik et al. 2002</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib6"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib6" data-open="bib6" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Bean &amp; Dore 2003</a>). In our paper we consider the Chaplygin gas equation of state to be a phenomenological description of dark energy in an FRW background and do not assume that it remains true for perturbations. However, the fact that κ should be large for viable models will appear in our results, too. Finally, let us point out that the Chaplygin gas may be considered to be a specific case of <em>k</em>-essence with a constant potential and the Born–Infeld kinetic term. To illustrate this consider the Born–Infeld Lagrangian density <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m18" content-id="m18"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq034.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq034.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=rav3uOtLYTtnKI3BR3GQ5XiSGTBR6URyf-cFT~NXCmCGrUbETAou6JE6~bnF8e7MS0jQq0GR9J5Say0DkFEmwAQ3JrX9aR~zztXjJR6yJKvyzGU2hLche-0Xg7fV~OyPybADkEPXj0N4dk7ryTJqSUdpHPw73NDRBT6-xiZQyASiQXg7jPySRJi-vKugzrNk0Eqkn2vyP5rHoTY~~-Btxnu621Uq0x8DgsDq~KLS8zTCvpjj9RictDFx6zdDrNvd3yf-2NqNRLMaaRKbRxAw6MMJ1UWb84b~gIDlMTl~~Qrjkk6HBH~eY3FA4pi5PWERNYWrp8588ZIK-6iX05f40Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq034.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(18)</span></div> where φ<sub>,μ</sub>≡∂φ/∂<em>x</em><sup>μ</sup>. For time-like φ<sub>,μ</sub> one can define a four-velocity <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m19" content-id="m19"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq035.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq035.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=VkteC31glixEHvEz0iW7C-7Vkt2SCg3hKsan8DqYKvVL0SNam95~BKpsCnU4K44TwH~kTDz08c58C93juADwTp63d-3bf3vkeSAkPgaGrDgBOTMrkinQm5IpG8Y8o5hRQ3bmkGi8Jbw0EyPnVd-EGdxVVkN78Yuk~JU1obSfWnfGsIJR0OQpMfXdMz2JXwAUd39XST-BZDI4jL2z-6aiE6HtZ-HYZeHp6StfO6wly8ijCVp-oDuOEg9-GdzMqVsFRuhJztw6SlghkXtZnaeDzS-YEcl24a6smGAYzP4Iom5Es6lQgEZCMNOdmnwJbqWi4VkvNU9E01jJnEALh02SMQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq035.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(19)</span></div> this leads to the standard form for the hydrodynamical energy–momentum tensor <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m20" content-id="m20"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq036.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq036.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=GHoNA3KSpwEQtdnTNwNy0H73d6ke~lU6aDOcyvq85l-JMH18dN2nFIlcvJWSsCEolqHBM6FZwZUreEXbDXTHB7ATw4KqoTd0tO6woIrpL5BbMB9xWHs0LedmYSNQxrwlnYciHiXHhNbs4AocsroBqzMe2VKuUUNfLHUG~5hfnN~3IS33NQ2kDuXso6RMd7tx4mK-Ekl2Amv7jUc5NpQvP85xZIW98Qr7E6SqbF6tfKhj2f9RbIvKaPpzwERWw7b9P~MfzqRZD9n~XtZZe5aJCTaFJ6sZpKYciZntTA8RFUqfR7f-zzgWAaoqXd7wKbjEU6HDCMErWeoRAVXN8QhzYw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq036.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(20)</span></div> where (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib23"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib23" data-open="bib23" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Frolov, Kofman &amp; Starobinsky 2002</a>) <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m21" content-id="m21"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq037.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq037.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=08jbCH83Bv5V5PuyBDhjP0ewPODGYjWkteIKWM8gLMHqpIuQKl5nEJnh~nlwg6ltBX5moTTqvByRrTaPQh5ujnwfAVW8Ahc5r2NLhN5u2EOCGkd2I~aAwjxhfHrQ1FdNlWZBTWPYe-gQsZ5hw2X-6n7dGdlCYtZBKGqsfuUPvjtwMMUMKo38tD43frMhxzgV6kHisVHrqdg~zVzYQZsPxQpjOD2lLP01zbGYz9~QOFV-UfRjiKm4xRBrdzPh71mJ7kLhf5-z-6oMpXHs5aBcQHD3mwc~b-uzMwv7hoWcav2y7UBsvj1F0fAb2TXjSIdMTO95UGUzQ4LQG5pnHPQ7JQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq037.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(21)</span></div> and we find that we have recovered <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m12"></span><a href="#m12" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(12)</a> with <em>A</em>=<em>V</em><sup>2</sup><sub>0</sub>.</div></li><li><span class="label title-label">(v)</span><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            "><strong>Braneworld models.</strong> Braneworld models provide an interesting alternative to dark energy model building. According to this higher-dimensional world view, we live on a (3 + 1)-dimensional brane (‘brane’ being a multidimensional generalization of ‘membrane’), which is either embedded in or bounds a higher-dimensional space–time. The simplest example of a braneworld that can lead to late-time acceleration is the model suggested by <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib18"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib18" data-open="bib18" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Deffayet et al. (2002a)</a> (henceforth we shall refer to this model as the DDG model): <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m22" content-id="m22"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq038.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq038.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=jtpdvFBvmCbrgtFTeu~3B-H6kFmokvlfTN-RfaYDZYUh3HQX1cxeK8FZhnBf5Jsa4oXXanU0wzi7z4Ev1BC9u7-JtW8-F061BZgpOA18~5yoOtq9BRQd-WyVjGhc23gLvflc9zwQ19M8u~kYm2z0JPu7micEjMFKp9K~KC4irpXtLy2Y0Mwj6UkltmaEHTVFVVAcV9mwJCYZktctOnBe1GgCZeFVfYzCWOTi69ewWEiPi7kPrdqmwHT99p-TPPNQl9r1s72btZrss1tbifqhxtuXc7Nv4UR~OlMWCDXTXOERiw6cr3j7T7QtY85nh~61jALLWyyczx80PB6l~K52qA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq038.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(22)</span></div> where <em>l</em><sub>c</sub>=<em>m</em><sup>2</sup>/<em>M</em><sup>3</sup> is a new length-scale and <em>m</em> and <em>M</em> refer, respectively, to the four- and five-dimensional Planck mass (<em>l</em><sub>c</sub>= 2<em>r</em><sub>c</sub> in the terminology of <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib18"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib18" data-open="bib18" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Deffayet et al. 2002a</a>). The acceleration of the Universe in this model is not caused by the presence of ‘dark energy’ but is due to the fact that general relativity is formulated in five dimensions instead of the usual four. One consequence of this is that gravity becomes five dimensional on length-scales <em>R</em> &gt; <em>l</em><sub>c</sub>= 2<em>H</em><sup>−1</sup><sub>0</sub>(1 −Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>)<sup>−1</sup>. A more general class of braneworld models is described by (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib42"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib42" data-open="bib42" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Shtanov 2002</a>) <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m23" content-id="m23"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq039.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq039.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=GreLpCxsZpmQ3Fa~cQkkxwTfaLoEH-k1~Zxhx1kbquKP4I8YZgg~JE-z9in~WVL3xnCJeEOzI3CdjHrERvVYTnaQoyy5GbVR0fg6R2ciLNmeuhdBhbFk0m6cbjiCRql0f0PPLjo4q36GUOgt~xCi5PTXlqzSD6TEQTUTMzmJYPZLABDm9fkI8jrVzc71oyhxVR52jOf3LJgFXl9hEYs4pqUxG0BPWuZ660uqGW6nydikrDxF~CKc1JSWZOMQcnA9EaR3yp5b-cxVPRMPblMgdn9H2TRgtAABfll~P8ezLivznLNGmVzUcly5biwTXMXI3RfTtSujILGV1nL4H5ZPAw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq039.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(23)</span></div> where Λ<sub>b</sub> is the bulk cosmological constant, σ is the brane tension and <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m24" content-id="m24"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq040.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq040.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=K~DcsQLv9v8Hl3rpAb-uZaP8bnb0LUJYxkpzKq~xsd7FbOet4tO1x8ZI3erkaWiocZweUjleMN-moWiLtEXEVF4Qov0rznmT3quuSv9CugpHpwB8QHTJA9QiVjhffU80xlmRXOPEMRNP09GLaKxepqb19t8JqSS8ZWDAU--SsOvy9CSnyp7p9nnyMjc5IRcv2nKa7JcI3KDmNrlXW2EsGSrSD0h5TNBEbWq89xfYxwxYK8kmkXj008pDtMjpZEOwxMkuArhEXf7MgQsexh-vi6cJmaIcB4DgaWMLwJzLuuLf3XTbLAYBcj0z7MJZFSjXbZEpMM9hm6Jm8oV3f649qA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq040.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(24)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">It is easy to see that <em>l</em><sub>c</sub> can be of the same order as the Hubble radius <em>l</em><sub>c</sub>∼<em>H</em><sup>−1</sup><sub>0</sub> if <em>M</em>∼ 100 MeV. On short length-scales <em>r</em>≪<em>l</em><sub>c</sub> and at early times, one recovers general relativity, whereas on large length-scales <em>r</em>≫<em>l</em><sub>c</sub> and at late times brane-related effects begin to play an important role. It is interesting that brane-inspired effects can lead to the late-time acceleration of the Universe even in the complete absence of a matter source that violates the strong energy condition ρ+ 3<em>p</em>≥ 0 (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib19"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib19" data-open="bib19" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Deffayet et al. 2002b</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib42"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib42" data-open="bib42" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Shtanov 2002</a>).</p><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The dimensionless value of the brane tension Ω<sub>σ</sub> is determined by the constraint relation <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m25" content-id="m25"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq041.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq041.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=xenTsLPf1-fi~dN8FA3QomBoHgInOrz6yzIbDT0gWLmhy07i4C1G1G4MOA7IPAxiY~TSVIQDsA8MSGyt4U6r1d0YEXCmqScwlK-0TNxGDgqZMc2SkKFXMbAVmL0LwzK3rcjenbUlX9Cmns0hHEKssIbTMSe46~y1H3wnm5jY2~DX3CM5-16~IwWf8MonxUbmyIMirOAh35iDphqr~tbAzl9kNEnjjSdaKErcO9JY732BVcUUiIvybOk7q363MgdnCeO6hLZOPBFq-WXd3SEEjU7QSzTwND96zx9FciXcQivmsJM-3jzwtmDnIRp7QDPmGnXR3K84k26feoimH~Vr4Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq041.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(25)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The underlined terms in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(23)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m25"></span><a href="#m25" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(25)</a> make braneworld models different from standard FRW cosmology. Indeed, by setting Ω<sub><em>l</em></sub>= 0, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (23)</a> reduces to the LCDM model <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m26" content-id="m26"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq042.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq042.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=oDTHUGZ2WPLSijcVAkp24JTotGgsTHa95NWf5kRjSijuCAOE~Hs87zKtM5LiT8BVJg~BhZiE7kMbo~nrTHMLzJkRJnEWkxYd3mi3Is98mC1lukc06-EL0lR2amcuMytmRJr6g-6usAJrWig6sV9MGL40B-lTToYSgDgK2pDoP2f5gjbzdkNXir8QpLPOR2HsFVryUMqK9Y~3e86~G4u-eND8G-U0b7ZakWI85AyHDcZUvmTb-kI2dMojNwf8rql8SeqC7ubnDQNGpG7YOyhJEn6ANw7X4-TreKLj0~S2NU2Lp6BZlN8RBtAj6MqSjnkakQ8Fb6yPMhjQEwkSUpbvvA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq042.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(26)</span></div> which describes a universe containing matter and a cosmological constant <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m7"></span><a href="#m7" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(7)</a>. The two signs in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(23)</a> correspond to the two separate ways in which the brane can be embedded in the higher-dimensional bulk. As shown in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib42"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib42" data-open="bib42" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Shtanov (2002)</a>, taking the upper sign in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(23)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m25"></span><a href="#m25" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(25)</a> leads to the model called BRANE1, while the lower sign in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(23)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m25"></span><a href="#m25" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(25)</a> results in BRANE2.</div><p class="chapter-para">Three important classes of braneworld models deserve special mention.</p></li></ul>                    <a id="16661650" scrollto-destination="16661650"></a>
<div data-id="fig1" data-content-id="fig1" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 1.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig001.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=IUzlvpuquFZk8NnA2RSWHCs7AMpXfr00qlTJZPWC0bmciZZi8EasIc73eNj2Kmsg1e18~veIsOi1XFl75qdv3k41HmjHe2xbaOiUJ8RepCSbxdcNua1LGzgTdguSryQicW7iGGdd6jG46kXS5ZWW14y9I4A56nP2t5XEMtmZhgzxqKuV0TFXXn56Q5v4dF5QcENezvTotY3J~tJbBTkSFuTaF8Yqdy3AVEkwvoOF5h-LN7dYLmh0K8Ptybbpmq5YDGdHixl9tAFqpBMCjq5Fq13K1GKzX1gIFECAcPGWCe9KQAbbOgQjqM4HO6zcbq2Bq6d5UFXIu1vRXbc7acE-Tw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="The left-hand panel (a) shows the time evolution of the statefinder pair {r, s} for quintessence models and the Chaplygin gas. Quintessence models lie to the right of the LCDM fixed point (r= 1, s= 0) (solid lines represent tracker potentials V=V0/φα, dot-dashed lines represent quiessence with constant equation of state w). For quiessence models, s remains constant at 1 +w, while r declines asymptotically to 1 + 9/2w(1 +w). For tracker models, s decreases monotonically to zero, whereas r first decreases from unity to a minimum value and then rises to unity. These models tend to approach the LCDM fixed point (r= 1, s= 0) from the right at t→∞. Chaplygin gas models (solid lines) lie to the left of the LCDM fixed point. For these models, κ is the ratio between matter density and the density of the Chaplygin gas at early times. For all Chaplygin gas models, s monotonically increases to zero from −1, whereas r first increases from unity to a maximum value and then decreases (to unity). The dashed curve in the lower right is the envelope of all quintessence models, while the dashed curve in the upper left is the envelope of Chaplygin gas models (the latter is described by κ=Ωm/1 −Ωm). The region outside the dashed curves is forbidden for both classes of dark energy models. The right-hand panel (b) shows the time evolution of the pair {r, q}, where q is the deceleration parameter. It is important to note that the solid line, which corresponds to the time evolution of the LCDM model, divides the r–q plane into two halves. The upper half is occupied by Chaplygin gas models, while the lower half contains quintessence models. All models diverge at the same point in the past (r= 1, q= 0.5) which corresponds to a matter-dominated universe (SCDM), and converge to the same point in the future (r= 1, q=−1) which corresponds to the steady-state model (SS) – the de Sitter expansion (LCDM → SS as t→∞ and Ωm→ 0). The dark dots on the curves show current values {r0, s0} (left) and {r0, q0} (right) for different dark energy models. In all models, Ωm= 0.3 at the current epoch. In both panels quiessence is shown as dot-dashed, while dashed lines mark envelopes for Chaplygin gas (upper) and quintessence (lower)." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig001.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661650/344-4-1057-fig001.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig001.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661650" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-fig001.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&Signature=JWCZYYnhKGdmamsTTPZXWLQt3IEwAPrN9vAf8~XXkcjTvS7xc2~-ZPtJPFFL9PWZkODy0rRibxJVwG9q6SoUEgoR-F3wRX2mVtcwcUhO4ipAv4KrAMwpF9hZD5~D2bO63ntrtMjWd8wy3b81~~cHW00FE5CjyoLxZXci4AFGQvdRtny~uzehmbxhHqRpwTI7JIWf~VKTTyv8yqYuvbsVLfMugcoI3bvPnsfnbFtq67ELnxF0~PnJxe83cuvEp6DK1HV6lxEEMkCKt8a8AQ1pHldtA5pTIJmbYkKWohwgwVb2M-Ic~pGf5GXWfNNdiALkB5X7JaW5xgHkQnEXTh9iCA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661650&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig001.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">The left-hand panel (a) shows the time evolution of the statefinder pair {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>} for quintessence models and the Chaplygin gas. Quintessence models lie to the right of the LCDM fixed point (<em>r</em>= 1, <em>s</em>= 0) (solid lines represent tracker potentials <em>V</em>=<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>α</sup>, dot-dashed lines represent quiessence with constant equation of state <em>w</em>). For quiessence models, <em>s</em> remains constant at 1 +<em>w</em>, while <em>r</em> declines asymptotically to 1 + 9/2<em>w</em>(1 +<em>w</em>). For tracker models, <em>s</em> decreases monotonically to zero, whereas <em>r</em> first decreases from unity to a minimum value and then rises to unity. These models tend to approach the LCDM fixed point (<em>r</em>= 1, <em>s</em>= 0) from the right at <em>t</em>→∞. Chaplygin gas models (solid lines) lie to the left of the LCDM fixed point. For these models, κ is the ratio between matter density and the density of the Chaplygin gas at early times. For all Chaplygin gas models, <em>s</em> monotonically increases to zero from −1, whereas <em>r</em> first increases from unity to a maximum value and then decreases (to unity). The dashed curve in the lower right is the envelope of all quintessence models, while the dashed curve in the upper left is the envelope of Chaplygin gas models (the latter is described by κ=Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>/1 −Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>). The region outside the dashed curves is forbidden for both classes of dark energy models. The right-hand panel (b) shows the time evolution of the pair {<em>r</em>, <em>q</em>}, where <em>q</em> is the deceleration parameter. It is important to note that the solid line, which corresponds to the time evolution of the LCDM model, divides the <em>r</em>–<em>q</em> plane into two halves. The upper half is occupied by Chaplygin gas models, while the lower half contains quintessence models. All models diverge at the same point in the past (<em>r</em>= 1, <em>q</em>= 0.5) which corresponds to a matter-dominated universe (SCDM), and converge to the same point in the future (<em>r</em>= 1, <em>q</em>=−1) which corresponds to the steady-state model (SS) – the de Sitter expansion (LCDM → SS as <em>t</em>→∞ and Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>→ 0). The dark dots on the curves show current values {<em>r</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>s</em><sub>0</sub>} (left) and {<em>r</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>} (right) for different dark energy models. In all models, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 at the current epoch. In both panels quiessence is shown as dot-dashed, while dashed lines mark envelopes for Chaplygin gas (upper) and quintessence (lower).</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para"></p><ul class="list-simple"><li><span class="label title-label">(i)</span><p class="chapter-para">BRANE1 models have an effective equation of state that is <em>more negative</em> than that of the cosmological constant <em>w</em>≤−1.</p></li><li><span class="label title-label">(ii)</span><p class="chapter-para">BRANE2 models have <em>w</em>≥−1. For parameter values Ω<sub>σ</sub>=Ω, BRANE2 coincides with the dark energy model discussed in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m22"></span><a href="#m22" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (22)</a>.</p></li><li><span class="label title-label">(iii)</span><p class="chapter-para">A class of braneworld models, called ‘disappearing dark energy’ (DDE) (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib42"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib42" data-open="bib42" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Shtanov 2002</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib1"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib1" data-open="bib1" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Alam &amp; Sahni 2002</a>), have the important property that the current acceleration of the Universe is a <em>transient phase</em>, that is sandwiched between two matter-dominated epochs. These models do not have horizons and therefore help to reconcile an accelerating Universe with the demands of the string/M-theory (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib42"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib42" data-open="bib42" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni 2002</a>) (as well as any theory that requires dark energy to decay in the future and transform into matter with <em>w</em>≥−1/3).</p></li></ul><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">Finally, we note that, for a spatially flat universe, the luminosity distance for all models discussed above is given by the simple expression <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m27" content-id="m27"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq043.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq043.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=UmQPkhrIX8Br6fgWknnHwqdlVedTiGUU34aWfeeu3F8X6pCGeJscmHAZDAsJI0UISto-15TRBvbKeFFzbVIMP8-DR3AD9vuybsmOYj6Mk~tJwxv4e5nMZyMoUkyGzMTC6A9lrzZ3TxJBTTO2zJ1buTviQ1jA3cCVJZo0emdV7MWDtugT81H8mwVDYtbrhYZ8ZYoMWKhUD3DnYZ2zJkESI4cmQ5iQBGq9tWcATmh2UVzGZQcAYT-KqqG0OJam2AKYcor7Qa5vJWhrsTx0mivA8zM~nkVxbVHGpCoJv8~z3zBDrK6VncW-KZuUeAVPnz~GI33LiQcFLTVHN-gx-QSCzA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq043.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(27)</span></div> where <em>H</em>(<em>z</em>) is given by <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m7"></span><a href="#m7" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(7)</a> for LCDM, by <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m8"></span><a href="#m8" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(8)</a> for quiessence, by <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m11"></span><a href="#m11" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(11)</a> for quintessence, by <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m14"></span><a href="#m14" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(14)</a> for the Chaplygin gas and by <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(23)</a> for the braneworld models.</div>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=16661654 id="16661654" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss3>3 The Statefinder Diagnostic</h2>
<div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">As we have seen above, dark energy has properties that can be <em>very</em> model dependent. In order to be able to differentiate between the very distinct and competing cosmological scenarios involving dark energy, a sensitive and robust diagnostic (of dark energy) is a must. Although the rate of acceleration/deceleration of the Universe can be described by the single parameter <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq044.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=RYgaLzG0hZ1MHLZ~cOZu54~zusafG8HB342QyDfOM~bnuXFgMDfoD0DGdXOiL~Ti0tqiLvbq3Y4LjupVewgA~eM0wNX~XpYqChs~pAVVhXukCjjCX-ld8yEylHY7CrT3inT2915yRCy~-YHA8QHLddWEdNxchsn01-6ZYQV4JWmM9CGd~X~SIglJGrnrSL39n21kdZFRCzm7nIfYjdUafZToUae-KIQ83Am6w4Z~D39EAFUpvzLbmXRHfwmLje0sz~PF3Op~KPFXT1sqAUjTMb0WUAl9OIvOOp13oydEWaMF1zfwO0GW4BO9aXRtfH~zlDwcSAYAnWZvZ~bA~uro8w__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq044.jpeg" />, a more sensitive discriminator of the expansion rate and hence dark energy can be constructed by considering the general form for the expansion factor of the Universe <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m28" content-id="m28"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq045.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq045.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=0pn3wjuz~mHBcfbmB7Cn7MU4CGw9bqv2i92XqxbX9SLj4NPTpR1aU~u28z7o4Lnj5j9c0TGZEm3u9hGS5c8QTnB2Lvftl-HabJ-EmOOuxeUoP0RozDwlQBwGiYDT7MlJGEm35cMfP1fLOQFiRgI8vJ5J4~BpRlHxp7uBrfbB0lnj9ByDNBA8SQNxuXVZlgkQJ9u~S4~o9Sk0fF7ePO0S6K8khBmSDWbtYc-xg-Fzv47qGqdMz3hQVhEni9-hs4yMLK0Cr5lICp6-MoiR7NhvGnGzKkT-rJ7PTkbsMymfIRK6DYJSAR4EtfNhWUMkW7IrxDgW06r7R2YAgynNdOYTCA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq045.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(28)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">In general, dark energy models such as quiessence, quintessence, <em>k</em>-essence, braneworld models, Chaplygin gas, etc. give rise to families of curves <em>a</em>(<em>t</em>) having vastly different properties. Since we know that the acceleration of the Universe is a fairly recent phenomenon (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib45"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib45" data-open="bib45" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni &amp; Starobinsky 2000</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib40"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib40" data-open="bib40" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Riess et al. 2001</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib7"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib7" data-open="bib7" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Benitez et al. 2002</a>) we can, in principle, confine our attention to small values of |<em>t</em>−<em>t</em><sub>0</sub>| in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m28"></span><a href="#m28" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(28)</a>. We have shown in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib46"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib46" data-open="bib46" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni et al. (2003)</a> that a new diagnostic of dark energy called statefinder can be constructed using both the second and third derivatives of the expansion factor. The second derivative is encoded in the deceleration parameter, which has the following form in a spatially flat universe: <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m29" content-id="m29"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq046.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq046.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=1O9g7RF3nvXkduyr5gNMWDqWz8kW8fmTgdixn-rV3TxPETjWILkcpbankVtKXkJiUDVusEh2o95iiVqxOsor2ZcOQdsKdrw1nTebL5XCJvGyHYdoD4p1gC7RGwibDwAqE9sBcbhxi6fQjtCbUiCaOw63RBfOJ0i-GGjypNXMCQnO37AIwNLep1TAYQfmt5M251CTYiyIHFIm1tTi-184b4ZI-kbPnWlE5QpNndMUbs6REFb8T25wZMfS~U~eIGTalN06KVpjI1~GdZ2O6DY0ftSHcsVWBPJfIxqmPGJ43FDW2O62cF8v3ESBcAZSMQ-W-HlcIDqYN2VxHSj2EXSwyw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq046.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(29)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The statefinder pair {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>}, defines two new cosmological parameters (in addition to <em>H</em> and <em>q</em>): <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m30" content-id="m30"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq047.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq047.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=isP3r5XufTmw-tVYkMnYwyxFF6U-3qxYCVdaRonOYDTMsEwFvepig1HTwBgMkHOH40MtjS2Ue0fJSN4ued55AXyrC4nYY2qItLJTeQgrEUap47uoZBEpKXkrkXe8v0fFW9razcJ5uSWpkNQ6FG-zoe31Gp4RfGNrln2f-UaKf8h8ynOlsIu4Sza9UsRu9pt8jh2ezkqClt-mvfTBP3DJjLXRfEi6IUjnYDOpTuf1cV44aGgp~0oMV4KU3sv7zeWvbji5B2yW5LT-SbEadpigAaoDPHn4erPy5~OjGMdkkmLYSQKx-4B1CX8aVogXX6uSJBWO6W6CI6XI2SMwJOp~2Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq047.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(30)</span></div><div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m31" content-id="m31"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq048.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq048.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=pvWCXGaEAmPNzS-wtoGGXWNXbcylPXPn5xXBvKPtbPn0jpQMrN8mkm4lBe3NcYvyfwnw7yPZ7x~aIHDF7xW82A5ghciTJAJOGiQdgl5KtvCJDh2cCFuHM51mnKhAYVfkf8HA2T3QfzG1vg0D9xpzOjYViYXXxNRqipBUeKJYiU3T-aqcztJ~lqHgq33XHfD5tVe6gkOWNcXHQZmzGKsKjJc0P2oHydw1PhjmB1QP0q6vVT-nfRUjHtuHehjM16hFJFBHqIT3eCxGiG9aenoE-2B54uI4jDBB7NBmH4gQoFLINwvrOGXjzNI8dOmRswEtrGZWQTystzIqusJM2wZlfg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq048.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(31)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">Clearly, an important requirement of any diagnostic is that it permits us to differentiate between a given dark energy model and the simplest of all models — the cosmological constant Λ. The statefinder does exactly this. For the LCDM model, the value of the first statefinder stays pegged at <em>r</em>= 1 even as the matter density evolves from a large initial value (Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>≃ 1, <em>t</em>≪<em>t</em><sub>0</sub>) to a small late-time value (Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>→ 0, <em>t</em>≫<em>t</em><sub>0</sub>). It is easy to show that {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>}={1, 0} is a fixed point for LCDM.</p><p class="chapter-para">The second statefinder <em>s</em> has properties that complement those of the first. Since <em>s</em> does not explicitly depend upon either Ω<sub><em>X</em></sub> or Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>, many of the degeneracies that are present in <em>r</em> are broken in the combined statefinder pair {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>}. For models with a constant equation of state (quiessence) <em>s</em>= 1 +<em>w</em>= constant, while the statefinder <em>r</em> is time-varying. For models with a time-dependent equation of state (kinessence), both <em>r</em> and <em>s</em> vary with time. As we will show in this paper, the statefinder pair {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>} can easily distinguish between LCDM, quiessence and kinessence models. It can also distinguish between more elaborate models of dark energy such as braneworld models and the Chaplygin gas (see also <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib25"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib25" data-open="bib25" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Gorini et al. 2003</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib46"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib46" data-open="bib46" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni et al. 2003</a>). Interestingly, as demonstrated in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss5"></span><a href="#ss5" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 5</a>, the statefinder pair {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} proves to be an even better diagnostic of dark energy than {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>}.</p><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The statefinders <em>r</em> and <em>s</em> can be easily expressed in terms of the Hubble parameter <em>H</em>(<em>z</em>) and its derivatives as follows: <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m32" content-id="m32"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq049.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq049.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=EB7v3~LNXy0sT7TWFWgoi0DLpcTKjDMI~OTHWC~W-nGW-m9cULBev0R9LeDmccAReBIusDmz~8-Bz1e7qvg~n39hFB98ZtXzDyfe9zwy6WZjAlndYt9j9p0vLagT992k-G5Fxe3eDgJIwppu6bwH9wQceotHZYG1BW~c8F37guIi471N4WETmajTbD7s~N4ec~np6fMyZ2CjsZeNrZpKviRz8FLWOmWvUYLDt-FXoA08D6Hi-ZqpED1LqIsP0cQY1j7FPeAWUiOpgNl1r-vDVR21z7c929tYRAb6V3mUPMH2VU7PGYmxCBIt06Gu6XAu~hPUyplWCfKddougy9T96Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq049.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(32)</span></div> where <em>x</em>= 1 +<em>z</em> and <em>H</em> is given by <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m7"></span><a href="#m7" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(7)</a>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m8"></span><a href="#m8" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(8)</a>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m11"></span><a href="#m11" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(11)</a>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m14"></span><a href="#m14" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(14)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(23)</a> for the different dark energy models discussed in the previous section.</div><p class="chapter-para">In <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig1"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig1" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 1(a)</a> we show the time evolution of the statefinder pair {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>}. We find that the vertical line at <em>s</em>= 0 effectively divides the <em>r</em>–<em>s</em> plane into two halves. The left half contains Chaplygin gas (CG) models that commence their evolution from <em>r</em>= 1, <em>s</em>=−1 and end it at the LCDM fixed point (<em>r</em>= 1, <em>s</em>= 0) in the future. The quintessence models occupy the right half of the <em>r</em>–<em>s</em> plane. These models commence their evolution from the right of the LCDM fixed point and, such as CG, are also attracted towards the LCDM fixed point in the future. For quiessence models, <em>r</em> decreases monotonically to 1 + 9/2<em>w</em>(1 +<em>w</em>), while <em>s</em> remains constant at <em>s</em>= 1 +<em>w</em>. For kinessence models, on the other hand, <em>s</em> decreases monotonically to zero, while <em>r</em> first decreases to a minimum value and then increases to unity. The region below the envelope curve <em>r</em>= 1 + 9/2<em>s</em>(<em>s</em>− 1) is disallowed for quintessence models, whereas CG models with κ &lt; Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>/(1 −Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>) are excluded. It is interesting that the second statefinder, <em>s</em>, is positive for quintessence models, but negative for the CG. Similarly, the first statefinder, <em>r</em>, is &lt;1 (&gt;1) for quintessence (CG). The distinctive trajectories which quiessence, quintessence and CG follow in the <em>r</em>–<em>s</em> plane demonstrates quite strikingly the contrasting behaviour of dark energy models.</p><p class="chapter-para">The separation between distinct families of dark energy models is also very pronounced when we analyse evolutionary trajectories using the statefinder pair {<em>r</em>, <em>q</em>} shown in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig1"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig1" class="link xref-fig">Figs 1(b)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig2"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig2" class="link xref-fig">2</a>. <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig1"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig1" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 1(b)</a> shows the evolution of quintessence and CG models in <em>r</em>–<em>q</em> space, while <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig2"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig2" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 2</a> shows the evolution of the braneworld models discussed in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(23)</a>. In <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig1"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig1" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 1(b)</a> the LCDM model effectively divides the <em>r</em>–<em>q</em> space in half, separating quintessence models (bottom-half) from the Chaplygin gas (top-half). From this figure we clearly see that all dark energy models commence evolving from the same point in the past (<em>q</em>= 0.5, <em>r</em>= 1), which corresponds to a matter-dominated SCDM universe. Quintessence, LCDM and the Chaplygin gas all end their evolution at the same common point in the future (<em>q</em>=−1, <em>r</em>= 1), which corresponds to a steady-state cosmology (SS) – the de Sitter expansion. In <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig2"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig2" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 2</a> the LCDM model separates BRANE1 models (which have <em>w</em><sub>eff</sub>≤−1) from BRANE2 models as well as DDE models. BRANE2 models have <em>w</em><sub>eff</sub>≥−1 generically, whereas DDE models consist of a transient accelerating regime which is sandwiched between two matter-dominated epochs. Thus, DDE both begins and ends its evolution at the SCDM point {<em>r</em>, <em>q</em>}={1, 0.5} and its <em>r</em>–<em>q</em> space trajectory is a loop! BRANE1 and BRANE2 models, on the other hand, commence evolving at the SCDM point and tend to SS in the future. <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig1"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig1" class="link xref-fig">Figs 1(b)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig2"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig2" class="link xref-fig">2</a> clearly demonstrate that the deceleration parameter cannot on its own differentiate between rival models of dark energy. The degeneracy that afflicts <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) clearly also afflicts the equation of state <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>), since both <em>q</em> and <em>w</em> are related through <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m6"></span><a href="#m6" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(6)</a>. We therefore feel we have convincingly demonstrated that the statefinders can successfully differentiate between competing dark energy models as diverse as LCDM, quintessence, braneworld models and the Chaplygin gas. Statefinders can also be applied to other interesting candidates for dark energy including bigravity models (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib17"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib17" data-open="bib17" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Damour, Kogan &amp; Papazoglou 2002</a>), generalized Chaplygin gas (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib28"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib28" data-open="bib28" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Kamenshchik et al. 2001</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib8"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib8" data-open="bib8" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Bento, Bertolami &amp; Sen 2002</a>), <em>k</em>-essence (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib4"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib4" data-open="bib4" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Armendariz-Picon et al. 2000</a>) scalar–tensor theories, etc.</p>                    <a id="16661663" scrollto-destination="16661663"></a>
<div data-id="fig2" data-content-id="fig2" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 2.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig002.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=vx9D58bROaTG~rKj~haLQb7UYFG27QhDxV7L1P2bHI6e-ptw9zNYJudumi~WPLk8lMhpBSUzJB6qIkOLdLXyYMZKMpq~ngHBibmHCGBccuaSa28mmp~8tqG2c5yVf85mvG8287oMzUWOJ2Me263pFePqysugEEVX7AqNgCn5tFYvrcoqw3yLNjcrSB0-YUIm3H08GZE~L56tRYU0RTFzQyqkZO8bLsAYwHZFY6jQj46m15oizKHeONTW4klyDdxMuPeWKEGhVR6GLNm1OtFKqr6jtznw8tvSvmzWDPfRcP6dVSMLjwsYwo3PIoAXCLV69I16qYpSDJuB6rSrj0zxQA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Trajectories in the statefinder plane {r, q} for the braneworld models discussed in (23). BRANE1 models have w≤−1 generically, whereas BRANE2 models have w≥−1. The closed loop represents DDE in which the acceleration of the Universe is a transient phenomenon. For braneworld models, parameter values are as follows. BRANE1: solid curves above LCDM; top to bottom: Ωm= 0.6, Ωl= 6.0, Ωm= 0.5, Ωl= 2.0, Ωm= 0.4, Ωl= 0.5. BRANE2: solid curves below LCDM; top to bottom: Ωm= 0.3, Ωl= 0.05, Ωm= 0.2, Ωl= 0.25, Ωm= 0.1, Ωl= 0.45. The thick solid curve in BRANE2 corresponds to the DDG model discussed in (22) with Ωm= 0.24. For BRANE1 and BRANE2 models Ω= 0 (i.e. there is no cosmological constant in the bulk). Dark dots indicate the current value of {r, q} for the models. All models are in reasonable agreement with current supernova data. For DDE, from outer to inner loops, Ωm= 0.05, Ω= 4.9, Ωm= 0.15, Ω= 1.4, Ωm= 0.20, Ω= 1.1." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig002.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661663/344-4-1057-fig002.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig002.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661663" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-fig002.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&Signature=DldXlcyWnLKKnGSSKaBgwRRfkinZjlUk6RXbL~iAw-cxaFtK3141sNU8xtSOvpYpD3X11k3ThEXLktVMKshU6qM6aI3pwQ~frfzjCHdFCV3PbA6k9vGIhgkswkc2Aw417OlJxkoteWlCZlNFvHa-2gJ79Dtvq4rS9UIrZYYJW3D-SeEGml~CSDRevNGLYT433Gxd0PKho2kkSra20ZkOs20DfUzbUHqAjjwK7GkyjgwNfjMIRlYuZDVzVyqAk8DmkUi-j2rAwfpIauPPuK1-Vf~RPMeRsEsdc52efes9pxtHvfYWk3vmHP4p3CsfU0eFafjeGv0R6GXJIKMUnXzVgg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661663&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig002.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">Trajectories in the statefinder plane {<em>r</em>, <em>q</em>} for the braneworld models discussed in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m23"></span><a href="#m23" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(23)</a>. BRANE1 models have <em>w</em>≤−1 generically, whereas BRANE2 models have <em>w</em>≥−1. The closed loop represents DDE in which the acceleration of the Universe is a transient phenomenon. For braneworld models, parameter values are as follows. BRANE1: solid curves above LCDM; top to bottom: Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.6, Ω<sub><em>l</em></sub>= 6.0, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.5, Ω<sub><em>l</em></sub>= 2.0, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.4, Ω<sub><em>l</em></sub>= 0.5. BRANE2: solid curves below LCDM; top to bottom: Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3, Ω<sub><em>l</em></sub>= 0.05, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.2, Ω<sub><em>l</em></sub>= 0.25, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.1, Ω<sub><em>l</em></sub>= 0.45. The thick solid curve in BRANE2 corresponds to the DDG model discussed in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m22"></span><a href="#m22" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(22)</a> with Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.24. For BRANE1 and BRANE2 models Ω= 0 (i.e. there is no cosmological constant in the bulk). Dark dots indicate the current value of {<em>r</em>, <em>q</em>} for the models. All models are in reasonable agreement with current supernova data. For DDE, from outer to inner loops, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.05, Ω= 4.9, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.15, Ω= 1.4, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.20, Ω= 1.1.</p></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">Finally, we draw the readers attention to the following elegant relationship that exists between the statefinders, on the one hand, and the total density <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq050.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=i3wrmWHOw1nZ0ED7xqTm93XgvK48QbAhAdZVxaXwOuaORaf6YPt0bx9knbfsKOWv67v9p4YEfbuc2GLleX5jnUUtbfoankmlPkCWWvnuYajgFK6iR2dRJFKYGWT0VOV5CNlwwmRrUkEx281ShOGh9rIeruqE7AIWyRppt-TkTGbfX6HELyKZb6ehVkf6l2WDdskBDqqShsnYP2NjYH1UGUjKW~xBefhzU8j9CDZhXatsveAuwvdMOMe6ZdQS~GqNadkAwDAHxdSlt2DeNNA1KIdbMYnoFXaGFI1uhOHAYHEQGIhT8EGjD8JsCHXBwHNwm~L3k1WmUXWUdTO~xMdr7g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq050.jpeg" /> and total pressure <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq051.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=BDdPVvjBNyW1fDI5XH15BCL7UBk62iYdu~prJYtM9CiRYCA7U18zg7wZ8a~eRfIEAxyopzeIqGRIxxWxY3aullHVqeqYVaAKApzPu9yY4JRizxnzhg-84AAG7HInYp7~Gb1FQ2GGPIzwzxrY4BJtFKn5qi34vV0vjlZcKXY2spo~58QkICKJ-QbzcXpW9iDbdnXE5fEbPKkLB1WxayAgFbSOHifJGUQClS3e9AUUk5FBhLmVmqX49FhB~t~5J~tloEkGiseaOEHXdQaKNVitYiI7cyeWf1QC~SuVnh-fqZpnVflco-55CCeGcUKAxAMr~pduiak8Oau6NwEPGeL8Ew__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq051.jpeg" /> in the Universe: <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m33" content-id="m33"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq052.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq052.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=ixOued8swjDZzfd~DVm88PLl-pM5C2EOAVJTcw5PmiWQnIvJp-a5~e4pL1mXlwKiDjsE9y9R8w--2v7Hy21k4mgpPkOURp7uUbxSNIF~QXVzSX2p~bIKU2anL30n9kH6KW1OeBZOf5IZUBMICfoWSHZ4PtiWPvUKJsL1gtdzQhZGXY1Po6PGnRUhJa51hjyc-Q4AtSi5i7sKqCntODj6~SdLxItFjbN49vPCmiQZRLgOX9T9KLI72GlCMvjepISRYkEZ-fLok6EwmnOUcd44x7gX7U7AUaDEnlwIMmlalvPOEfcCJ3-zuCNh00GrWlJ4Hb8MGeNju-MxwtRWo52tJQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq052.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(33)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">From <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m33"></span><a href="#m33" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (33)</a> we see that the statefinder <em>s</em> is exceedingly sensitive to the total pressure <em>p</em>. This has some interesting consequences. At early times the presence of radiation ensures that the total pressure in the Universe is positive. Much later, the Universe begins to accelerate driven by the negative pressure of dark energy. In between these two asymptotic regimes, deep in the matter-dominated epoch, a stage is reached when the (negative) pressure of dark energy is exactly balanced by the positive pressure of radiation. At this precise moment of time <em>p</em>≃ 0 and <em>s</em>→∞! For LCDM this pressure balance is achieved at <em>z</em><sub>*</sub>∼ 10, consequently |<em>s</em>|≫ 1 when <em>z</em>∼<em>z</em><sub>*</sub>. It can be shown that the redshift <em>z</em><sub>*</sub> (at which <em>p</em>= 0) is quite sensitive to the form of dark energy. We therefore find that the statefinder <em>s</em> diagnoses the presence of dark energy even at high redshifts when the contribution of DE to the total energy budget of the Universe is insignificant!</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=16661667 id="16661667" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss4>Model-Independent Reconstruction of Cosmological Parameters from <em>Snap</em> Data</h2>
                    <h3 scrollto-destination=16661668 id="16661668" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss4-1>4.1 The cosmological reconstruction of dark energy properties</h3>
<p class="chapter-para">Cosmological reconstruction is an effective statistical technique, which can be used in situations where a large number of theoretical models are to be compared with observations. Instead of estimating relevant parameters for each model separately, we can choose a model-independent fitting function and perform a maximum-likelihood parameter estimation for it. The resultant confidence levels can be used to rule out or accept the different models available. This technique is effective here because, as discussed in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss2"></span><a href="#ss2" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 2</a>, a wide range of theoretical models have been suggested to explain dark energy.</p><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The basis of cosmological reconstruction rests on the observation that the expression for the luminosity distance <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m27"></span><a href="#m27" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(27)</a> can be easily inverted (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib49"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib49" data-open="bib49" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Starobinsky 1998</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib27"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib27" data-open="bib27" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Huterer &amp; Turner 1999</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib33"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib33" data-open="bib33" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Nakamura &amp; Chiba 1999</a>): <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m34" content-id="m34"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq053.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq053.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=AcR70-HeeQBPBhGQjLigG58Zbc0YaauZ4yil-X3NXLUluJJmxYOUkMLcAyXmBjoylyJMHmRIE-ja9hdvB-3Mjg~gls6H-yzFWK1zDPjt158dGjNbTp1SwGUzqyeayE1w3bCKNYOvWys9HK3m743MV7P5FdwNIYXNT0ZmfIt8GUHtIliyGw0voWJOBN3b0treHE8AWGyMe-hXo~6oYxfrCvXDMkLZk9vBRIfSRzM6rJWWM0bhDO5tn6s5cTc4KrGlYSY45eB-iy-xM4eQxVKJyxiXe4ELVUBOO~PV3O9KlXAp1nnnz4XlZO93uG9YMBKO9Zc4xJ2Sy5QApfxVVVzxrQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq053.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(34)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">Thus, from a mathematical point of view, any given <em>D<sub>L</sub></em>(<em>z</em>) defines <em>H</em>(<em>z</em>). <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m5"></span><a href="#m5" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Equations (5)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m6"></span><a href="#m6" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(6)</a> can then be used to obtain the dark energy density and the associated equation of state. Similarly, the statefinder pair {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>} can be determined by employing <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m32"></span><a href="#m32" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (32)</a> together with <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m29"></span><a href="#m29" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (29)</a>. However, in practice the derivative with respect to <em>z</em> may not be simply performed since <em>D<sub>L</sub></em>(<em>z</em>) is noisy due to observational errors (mainly, due to variance in supernovae luminosity). Therefore, the <em>smoothing</em> of data over some interval Δ<em>z</em> is required (Δ<em>z</em> may depend on <em>z</em>). The value of Δ<em>z</em> is determined by estimated errors and by the required accuracy with which we want to determine <em>H</em>(<em>z</em>). Of course, the resulting <em>H</em>(<em>z</em>) will be smoothed, too, as compared with the genuine one. Note that our presentation here is very similar to that in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib50"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib50" data-open="bib50" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Tegmark (2002)</a>.</p><p class="chapter-para">Instead of actually dividing a measured range of <em>z</em> into intervals, one may <em>parametrize</em><em>H</em>(<em>z</em>) by some fitting curve that depends on a number of free parameters. This leads to model-independent parametric reconstruction of <em>H</em>(<em>z</em>), ρ<sub>DE</sub>(<em>z</em>), <em>w</em><sub>eff</sub>(<em>z</em>) and other quantities. It is clear that the number of free parameters <em>N</em> in such a fit just defines the equivalent smoothing interval Δ<em>z</em> (in particular, Δ<em>z</em>=<em>z</em><sub>max</sub>/<em>N</em> if Δ<em>z</em> is chosen to be independent of <em>z</em> and we are considering the function <em>H</em>(<em>z</em>)/<em>H</em><sub>0</sub>, so that its value at <em>z</em>= 0 is known exactly). Thus, the parametrization is equivalent to some kind of smoothing, with the actual method of smoothing (weighting) depending on the functional form of the parametric fit used. This refers even to such sophisticated methods as the ‘principal-component’ approach used in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib26"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib26" data-open="bib26" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Huterer &amp; Starkman (2003)</a>. Since decreasing Δ<em>z</em> (increasing <em>N</em>) results in a rapid growth of errors [Δ<em>H</em>(<em>z</em>) ∝ (δ<em>z</em>)<sup>−3/2</sup> directly follows from <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m34"></span><a href="#m34" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (34)</a>, cf. <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib50"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib50" data-open="bib50" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Tegmark 2002</a>], for a given <em>z</em><sub>max</sub> there is no sense in taking <em>N</em> to be large — this will merely result in a loss of accuracy of our reconstruction. Thus, we will consider only three-parameter fits for <em>H</em>(<em>z</em>) [these will correspond to two-parameter fits for <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>)].</p><p class="chapter-para">After the discovery that the Universe is accelerating, many different fitting function approaches were suggested and some are summarized below.</p><p class="chapter-para"></p><ul class="list-simple"><li><span class="label title-label">(i)</span><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            "><strong>Polynomial fit to dark energy.</strong> In this paper, we reconstruct dark energy using a very effective Ansatz introduced in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib46"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib46" data-open="bib46" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni et al. (2003)</a> in which the dark energy density is expressed as a truncated Taylor series polynomial in <em>x</em>= 1 +<em>z</em>, ρ<sub>DE</sub>=<em>A</em><sub>1</sub>+<em>A</em><sub>2</sub><em>x</em>+<em>A</em><sub>3</sub><em>x</em><sup>2</sup>. This leads to the following Ansatz for the Hubble parameter: <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m35" content-id="m35"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq054.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq054.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=w4mprlYI5tSIVZcaZVbzT9YcQhhT3ptJ4YQtGClf-s1JF7xLIgSUvGNk6g4NVXXffwZkmLFmBo832NnpsWDLYDrZ9DYR8RgsKK5ky5Wzd6LyAOerJVO5rqHl2uyOQBNmo6ibDlHP19y3aUiXFXETS85~zQJZNqyp86MbBdwBNmG-bpla0yKAM7EcSzY6aEA3ISLdvbsX~fpR2WBCSg3Fflq-gKrt9GY-zBJzes6len3gcFUJblszFVMTolyGFRYaxeWEXUwu-4uiPavJz9ZbXnMzAON8g0R7w7ddohk-9kDFppCinTYbx7DiIR7qSloBrFcXhXMJQ1ZAx0KtRubQPA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq054.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(35)</span></div> which, when substituted in the expression for the luminosity distance <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m27"></span><a href="#m27" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(27)</a>, yields <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m36" content-id="m36"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq055.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq055.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=edKbwNv6KYbKp9vntZZnWTmsQNJvpYYMN485OyI4166Q4jz74kMR5IOdp4YIq-OjnkrTFeyyckWsfv7xm7H0BkYSRutZwpqO35zBTYZ1rwV0savzuNNssXuGkfWDi~i3uwTqqAWstroYnTR79Wg65ornkOdqeaX1Q3QCF3CExPbRzcM0qSq~ROiCCV~OeG7nmQxKZntskDbjiLoW78MrD6oSWKxf-4~mXWMjEjVi~1~UOI0gLYvL~7isgGNCqN0kBnLDLlahatYMMJZudy3kFndXmhQ~dPL~kw7q0d8zk2MGoIS~K4Zg9QyiDMN~mevg8XVB5u0AMbINwpwU6G1DnA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq055.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(36)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">The values of the parameters <em>A</em><sub>1</sub>, <em>A</em><sub>2</sub>, <em>A</em><sub>3</sub> are obtained by fitting <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m36"></span><a href="#m36" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(36)</a> to supernova observations by means of a maximum-likelihood analysis discussed in the next section. There are obvious advantages in choosing the Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> namely, it is exact for the cosmological constant <em>w</em>=−1 (<em>A</em><sub>2</sub>=<em>A</em><sub>3</sub>= 0) as well as for quiessence with <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq056.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=hMGiF9MKIJ8H0C1GzkhswQP73NHuM2spObt5S~qPJiE8HOjOwy6v2Zt9uBF~S7N1LjC-gv4ZV4Z~sI-TnSvNkQDaWV-aMIbZgYrBL5w~4u8Aq~LCiJiDX5dvwtS3hMwz-0i8tR5qJ~DejwHfwj7YQ9WaSHxuNYLT3PZ36IOh7VSfww7QPVuq-uLXp4gxwSUOQAwbCG7jn7nPMWykNE5uuiPI2ChBtGkZ8BrCB9Y7j6cAk4mZzn8C1kI5EsGOiaeDPCvSc31fqY~SskBblMliOgGhq99Rff0P6RUsSCZpKdq~3-yNMrhOrctFrds5i2XHaVCjVFu3~huCX5MUfctQUA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq056.jpeg" /> and <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq057.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=aYMOkIYEmwyVgH0D66-QHKhQvLIf0Wg8zu2FYEDnHDnsJ7bUtEQxuIrUPor4IxuvYsUBnT8RQTEL5uKp0v0aHWJwbyZ10A1PGHaP5FvoqjkQXG0LqWeh6OwqdX6hViRVJvPAjDfTFgJcV138IN8i91jc7k2BJzVVl7Y13tqYGFPuT7QI4s-YyUaYCTVECnEpkfgytlor2UJAn5WX1UfYxxfUfkVbowEnz2hk8Ah-X29g0Kpo38WCJHBS7jtFu6l2NN4JgKZWdg5uH1yZkAJs5NSOC1ZJA5kgB3Bqf~fBI7wDRnh4~Idh174fM3dLB1ghg70GQ~nZQ2gwhR3ij7YfLg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq057.jpeg" />. Furthermore, the presence of the term Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub><em>x</em><sup>3</sup> in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> ensures that the Ansatz correctly reproduces the matter-dominated epoch at early times (<em>z</em>≫ 1). The presence of this term also allows us to incorporate information pertaining to the value of the matter density and, as we shall soon demonstrate, permits elaborate statistical analysis with the introduction of priors on Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>.</p><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The statefinder pair for the polynomial fit <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> can be written in terms of <em>x</em>= 1 +<em>z</em> as follows: <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m37" content-id="m37"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq058.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq058.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=FzUrATzfBP-~77Hkbm766amTYkCI5hrWZ6hWcG3ysg~CDmkFdAhHKm-fA9iBCu429DR3hHMfCCktJeFwFj-MniPX4tKaYpx8ljxpyr-whwHfIKA3zBAVV94bUUGCWdE64ONik32CCKr1fduP3POzCnHmgti9fnnUYZvXYfBDej~iYfe5oIDZis8UleRoLG13oaoJ3aeVMRzkdFjiMZIC0WikycSmDqdjMZCaH8rDnowpxdf3Ru5K-QdLzwmYpnKUjS6eY2qwaMTgKqEpWVwSD5fmeek1kX6RYbv1C7c2V57eoAM9s-vBZJ7E9TrS4n99YmkwlZmexc5Tvjxbf44xvQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq058.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(37)</span></div><div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m38" content-id="m38"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq059.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq059.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=FJfjnAJM6i0n-r1z740c6au1CnzDHoUHjr1efnA1bORs~YsE~9-t2CwX0OgqnAxQvNzNjaVq7gHNVvbgxyo3lLeqnQV~Y0Nij-69vSAVImKJ8D1KIHKnj9wOyQDNue1ybU8qfIvKNKtg~WuYeHE2jNw~2xHvOHXh1T6z-QSNO7hMRhi3iwNCWZcWPMifm9CD5CpzeXu7Uz1CO1m7RHPsSlgMe7vpXcbnPQnU5REl5dTlg0ohrrr58mlOpydfCLwsn6nfzWBMzHFha-3dhLnScU0ZdoOrFHorA-6P9qsaLOwbk9RquT25VEm656BGBoErGHUFYEoce9vwF6QnVeg9Fw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq059.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(38)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">It is also straightforward to obtain expressions for the cosmological parameters <em>q</em> and <em>w</em> by substituting <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m4"></span><a href="#m4" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(4)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m6"></span><a href="#m6" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(6)</a>, respectively.</p><p class="chapter-para">In <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig3"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig3" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 3</a> we show the <em>maximum deviation</em> between the exact value of the luminosity distance and the fit-estimated approximate value for a class of dark energy models. For LCDM (<em>w</em>=−1) and two quiessence models (<em>w</em>=−2/3, <em>w</em>=−1/3), the Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m36"></span><a href="#m36" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(36)</a> returns <em>exact</em> values. (The Ansatz is also exact for SCDM.) For the two tracker and Chaplygin gas models that we consider, the luminosity distance is determined to better than 1 per cent accuracy for a conservative range in Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> (0.2 ≤Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>≤ 0.5). We therefore conclude that the polynomial fit <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m36"></span><a href="#m36" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(36)</a> is very accurate and can safely be applied to reconstruct the properties of dark energy models.</p><p class="chapter-para">In this paper we will use the polynomial fit <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m36"></span><a href="#m36" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(36)</a> to perform a model-independent reconstruction of dark energy using the synthetic <em>SNAP</em> supernova data discussed earlier. Some details of our approach, which involves the maximum-likelihood method, will be discussed in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss4-2"></span><a href="#ss4-2" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 4.2</a>. Our results for the cosmological reconstruction of dark energy using the statefinder will be presented in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss5"></span><a href="#ss5" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 5</a>.</p><p class="chapter-para">Although we will mainly work with the polynomial Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> to reconstruct the properties of the statefinders, it is worthwhile to summarize some of the alternate approaches to the cosmological reconstruction problem.</p></li><li><span class="label title-label">39</span><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            "><strong>Fitting functions to the luminosity distance <em>D</em><sub><em>L</em></sub></strong>. An interesting complementary approach to the reconstruction exercise is to find a suitable fitting function for the luminosity distance. Such an approach was advocated in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib27"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib27" data-open="bib27" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Huterer &amp; Turner (1999)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib47"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib47" data-open="bib47" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Saini et al. (2000)</a>. In <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib27"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib27" data-open="bib27" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Huterer &amp; Turner (1999)</a> a polynomial fit for the luminosity distance was suggested, which had the form <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m39" content-id="m39"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq060.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq060.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=Apy28TOaVwFhzqIj1WRK7bTfoG8K8G8UTgV4-znwhg-QPVZxzm094aoqeXEuW8vGposd19yDjW6dmKDtmiMs0BQAvh4ZIruABkcrng3xYhVv4e4XFh8v8HXL36pksXi9OIHAWJXwX0Tav0aFI68ulUgqu2zycw188GUoSNoH1h1HPXEVdX-6F5f2e363QscOBU-2OGt-0r3ZXk94EY4~zfl2sZtrSjuuR3Kv5fXGImdtVfcXtfFc7Y1hONTmNimB5cuwASvbWn6gihr21lREx6DPH7HumoAHOzhF6W3qV0iS4~Nxj8Z2tnPsDi3Wwc~zEdp5jSHHO-0wKxttHKUfpA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq060.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(39)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">The Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m39"></span><a href="#m39" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(39)</a> was examined in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib52"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib52" data-open="bib52" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Weller &amp; Albrecht (2002)</a>, who demonstrated that this approximation does not give an accurate reconstruction of the equation of state of dark energy. Similar conclusions will also be reached by us later in this paper in connection with the reconstruction of the statefinder pair using <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m39"></span><a href="#m39" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(39)</a>.</p><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">A considerably more versatile and accurate fitting function to the luminosity distance is (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib47"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib47" data-open="bib47" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Saini et al. 2000</a>) <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m40" content-id="m40"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq061.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq061.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=MPHtLsbHZ7dsTLNItCVPUhhPhQi-h0OXbVXjnvu5S8n8j0Tu586Ve8MRdeRt~Prda-ejfBnTOG1BBlToOvaPeKR9xHXm1SrdOpWK--ewdLDfKGYk7UDdGO0ohnWo1ruhk2DXL50K8ku6eYYCPnFSTQekyTFBPKfoHN8yR3PKxKfo39uHUFkc4v8fgRcf~GcXwEsH8YzWA-eYZaFRXKiDNz8ywkay0ZcxfEJ5RDY55NU8N~csb2P-DnlGC5g3Ib3nVQ6MPdop~qwjPjBRoTJABeR5e16Varbky2ggp4dOqs1oPL7kOPigR8o5oSmioRU-UAR4V3I56kLFCfOBo-D5jw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq061.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(40)</span></div> where <em>A</em><sub>1</sub>, <em>A</em><sub>2</sub> and <em>A</em><sub>3</sub> are parameters for which the values must be determined by fitting <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m40"></span><a href="#m40" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(40)</a> to observations. Important properties of this function are that it is valid for a wide range of models and that it <em>exactly reproduces</em> the results both for SCDM (Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 1) and the steady-state model (Ω<sub>Λ</sub>= 1). As demonstrated in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib47"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib47" data-open="bib47" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Saini et al. (2000)</a>, an accurate analytical form for <em>D<sub>L</sub></em> allows us to reconstruct the Hubble parameter by means of the relation <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m34"></span><a href="#m34" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(34)</a>. Cosmological parameters including <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>), <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>), <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>), <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) can now be easily reconstructed using <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m4"></span><a href="#m4" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(4)</a>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m6"></span><a href="#m6" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(6)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m32"></span><a href="#m32" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(32)</a>.</div></li><li><span class="label title-label">41</span><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            "><strong>Fitting functions to the equation of state.</strong> A somewhat different approach fits the equation of state of dark energy by the first few terms of a Taylor series expansion (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib52"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib52" data-open="bib52" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Weller &amp; Albrecht 2002</a>): <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m41" content-id="m41"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq062.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq062.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=RZ8Sp18SqB5ZzgkIj-w5wmpm2ZPghxu5bvWyI2EGqpz2DQblf9~fkb3id~OFK4MCLj7hVnte1L8MQqMYe03x6WVJMWtfAkfHSndFZyiVbWMBpqYWNPD9gnYPuhPlukfv7VpdE9bE9gRFVNBh9XiDGn81VSqNcYRhAXsmdSHzPvB~q39nfLG3~VbEJjVz~6VYapHRX2lwf5cAmNWMc-VUEMbUUXPE9hfGqG~RJC8aExd-01PLcwqRqJHTePBi6q37HsQ72CPCQJIVix02X~mH9y-RsRjmo7FZk1YhX1TD-WQwqRtxDX-Eb0BWB5jMXHGbCLIcFRxi6OuylxuKISVHMg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq062.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(41)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">For <em>N</em>= 1 the luminosity distance can be expressed as <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m42" content-id="m42"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq063.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq063.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=EBUmhf2TsVcvOh6RrY~wZwa5~rZasgvEBWVu76Lo2YTPpVH5yL5gqolWABK4mJGrnkFGNaPzRkuF8D1B9eC5nuGZGRHNpX7sJjvxRK5rMT1uI7~udhaJmP5YY2ZMNv9GrMUInza-kFTe5loOqt2pT5t7CqYZeE6WbQtqooFIejIUYUrnV64bA9T8haxtKO2Y9uIkYLMAVQ6tJ3xf9~musrO5xK6tw6OSDy4W6aFt4P1vXA3yxSwyXkR9VRKxzsSuvoEG0zBFeQtQlj1oCzlXj8o207tEYLTE6X2W0AzjUkXFHLH1L4PHide2tgOVwZKKp0FVKWcUwHuCr1bYxy1Kfw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq063.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(42)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">A modification of the above prescription was suggested in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib24"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib24" data-open="bib24" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Gerke &amp; Efstathiou (2002)</a>, which used a logarithmic expansion of the equation of state of dark energy: <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m43" content-id="m43"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq064.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq064.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=jbqWmtd~0JSJli76rwDLmjn2G~cdO0vlQhoQLwcY3i6kCS04HrTG9TF1IlBfGzSlvqX5T8UexS-Wq7~e8NrHW-k5ovzqMU8pMoaFp2SJF84QX2JLUQW8Zf1H8WSQMPZANyzqhyfK7zmXx28KUJmlfxwVR2MURRsFiFCWDib-9-Fr0GgrquJONEPpYS1x-TjLPkccoXXZ58~2GWWKvZg4MTGp9xsZya23l4BQ7YO6VUzDBz29CkUsWv2Cgh2RfvetiG2uouemTU6Saml04Pa5H4XE-71OjMzHv0P5riWaqY52xBpB32kV0PSWvAZ6arQLe1PsyYhdxGQ7zsCUT3HPDw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq064.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(43)</span></div> where α= d<em>w</em>/d(ln <em>a</em>). Yet another approach (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib31"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib31" data-open="bib31" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Maor et al. 2002</a>) advocated a quadratic fit to the <em>total</em> equation of state: <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m44" content-id="m44"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq065.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq065.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=HQRtsC1uPtlcvR-MfbORG63qz4dmLbxRDNbG3CkBi81Kokd251AAc8~9Y1luXl6fxBfd898gOqR~9IEr4ycMVudQCI-xwuB73YZFHku-6QkqddnCUllv0iG~PKt3CXScxbZCDkSIjQO3F347Vu3VKNY1HALJvJXR3N0VadNJrj4bS~oxm9zr4KgdB80ZYxPuuhTPOXun1jAAYzig3NS8yMXb~5ERXv8Y7BdXNKKogH5jHeZAR~7t9HV~IC3H~Zvi5b7IHS5LxqVYrZN5z-Ok72UKf46Bwcjg6FwuetKG3X0Ak-lflx0Gj2~qZ6fGxK2z5YQPs-OnYNH9oFG1VeODQg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq065.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(44)</span></div> where the total equation of state, <em>w</em><sub>T</sub>(<em>z</em>), is defined in terms of the equation of state of dark energy, <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>), as <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m45" content-id="m45"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq066.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq066.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=LfdLln5zS0gWTra-wvYWs6Un7Rvoo3h9aprP2T2ybl8nBYrriuYMZUmlncHuAxD2jyihDOXBBdAP58FSdft1y4Dwh8lO01M-UUl2UDIpre37QlAOgXRR3qi7FqKpjrHLWv1mRE-ny3kUFNvf0LWOAQ7usjQuoHFknLMcdHBMtLnNG8wyLTMOPP30YnvIlNxM9OuiAnR0yJ5zYHxalCHwAT~euuqdO~UQgG2Eip9NYOeQdPSi~T5QoOwBjzHp0WFvMT8QzfZudBMxWPEkdyC19UsYnf5dhJmJW3sudfydB6ZTNmM5wdqGBjLsXrG3OdXvocOEyJrGPkt0FKf48VFXug__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq066.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(45)</span></div></div></li></ul>                    <a id="16661676" scrollto-destination="16661676"></a>
<div data-id="fig3" data-content-id="fig3" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 3.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig003.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=RTeURgCczJmC044gG7GoE-BqEIArZ4xwpDm4aPKiGC0uduTXBKWnnCCNUFGf7PfexCbfdTmZEJ5zqDOKeZw3~JVGYm-d2HJ7LTa2XJ4c2zHkDYJHWw3lbj2lfiSsY9HbWnGTPF0SmZqW1EQ6HeB4ZlPY1jG2Nzk41Rs7tdH0o-AacpHZpXNkHIeWnWFpp2CqCDwQ8ju5dm49JG1dPRfzbrO2~pDiaJZLswpkrbTsoShsr6BYrGMlbsMxT-l3W47iPRmUb5KQNqFbgTFilOATBJqMnGyZNvoMNoaHerIqjPI4OaFfEc4ZMjuYPSdOVjjkOBLNc3j3WyS7i2piyDQr1A__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="The maximum deviation |ΔDL/DL| between the actual value of the luminosity distance in the redshift range z= 0–10 in a DE model and that calculated using the polynomial fitequation (36). The solid line at ΔDL/DL= 0 represents models with w=−1, −2/3 and −1/3, for which the polynomial fit returns exact values. The dashed lines from top to bottom represent the tracker potential V(φ) =V0/φα for α= 1 and 2, respectively. The dotted lines represent Chaplygin gas models with κ= 0.5 and 2 (top to bottom)." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig003.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661676/344-4-1057-fig003.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig003.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661676" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-fig003.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&Signature=dan57a7yFYVhG9Oe-0JJXqn813N8Rwtq56J6TSQsuGPRt4llGXZj7julf1oiX~cN0RLNrk33INCupcrVArwLaB~5l0VI9Hn0XYH4MO6KJhdREBVPCqddrQZmS9l0eOKgR9joyFkJ-zZTWi9lHbchijaVlyqUtxEgXzQzSK7oyVZtgfFbIVry4IW1vKkLxLmUyYjfLOqEmlbLXEvnZhBDTGNT99QpFIP06quXF3tIABgLYHzt48Zd00IWfEDaMmdA9YH7WfJYNqD6e3OR7PjDGGQrL487K~PRKtZDix6zjjavS4lCmM8~V72eMq5qaAIUB9oWYsP2Vmd3evsDWFVtLQ__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661676&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig003.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">The maximum deviation |Δ<em>D<sub>L</sub></em>/<em>D<sub>L</sub></em>| between the actual value of the luminosity distance in the redshift range <em>z</em>= 0–10 in a DE model and that calculated using the <em>polynomial fit</em><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m36"></span><a href="#m36" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (36)</a>. The solid line at Δ<em>D<sub>L</sub></em>/<em>D<sub>L</sub></em>= 0 represents models with <em>w</em>=−1, −2/3 and −1/3, for which the polynomial fit returns exact values. The dashed lines from top to bottom represent the tracker potential <em>V</em>(φ) =<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>α</sup> for α= 1 and 2, respectively. The dotted lines represent Chaplygin gas models with κ= 0.5 and 2 (top to bottom).</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para">Other approaches to the reconstruction problem can be found in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib15"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib15" data-open="bib15" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Chiba &amp; Nakamura (2000)</a>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib16"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib16" data-open="bib16" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Corasaniti &amp; Copeland (2003)</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib29"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib29" data-open="bib29" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Linder (2003)</a>.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=16661678 id="16661678" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss4-2>4.2 Maximum-likelihood estimation of cosmological parameters</h3>
<p class="chapter-para">In order to determine how effective the statefinders are in discriminating between dark energy models, we adopt the method of maximum-likelihood estimation to our reconstruction exercise. Supernova data are expected to improve greatly over the next few years. This improvement will be spurred by ongoing efforts by the Supernova Cosmology Project<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fn1"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="fn1" data-open="fn1" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn"><sup>1</sup></a> and the High-<em>z</em> Supernova Search Team,<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fn2"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="fn2" data-open="fn2" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn"><sup>2</sup></a> as well as planned surveys such as the Nearby SN Factory<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fn3"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="fn3" data-open="fn3" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn"><sup>3</sup></a> (300 supernovae at <em>z</em>≲ 0.1) and <em>SNAP</em><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fn4"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="fn4" data-open="fn4" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-fn js-xref-fn"><sup>4</sup></a> (∼2000 supernovae at <em>z</em>≲ 1.7). We shall use data simulated according to the specifications of <em>SNAP</em>– a space-based mission, which is expected to greatly increase both the number of Type Ia supernovae observed and the accuracy of supernovae observations.</p>                    <h4 scrollto-destination=16661680 id="16661680" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss4-2-1>4.2.1 SNAP</h4>
<p class="chapter-para">The <em>SNAP</em> mission is expected to observe about 2000 Type Ia supernovae each year, over a period of 3 yr, according to the specifications given in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-tbl1"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="tbl1" class="link xref-fig">Table 1</a>. We assume a Gaussian distribution of uncertainties and an equidistant sampling of redshift in four redshift ranges. The errors in the redshift are of the order of δ<em>z</em>= 0.002. The statistical uncertainty in the magnitude of supernovae is assumed to be constant over the redshift range 0 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 1.7 and is given by σ<sub>mag</sub>= 0.15. The systematic uncertainty limit is σ<sub>sys</sub>= 0.02 mag at redshift <em>z</em>= 1.5. For simplicity we assume a linear drift from σ<sub>sys</sub>= 0 at <em>z</em>= 0 to σ<sub>sys</sub>= 0.02 at <em>z</em>= 1.5, so that the systematic uncertainty on the model data is given by σ<sub>sys</sub>(<em>z</em>) = (0.02/1.5)<em>z</em>.</p>                    <a id="16661682" scrollto-destination="16661682"></a>
<div data-id="tbl1" data-content-id="tbl1" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Table 1.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-tbl001.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=vEXGjGs2~PUrDoUbkQHxNk4nQHa2l~d7SLqr86tG6ffZ0R~OpV4deSR-UZ3JmUaITtJHWUGkVrv9eb1pBkOoDSNU5KvnXAMYKo0I232tVz~c2VbXYA9WGKknqDp2CJ0D7jScecHAvnpHzCfakCXKxN22RZmTgK4f~ZEo49AbnYWFEG7FYlMFl5QQq5KVs84mLygOxwpf86QDBXAvAL8H~N~Y7ezrPVj0zmkktKpsI-2nvCkf1-NucRirRSInOGrsF2y2efJIhrEH7oE8m8vy44gt-hW6JyvDqtpJSYKAQenHEqSjZuGX-ZH~zhubt5R0v3IjJO9W9GJYljH9ebgl4Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Expectations from SNAP for a single-year period of observation." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-tbl001.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661682/344-4-1057-tbl001.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-tbl001.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661682" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-tbl001.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&Signature=rDJp5pWI9AWmd4VIm4rlUhkt7kCPzNQtKxzXUl7DYyCEB~RxH~s5~MIJK9p~Uqu5LBWxw8Q2bqV6q28KjyOH6vZucWSbR8e7Vinh3mXhrtaqpEM3bleaKmy5pewVsFVwnpC~nnCRaB4pUdjVRutBjw2n3EHTIV0RKklUFHPNkfTP0GJIcmZbi-9G-8nKZfjEfh1aX2jm796axarzlQNSvCQhxIedxs0mhatETIAmT2wI-BMymTO69DF-x0Pam64Cc3RaVK2zMIWw5zxwuwpUtxae3Wkkrl425vUp4kgExZO4g857QsIkRqlZOmGQNvioM2NvvLni~N~h0900LCPMBA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661682&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-tbl001.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">Expectations from <em>SNAP</em> for a single-year period of observation.</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para">Optimizing the model with 2000 data points is somewhat time consuming, therefore we produced a smaller number of binned supernovae luminosity distances by binning the data in a redshift interval Δ<em>z</em>= 0.02. This interval is comparable to the statistical uncertainty in the redshift measurement of high-<em>z</em> supernovae due to the peculiar velocities of the galaxies in which they reside, which is typically of the order of <em>v</em><sub>peculiar</sub>≈ 1000 km s<sup>−1</sup>. In our experiment we smoothed the data in the first three redshift intervals in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-tbl1"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="tbl1" class="link xref-fig">Table 1</a> by binning, the last interval had relatively fewer supernovae and was left unbinned. The statistical error in magnitude, and hence in the luminosity distance is weighed down by the factor of <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq067.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=qmt0rKmmzhyCxeaC9Vg8hStKOmd5whq8kNbI~a4SxJmsJacqEm~v6-7NvVFprAMhgTqhPCGDEyF1RmeP1h7PTzMbNNdaZyUpASdke0hu0d7MLMbs8CLQtnaVUcDihzfUNuMU0D1V6A9bknnQoOZpRSufQTjY~AwoaeMkaiiJewCuLLXY6GlOu2zw9YOgJRxFoI7dP-TFgskSNCUlXFx~y8AgWfOQ9uBnvN2mb3IXE6~XPIQH5K5Ni2sR-9s4X1Lja9bMQXLcwrW9JyaEOQpWBZ5WJPf6Eag9mMp4cxgOv~VTdzq7VkKGRqDORKRzZS23YwUXU4SghDSbv4s89kjlow__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq067.jpeg" />, where <em>N</em><sub>bin</sub> is the number of supernovae in each bin.</p><p class="chapter-para">We use <em>SNAP</em> specifications to construct mock supernovae catalogues. We may then use the method of maximum-likelihood parameter estimation on this mock data to estimate the different cosmological parameters of interest.</p>                    <h4 scrollto-destination=16661685 id="16661685" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss4-2-2>4.2.2 Maximum-likelihood estimation</h4>
<div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">The observable quantity for a given supernova is its bolometric or ‘apparent’ magnitude <em>m</em>, which is a measure of the light flux received by us from the supernova. To convert from <em>m</em> to cosmological distance, we use the well-known relationship between the luminosity distance <em>D<sub>L</sub></em> and the bolometric magnitude <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m46" content-id="m46"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq068.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq068.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=Q52R0r5hv1NVXijs-tv-fRc5vOhP3c5Mb~AaaPlmwyi-HtWFluMM56It2Xtj1~40brJVxIYhrK6UAHMO4hKYZlaI~~mt2E-~gqcQjW2FLGoxI3i-VhXVsXfeDP7sUO3a~pYs3APAWsoFOmDG0fP5J5M9ZfPclnZHebJtzm3n9a2vfBJH3nlnzVltviBB62rR~vzthRSHBP8Oet7hSmF4zfXLUuWth9GuBPAhL79jErOCpHumc8RY8gEcHuagKFD2Z9YMcvAV3SGbPDWetkWNFee8rN~tQJieXSGW58~WMGYzNzG1I-J8pc6n33tJ0SndwFTe0nkf2rtNrjriDoK6DA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq068.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(46)</span></div> where <em>M</em><sub>0</sub> is the absolute magnitude of the supernovae and the luminosity distance <em>D<sub>L</sub></em> is measured in the units of Mpc. (For Type Ia supernovae, the typical apparent magnitude at <em>z</em>= 1 is about 25, which shows that we are dealing with very faint objects at that redshift.) Type Ia supernovae are excellent standard candles, and the dispersion in their apparent magnitude is σ<sub>mag</sub>= 0.15, which is nearly independent of the supernova redshift. To relate this to the dispersion in the measured luminosity distance, we use <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m46"></span><a href="#m46" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (46)</a> to obtain <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m47" content-id="m47"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq069.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq069.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=glFrPwXsTwQVK2Y9fizNz-G01nP~au1EQkV~0CtH0E--LbyietAlzw4Y2TTzbxHLwufXYTLxEMLSmmX~aDakH8-qDgGtWB8U~AVEl680aoL8vMVYhp50wIWDlj0d6TIFzfplWanD2lrh6bfb0XaR-aPn2uuUJaRg5G3~GQev4EYv7-sFM5swZYPxWzo7jJSM0DJ9XLxCYYKEKrdQrzligzy3w0pkfOz6Yx9WXxZlYYYGtbqw06qgKLnqY~80lN47r44XDX3DNmp99Z4trMMaDxcWJMM66vBZnwiOmAXPuz7Lir8WpiSwMpJEw7kGwB8u6OIrTOLL4QvWJISVBnMfUg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq069.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(47)</span></div></div><div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">While constructing mock supernovae catalogues we shall assume that the errors in the luminosity distance are Gaussian with zero mean and dispersion given by the above expression (∼7 per cent), the normalized likelihood function is therefore given by <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m48" content-id="m48"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq070.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq070.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=TZ8wPzsrwIB5SOzfwwM~C6xLBXQ6IEp5K9bU8L~8L4Vn~Mq0Yt7SwWjTdDw0T-LMHOoUkCFtJdBuP5pB7bLW0Hevgql88pwDYIIIh8VmBxwJFN-blvHKl61INjs3k2qhBfxLG2ZBWNQG0~SgrMI4msrETNm3bXPsqN3Rt8h3dKt7QF4ayNKIHPbJWEKlADvCV5To~GTGAgOxknpZRlF2PCgTcEJ8q6r-OQVYttkK4P4Jw0qJHyEAqQ-oTJb-Tqqv-SVCS7--ZGnw0A3rS0khYP3Pm8sv4QM3sF7dgvM8-I1qHQKPgUeCjyP9ZKXIyEK2C1NR8Xd3d5fd2dgHQk6uRA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq070.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(48)</span></div> where the index <em>i</em> ranges from 1 to <em>N</em><sub>dat</sub>, which is the number of supernovae in our sample, and we have denoted the fiducial supernova luminosity distance at a redshift <em>z</em>=<em>z<sub>i</sub></em> as <em>y<sub>i</sub></em>≡<em>D<sub>L</sub></em>(<em>z<sub>i</sub></em>), where <em>D<sub>L</sub></em>(<em>z</em>) is the luminosity distance simulated with <em>SNAP</em> specifications for a chosen background model using <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m27"></span><a href="#m27" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(27)</a>. <em>p<sub>i</sub></em> are the parameters of the fitting function. (We shall mostly exploit the fitting function <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m36"></span><a href="#m36" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(36)</a> for which <em>p<sub>i</sub></em>≡<em>A<sub>i</sub></em>). We maximize the Likelihood function <em>L</em> to obtain the <em>maximum-likelihood</em> values of the parameters of the fitting function. In practice we minimize the negative of the log-likelihood, which is given by <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m49" content-id="m49"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq071.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq071.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=gW12LFUfr4ty6CQZrRhWC5Bdx8727~uEb7oMNucXCCImkYr4BJ05sIbcUPQCZpWWyN--IRMgI3OiIU~YzvlK9UDgYdaCWLjVpn75UArKAEcIQ-VTjhaoHuRdP8IOo4fRtcZ2S7~nwgZlLoGQvzSMblOrJy3NuqvZz7WkZ-mZ-WhxGgUjBpk6iaF46V-NXSLmAXkpsZ8B99c1Z5mDOadxuorFov8tu7X2kncQVAuyIHNzWD6w0U0PgV3lXkTAe8U~6g6cuAUY~VxukoWTpbvGhOg7VtOxDDdWwiEnOHhasK2K6QhkgG4O8vFqbfTqWNLtFTUzTlMt95LM6teVlq8g8g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq071.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(49)</span></div> where a constant term arising from the multiplicative factor is ignored. We are interested in estimating the statefinder pair <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) and <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) and the deceleration parameter <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) from synthetic <em>SNAP</em> data.</div><p class="chapter-para">The priors that we have used for our reconstruction exercise are the following.</p><p class="chapter-para">The values of <em>H</em><sub>0</sub> and <em>M</em><sub>0</sub> (the absolute magnitude of supernovae) are assumed to be known. We consider a flat universe, so that the present-day value of Ω<sub><em>X</em></sub> is given by Ω<sub><em>X</em></sub>= 1 −Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>=<em>A</em><sub>1</sub>+<em>A</em><sub>2</sub>+<em>A</em><sub>3</sub>. Also, when optimizing the model, we may assume priors on Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> using information from other observations. This leaves only three free parameters (including Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> on which bounds can be specified). (Optimizing without priors we found the variances of <em>A<sub>i</sub></em> to be much larger if no bounds were specified on Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>.)</p>                    <h4 scrollto-destination=16661690 id="16661690" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss4-2-3>4.2.3 Reconstruction of cosmological parameters</h4>
<div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">Using the procedure described in detail above we now propose to reconstruct different cosmologically important quantities using <em>SNAP</em> data. We shall focus our attention to the statefinder pair {<em>r</em>(<em>z</em>), <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>)}, the deceleration parameter <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) and the cosmic equation of state <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>). Using <em>SNAP</em> specifications, we generated 1000 data sets {<em>z<sup>k</sup><sub>i</sub></em>, <em>D<sup>k</sup><sub>Li</sub></em>, σ<em><sup>k</sup><sub>zi</sub></em>, σ<sup><em>k</em></sup>, where the index <em>k</em> runs from 1 to 1000 and the index <em>i</em> from 1 to 2000, with the LCDM as our fiducial model. For each of these experiments, the best-fitting parameters, <em>A</em><sup><em>j</em></sup><sub><em>k</em></sub> (<em>j</em>= 1, 2), for the polynomial fit to dark energy <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> were calculated. We then calculated <em>r</em><sub><em>k</em></sub>(<em>z</em>) and <em>s</em><sub><em>k</em></sub>(<em>z</em>) for each experiment from the calculated values <em>A</em><sup><em>j</em></sup><sub><em>k</em></sub>. The mean value of the statefinder pair and other cosmological quantities is computed as <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m50" content-id="m50"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq072.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq072.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=RXOCHuYpaNx3r45fSw0dImc08k56eDcanL6YB9Vf0-wmG3zjUS899brEVS2rPedtAjH~7vLCj0aGxHj2HsKVly0wbCp2WBsJTeD4YcYBAfLJeNAkE9c6EeXyWJDiF2ET-wh~tmkUNidIWCLEXPBCdBdybRnk1QuavDiPUfxQzmR42Tc6ttPfWond3YnAcSyzG9VadhiulWeXMwYtJvBcfuEwmGkF0GDpDRbjKJASjjdG6NgaBg-47mclDYISO1-H3PhzJoP-ZkpS-aCZx2YhPCcgdfyE~4d6ahdJb~eBm3y80CMVaeUY2dPwjWlu7sW0GDllPW8fsnpLv-7DKv~SfQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq072.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(50)</span></div> and so on for other quantities. Here the angular brackets denote an ensemble average. We may also calculate the covariance matrix of these quantities at different redshifts which is given by <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m51" content-id="m51"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq073.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq073.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=5Bjl2M~zgYVRltfAl0bxCr0wZbHFxwMihHvIVS0JY7H6xHKEcPekKRPVPkVTyF33KW7dsaTIheLMDU7ObNgrJtx~HvE6S~LQu2Fxuun88AValxuwWgIs9ZjVTBvpIVviSeesfo7WN3mOSSR7-nkMgOPo5n7~F7utDU2M~zECnnwgQqHDXxuBDuvEh32McxnrwberLBoKJG37Ua2IpbQL6vaYF-xg5xJKAwQZUUcZDKwK~DeDchqaNDOznE10IVcYWWjpToB4QP8R0WrgjJBpbFyvW62f70KmU9mOoOsCFeV4Pdz2jQV6LF5GVdpnDig4O2jxRjWYPDFwJjihesBjiQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq073.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(51)</span></div> where <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m52" content-id="m52"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq074.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq074.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=K1QIalc1SWJXcqExBdyx9K2t54bjEnA8IKrdVrOHURv2atWKriGXySfMZgwLoGpVgdoDSe-3lxrlg4TI3K3l7e8uz7GU8uNp-Nqsxm0NewpYsn3j7TLq8gVo806Cv0MDrvk~wsPs4qway5ITu7a3qco5noLZ9dqJbgyy9tHxAE7uFmmbpdOnwSAgyt1VqHQFyP6M608O1crv33~WeSHaAE9lZlmSgXRPuGhNtmPCe~BZi-geThZyXGrOqWBXIANoEy6rjKbulaaXjSjbCjIExJMf--3dT92ffUesqIPT7Qb3oLZGaHrwqa94XtMtpzeISZvSCaI9uZPMi9-bc3ybdQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq074.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(52)</span></div><div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m53" content-id="m53"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq075.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq075.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=bJnthAOu~F70YJibeySKbc2dXpLE8TyVftqWOFgIdeA15VprmCViVY6VYaRkDsROuB0S40OTWscT1Hyi-QWc2z3gPtZRDq2b-sVlY-llCyZcuIfMwgNf0DY0LJKDUcInLT58FOIeeZ06vJWo2fioedPe8BnUw7UYHsFBX~Udnt-bOnYGYHO4DB0AlpeDv0YKVU9ZGgEq~uaUqbkmp~QM5kfZB0t6plcN~1LjKxvR7Mgb3Ky31BKAMOCljXjfsufw5PQs3rsk1ds5FIG4V57OmiYOqguJPnKeHbbcI0z2ki2q6y05QnBD7yjSRVbjLOPg45SSc09D2B9-xqRaZ69JQQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq075.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(53)</span></div><div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m54" content-id="m54"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq076.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq076.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=DwIQSGd-xQ~8Itppb--JZ2HuHFiblQN9ONtH4~6XgskTVMJOJqWalxfwnuAhOkDRjJqCYBJlVTc8aeAtDhaoDOzHueyvH46-mlUAnnO5nIrrj3ouCwxSAVepxIu4765yEiET16LU9cieem7vSf9G74mGHxukNHHVteooG9m2zqiOVhfWRVjzr6fHbXgKlhhK0qcD1zSju5qqPdbc9qYCKtln-3lJl4Ag31iApI6YzdUvvRBFFfrGmEA5KKied7xMv8tOEZa003Dhjdkj2hjIUaT8PfJP3Re~jfRxd3qAWIHC-W0Jv1vAaYpmnYz~37i44dyC0PbRfWSKOcTfhOVWQw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq076.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(54)</span></div> and the angular averages are evaluated as in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m50"></span><a href="#m50" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(50)</a>.</div>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=16661706 id="16661706" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss5>5 Results and Discussion</h2>
<p class="chapter-para">From the results we can estimate the accuracy with which the Ansatz recovers model-independent values of different cosmological parameters, especially the statefinder pair introduced in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib46"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib46" data-open="bib46" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni et al. (2003)</a>. We can also determine whether this pair is useful in discriminating the cosmological constant model from other models of dark energy.</p>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=16661711 id="16661711" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss5-1>5.1 Cosmological reconstruction for an LCDM fiducial model</h3>
<div class="&#xA;            block-child-p&#xA;            ">Synthetic supernova data are generated for a fiducial LCDM model with Ω<sub>Λ</sub>= 0.7, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 and assuming <em>SNAP</em> specifications summarized in the previous section. Next, we determine the statefinder pair and other cosmological parameters as functions of the redshift using the polynomial fit to dark energy <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a>. Our results can be represented in two complementary ways. First, we show the confidence levels in the <em>r</em><sub>0</sub>–<em>s</em><sub>0</sub> space, where the subscript ‘0’ denotes the present-day value of the statefinders. We also find it useful to consider the integrated, averaged quantities: <div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m55" content-id="m55"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq077.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq077.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=DX4xH3cnKEJxVRlqRAVA9SHI5SDhCJWKjiG4fLDAMw8ff~4yEojxGZjSlqjF~gjNGNKqBsdKvvU0UDGLXKKkYgoA7EM7ee3aAC164-snbd~7hU-H5kgnAAmQoXX4EtIG4ua9c16fRhrVK~zvfteHngcgISqcIkGTFg60H5Hg2I8ExiIvLapwnHLSdSPWiLIC1sbG2mrvwV2ea-TQpeg2eQ-mGLTaS-fD6FnG2~hjoxlq1lsISLnqd2x9eDv5Fu31vRj9JkwxDlq7zl5SzMYDtKKr1cR~DEGhtdKA1w23EPuaJUd-euT5o6WHUCea5WDCEcj2CsDoj5hJ5~tL7gD9-g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq077.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(55)</span></div><div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m56" content-id="m56"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq078.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq078.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=ySVb8Gghjwz1mzTpjac8E~1GCsCygJ-du~dccdX2bU8ACquDctkibgTThSxuZNnZNU4~231YLK7M-cIWrbDSCyPC5dpn-OdXaZ6nQF~-CBc-EVMPXvmk~i9hUs~7dTZSoDPi0GcmwR0W5Ohpb9aC4bs5px~fFY~0VAu6KHG0H-KEasjvHA5mzVB67MoLnpLODDKMq0KIn~kUOghtEXeHcKC8encOvhc6yY19c0ON99p-atGbTnU2OXqgvvkWKCclSUWGyD2iEdS1oL5FE1A2bD8pQKuyhHlW7XKvyNj5KzY80dhb36xWdgmT4WtOogQFiaOdYQj2tij57G9ampef7A__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq078.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(56)</span></div><div class="formula-wrap"><div class="disp-formula" id="m57" content-id="m57"><div class="fig-graphic"><div class="jumplink-placeholder" id="344-4-1057-eq079.jpeg"><img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq079.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=ZmEPJHLATwxcSuE-EUR8JpA2LSFaeYxZRmSMa34zqaRmcVPpFJLGLP319onnFoHF5i-rDniAHfiYzkZwKA~hm6Y~B1E4Kra6SM-d603nIdqONpamVYt6uJP~jU-mosMHqMJme3QavmYADI499BwtjBMBqsRfOglr5kqfJPv2Mki7JXVQLM4T-3dOxv0lHv6A6dWqFeTDPHz1YxRsnnOOppMoQlR2Gofj1~-qK4WffGBm7uq5Nq7OGksRYT3EAuItan51igNfvA0vY06tm63xQOPjdX2kBeHZIxSSrBwLHrFX~EcRvkV~hY3WIr5xCWTSME9jQnBoY5PQUtGQK4cfKA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="formula" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq079.jpeg" /></div></div></div><span class="label title-label">(57)</span></div></div><p class="chapter-para">For the LCDM model, <em>r</em> and <em>s</em> do not evolve with time, therefore we find that <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq080.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=b9x1LYg6LpLx7AjwtIcSYbXnm~lYl~tqd2fm65675Sa-rQbBFGF1UgPkvpLos1gVZivMemNYTZVFatVXxIciRpRTMJnire~RcInVxUDdEFsm7~0wu2wiDDCIQvc7mv3Ey6sVOyPvDeU8ZgPd1NTuFW6OCAFMxt-uh8pTurOWlWKuI89kgLGpUDZQ470P26~eEGIpVKd2KnXL~h9UwmizBnybXLAA8fHyCXfZWppzY9dv6Sbqyr3qRUIeCibp1NKJiZdqruJ6yD8mZnLNPXFoO~WB8iYZNTOa5MUmCx3fF6aaAK4C5i2iIY~YeJ6so4ssNfQdxhKsr7TIusgyq3WpPg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq080.jpeg" /> and <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq081.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=e5qSBD95368uh2ZvQSEFUPGVvQTSeUpxpYEwi8zGQXb7Y0PDXCz7~g2YepXPySRVa8BBT4EbRcUW~C7W1tjZfPvQTm7vZwFkwfUKGWtgFfc-d27hSS--f8IEONbfhhtK9UOLl5rgTzbumfAT7sQ~6zdGoFiiVMYbnipUGbm2MOsWN1xpe-Kdb-tN9-nt3~JhNs9SlVCh5YZzFsHWh559Uy5YQpwG9czVSByGppnU4ZArLFDzHDJag718RImCATjQ8fpIedJ2pAm54H7WYdtl8IuaBIDGxbkj8EJuccOQVsIMiwVon7dPo18x6VKOC6~JDkdZiWxFVKTRYLCXZZhuCA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq081.jpeg" />. However, for most other models of dark energy the statefinder pair evolves and the averaged quantities differ from their present-day values. As a result of averaging over redshift, the averaged parameters <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq082.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=USl46ZYhRZHOJWePu7LOu7AoGpXT6A9nDoJhvlPDF9zKVvf9UNUPjQOdPECJt0vBdNsdJtDrOmbTGTgzV5jDD3U5C99HKZcsLKDQ67xgv9PMG6Bhwvop1NHgsLlzya9WkwqqeLt~zEBo~nTLeXvzbIpYudfC-rwRaNMO9Mbqw6DSqw0-Vh4M1kkFVkh-rpowMkTlcIgUc0BgzvpQ47eU93IRXC0E6TCLDBr6QzO0sDbRRczCo0MHnuQ4Y5aaT1MbtY8ll9EfiiQ3~~Il~B-9gfmJv11Lq-z2KhB0IfpPjG5NLqTie37dOWy-bsxkI2ZqZV45GOLkKwxse0e3MqFAwA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq082.jpeg" /> are in many cases less noisy than <em>r</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>s</em><sub>0</sub>. The maximum redshift used for our reconstruction is <em>z</em><sub>max</sub>= 1.7. One of the results of our analysis is that the deceleration parameter <em>q</em> is very well determined (see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig9"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig9" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 9</a> later), therefore we also construct a second statefinder pair, {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>}, which will be shown to be an excellent diagnostic of dark energy.</p>                    <a id="16661721" scrollto-destination="16661721"></a>
<div data-id="fig9" data-content-id="fig9" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 9.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig009.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=bqV9~iSP4NpNoP84G0YzCrATo7SFrhOfKJMKoUxDTSh58WpeEMw4j-1H1lO21APh57Y3KWQIRc4wz~Z-9oGQA9Mf9EgY421-gJtSWElYA9TbuK1TIIkgWpy6CWnGOcyCMyf4Z5g~8QZLggCvXyxUCa2lIlUwALZAxP6GUJ6Jj595w4e7BqWVvj0RcPiBnKGE2IhHsn5fNxnFnP0jnP4eXXRAI96N8wdSoxyGF1rbWUHn8vFMTWyyvloYxVlPtT~pR8KKWf1OKg-2KVfrppSGgpOalrKNvzKba6uko5ePbGy-o111yUtbYaoc163lM2mVNewo2oUfrrOnH-IDCRbvNA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Variation of 〈q(z)〉 with z for the cosmological constant model. The solid line shows the best-fitting 〈q(z)〉 averaged over all realizations calculated with the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35), for the prior Ωm= 0.3 exactly. Shaded regions represent the 1σ confidence levels for 〈q〉. We find here that the use of exact Ωm= 0.3 and the Gaussian prior Ωm= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.015 gives us almost the same bounds, represented by the light grey contour, the dark grey outer contour uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.05. The dotted, dashed and dot-dashed lines represent the model values of 〈q〉 for different constant-w quiessence models, for kinessence models with the tracker potential V(φ) =V0/φα for different values of α and for Chaplygin gas models with different κ, respectively. The horizontal thick line represents the accuracy with which the acceleration epoch is determined in this fit. This figure demonstrates that q can be used as a discriminator between dark energy models at low redshifts ≲0.5. Indeed, the location of a sweet spot at zs≃ 0.2 demonstrates that the value of q(zs) is known to remarkably good accuracy!" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig009.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class