em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>α</sup> for different values of α and for Chaplygin gas models with different κ, respectively. The horizontal thick line represents the accuracy with which the acceleration epoch is determined in this fit. This figure demonstrates that <em>q</em> can be used as a discriminator between dark energy models at low redshifts ≲0.5. Indeed, the location of a sweet spot at <em>z</em><sub>s</sub>≃ 0.2 demonstrates that the value of <em>q</em>(<em>z</em><sub>s</sub>) is known to remarkably good accuracy!</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para"><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig4"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig4" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 4</a> shows the 99.73 per cent confidence level in <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq083.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=bEtZb2~1FQG9QSE7gZGX-GFp75l-9ieOkKumpQJaeLlL72YQqD1pLtL5rTBGxsbr~zc6M2t27Rt9isHvp2iylokYRJe0FuYFzhi76jKkwYfQR3IId5Wq~P8IjnwG031OloqME0tdZc5LTk~aNHUDT8-ircNC4wtrMLJm86wugmthjv10kjFWCt6AZIzMuM2c9Pv2PLAu4LrWGIrIPrP4DqPwthM5U03zJ~iEctq5Q1bhNEvfjYXBtH79YLdYJSN1oGY6KbLvIPfFBiZj6UvpET4TUZqWuTXR0kq6n1VMzitUi-icaDlJ565nDUn747rKVAL2L9n8GpVRp8hSH5TnmQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq083.jpeg" /> (left-hand panel) and <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq084.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=02Z-MqIVirabcLJMH62fYF~PEiuJb1mPMPQL78CDZHMNu07PdN2UkEP~c8LRta~FrFLuZw35bVhKGzM0vw6zllzm07aMnt92oZuWtb72z7k2UJrLZgQurCtAQw~k4G6HgygsFOaw7Lr-~BmwTHjWsv4~VGfWrg~4RrJhSOgfsbLni4fgKIurUTMex3u-HAY8poEk6IIaaSTLEXQLa7zPUFVlOMNkdzcNyCWjVuVR66f8vu3c5y7dYjYGelPT6pV8BukHHAV4--x15lwCPsTc-ruvScYt9CJunC39S1IDYyLO12K9Vk3sFTctHomC3HdL9p-IEzoVMAKcJhDEkEx-jA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq084.jpeg" /> (right-hand panel) for the fiducial LCDM model with Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3, Ω<sub>Λ</sub>= 0.7. For comparison we also show values of <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq085.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=OjQQ6IiXsdu9UZEWLimDVpZ1EQDuz1-tWASRbEfhZ9kHtZfvnosMoP14QtPePWAEjciSXlAhGogMAM9-kcfremBBmSatNzsPt56zmDoTX~X2MX8ETGHQ2g1e5WxWwwlmHETUBV9zV9KXV2hoCKof8YtzJ5C842F0WwwEEbyPMDACUc0k1qOA8bm0MJN0XPmxxemWOaW8Xf~Fx6V4ZfSMNPMpOwJHcmXnZMcSRM~6XhYxB4VoDSnyjPFKldbC~PCQh5g16s-Df9aXEcyL0u5ic6Gs-7PyOJybFTP3CM3KeK7Jx4TWvpIm4yu2LInL873kRVgJWqXi1kKeX9OZQC-a-g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq085.jpeg" /> for quiessence, kinessence and Chaplygin gas models. From this figure we see that the statefinders can easily distinguish LCDM from: (i) quiessence with <em>w</em>≳−0.9; (ii) the Chaplygin gas with κ≲ 15; (iii) the quintessence potential <em>V</em>(φ) ∝φ<sup>−α</sup>, α≳ 1; and (iv) the DDG braneworld models discussed in Deffayet et al. (2002a).</p>                    <a id="16661730" scrollto-destination="16661730"></a>
<div data-id="fig4" data-content-id="fig4" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 4.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig004.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=ary-MHg7l5jGV22ZrkDbRHSevW~TWaxtq-qZrUDjdmKwvPavLr6XNVwPAFrfThq4m2NKhpjHlWISiMrzamB1YY54IM3wf9FFq~Xi2dp~GApxJRlFbsC7OYIHRadXZ0avPHobN0sxYvowaXg4m6MikApQa8J-6aP2z4mL5i9yZbCPbGXPLzjlQBikzy7o5Jp-9UjYzTFtTPzPCcB5OJ1w6KYbvBKOuVr8MCZcRiskLNP7xfvoQb-Xhscrt0FzyeuiwRMfNDqGDeNa-F4ZSLglMCLxsByOzMQYzrawhdsXx15SVQdii09r5~7wRSiH1R8kv3v-OeMr5r9RWSz7Qzohfw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="This figure shows 3σ confidence levels in the averaged statefinders (a)  and (b) . The polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35) has been used to reconstruct the statefinders for an LCDM fiducial model with Ωm= 0.3. The dashed line above the LCDM fixed point represents the family of quiessence models having w= constant. The dashed line below the LCDM fixed point shows Chaplygin gas models. It should be noted that the best-fitting point in both (a) and (b) coincides with the LCDM fixed point (solid star). In the upper half of both panels, the solid rhombi correspond to tracker potentials V=V0/φα, while triangles show w= constant quiessence models. In the lower half of both panels, solid hexagons show Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. (The constant κ gives the initial ratio between cold dark matter and the Chaplygin gas. Only models with κ≥Ωm/(1 −Ωm) are permitted by theory, see equations 15 and 17). All models, with the exception of the braneworld model, have Ωm= 0.3 currently. The braneworld model is marked by a cross and corresponds to the DDG model (22) with Ωm= 0.24, which best fits current supernova data. Comparing the left- and right-hand panels we find that  is a slightly better diagnostic than  for tracker and quiessence models and can be used to rule out a constant equation of state w≥−0.9 at the 3σ level if the value of Ωm is known exactly." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig004.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661730/344-4-1057-fig004.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig004.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661730" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-eq086.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&Signature=Tg~Bun351rTL9tn9NVgJyDhZ1AZ8UsKYGKzSj0X~jxRsImNXEJ6H1d3v2sRPvlaqanVH43wxFi8RyaoGlJGutW0Vi1Y9VOgyq1HIdIo7PCzD09o2k3KrdbYEK05iupUqcFAJQWo7YuJoqc4djaovF5ij7qsEK4qJIVeRs~0NE6ORjIQ8At7L6yS9tUQ0Is3pMP4gX6Vrm62UGpLJJ5BCX6EjrEWvC8jhogokB3cuF9dWLp9abkrAzRh-cV8QzJ1-HP9bYD5zXxs1J0R9T3S61iTLuc0c00pNL2b7D~RtgKF8VaNOvJOdAU3vQtdQEzZDbrIg5ik0SPFKBq9tZW7Wgw__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661730&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig004.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">This figure shows 3σ confidence levels in the averaged statefinders (a) <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq086.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=tQfmlCf1hp4mgnOF1jfAbYuz85QOp8Nl6oHjHTA49vJOXRG-4mxGj7jMX6BjZxej88avR5z8~wOFzCxBZo8Nay9ZiTKGR4f5~iwP6DbkaUNbs8r0q-GhhZHt9Alruf5RXDqAcFEF51qI7SNQOvHFdo~-mwh3oKHCRoMX9J3I252DzvVH8ssiw2q229PaKOJI9S8VXucmVchBcNo6HM61NB-iATtl9e-wiAzX9FeU3FdR8ExOP12NwqMjBprlTNZfH9jWZEbzmciBr8h7jwURzLzEoXIbBLNOm8HbMVDdwDgiiIElCY29LkZ2G~vSwrkP0wxgdH-BbSFB2aQtOX2tCQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq086.jpeg" /> and (b) <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq087.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=jwRrjF1SUL3kCeOJklnHH5gzc4U~q6fAwNjmm3-uYdsntGiceURwMNHxAOVXsAux56dYfinbdBcG4bRrWec9kJzKs-tLandO8UimapUtF20e6ytaAcnbo2NOGCNEFnQWQXrw2bBE5qL4IF1u7Wm0d2Py~XJZWBqQdkdSe0aGWGvhz9RhwFlMDyiMfWVUPFVzz4Ekv7l0xQaHaTOtuFGfmpCF2810guaGOaDZjGeFlsx2Wxhz2J-PeOE0uyv2eOdqKl2PfPBEfePFTteeabdiUJbfNzVmfb0qJhKdVIi0hQnYx1g05cI8z2mslRXRIyp5TwlVWObvqkJK9A7OQo8Ftg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq087.jpeg" />. The polynomial fit to dark energy, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (35)</a> has been used to reconstruct the statefinders for an LCDM fiducial model with Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3. The dashed line above the LCDM fixed point represents the family of quiessence models having <em>w</em>= constant. The dashed line below the LCDM fixed point shows Chaplygin gas models. It should be noted that the best-fitting point in both (a) and (b) coincides with the LCDM fixed point (solid star). In the upper half of both panels, the solid rhombi correspond to tracker potentials <em>V</em>=<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>α</sup>, while triangles show <em>w</em>= constant quiessence models. In the lower half of both panels, solid hexagons show Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. (The constant κ gives the initial ratio between cold dark matter and the Chaplygin gas. Only models with κ≥Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>/(1 −Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>) are permitted by theory, see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m15"></span><a href="#m15" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equations 15</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m17"></span><a href="#m17" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">17</a>). All models, with the exception of the braneworld model, have Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 currently. The braneworld model is marked by a cross and corresponds to the DDG model <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m22"></span><a href="#m22" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(22)</a> with Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.24, which best fits current supernova data. Comparing the left- and right-hand panels we find that <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq088.jpeg?Expires=1712717369&amp;Signature=TjaCauxqhyCU0AVrzAJioEBPgIRUAiIX710DRtmjkdQIWJiGvvU7N62SMIK~EvGn73nwpfEss-wS2Kal7n3O0Z4rcdTFVnPNmCLtnhm0e3yqVYon9YPjJwpEEvfpxO1duZ5Uzm1I-j5nCkhgQ8RxruXEhcGTG87an4gRlOsL50up5n6bxqwHCpe-4AXid95e0O6DGfdH61pXrIJ-CHnxXlVvkxHwtWTk0Xynyxz9LBWO~fyOMjRGlXV-g4I8Ilr3ctNKlburi667W3VV9dBGbyj-HBlFjU5WGrmDs5ZjprcOmIjHAXmFfm~ARmGejCH-GDaoZxZaVPZpxq-BaksUQg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq088.jpeg" /> is a slightly better diagnostic than <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq089.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=2XG2Lb~ecIagS9lJeEVMslql245CwWeyMvehKGYaqADK4iX9DL-kT0cGITtPBZXbRGv69t0Qg5wMtcxbzvqfUw60bDXmY0YLmJtftNyFvQhK0m5Vv9TjSVNIPUDpYVvrEjV9mmowuPsoLIKQ3Flpc42mUIQjNd0KTb5QydBKfjWtwzyrxzwzTEMqrv5uBlU8n6Z-6132yEvKRjOEgtAQy-t1cyOOLdy-4GMhaM5n8x1xtKLPaLWkX~1c0Yw2GgibpfDdH2IB8N~xFRkZ4mOb-UD3VbwMAhM022MJ7fEK9H85Clch0C~HvXiyUacViQBpVmZ2siUPJTbFm5w9fBMXZQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq089.jpeg" /> for tracker and quiessence models and can be used to rule out a constant equation of state <em>w</em>≥−0.9 at the 3σ level if the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known exactly.</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para">The above analysis assumed that the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known exactly. However, in practice it will be some time before Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known to 100 per cent accuracy and it is only natural to expect some amount of uncertainty in the observational value of this important physical parameter. We incorporate this uncertainty by marginalizing over the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>. Two priors will be incorporated into our analysis, the weak Gaussian prior: Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05 and the stronger Gaussian prior: Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.015.</p><p class="chapter-para"><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig5"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig5" class="link xref-fig">Figs 5(a)–(d)</a> show the confidence levels in the statefinder pairs <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq090.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=FTNZy8HE0DtwMsiP6V840IOitwhfgimK0mh5YeOGDrtQgOiQwBsexp~vDQN9varKWyQMlpeLbmbVTdTsrmjCqlMmL-xAEEW9voc1buAia7PPXF~evimQNneevmp34JG6E6moJ-h4tK1sVFlqCv-6kK14CAKBHMKCXaLaCbC~6GXgUqPFck-YZY4fqRu~lsRrdKw2~z25M5sQSPVJyzr0EOOkRE9KHc7p1ymvsH02alEzAvA4cpOA2BLTAX0hAGNoq8ivgp5e8wNMpJ4HSxXlZdVv44JUUC3vncV4EIYViuyFjJD96jUIL7xfxvcHRuhg2xPwFPX8zYaYOEBBOmAVJA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq090.jpeg" />, {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>r</em><sub>0</sub>} and {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>}, respectively. For the purposes of discrimination we also show the values of <em>r</em>, <em>s</em>, <em>q</em> for quiessence, kinessence, Chaplygin gas and braneworld models. <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig5"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig5" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 5(a)</a> shows that the diagnostic <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq091.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=z4XQUaMw3fEdZH2T8rPsuArYC9mAZ4lsvlhdyYWNrSH53MQ62hmHgkSz~Fie8UX5APkFzZyr8X0J3g4~1krXBfQBELIDSLYHq6uX96ypuXj4DXkgINtOEEZtK8WJAJr2cKytBh7Zh--guP2x82mRZW~JbD~XtEqvr-AGu4fhdqNNRnDTqgLgT~SriegtlEWetl2IacszwFHrI2WqbCGX6DZjK3X2j~doUkvyFCdLjBA7AmQWmoxfPCe1CBO6hkyDvbp-3~P~yLlY8Adt6kfWlRTXxfqAHoovPSji2EGipIMeOsPYf28l4fvpS11Y1VnEjP80Opxb1I4dzhvmDtZLpg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq091.jpeg" /> permits the LCDM model to be distinguished from quiessence models with <em>w</em>≳−0.8, quintessence models with α≥ 1, Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 6 and braneworld models at the 99.73 per cent confidence level and after applying the strong Gaussian prior of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.015. The discriminatory power of the statefinder clearly worsens for the weaker prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05.</p>                    <a id="16661750" scrollto-destination="16661750"></a>
<div data-id="fig5" data-content-id="fig5" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 5.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig005.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=Yc-COCQ-YihBVkwEWL9v4a1THNxiZGDCWRN1U0hhti9~MiY44rQ56CeZ8gSyH2PgIHletJd8rTFuEWzzJQPPeAghbRkd92IvlL~mxtyG~lpMuqwIsH7oiaR8TwEDV~yzTTrsznXh6HoloWL5AAZrrXLJPfFePi7JU31Qh3pAG64KV10z3v7Z0Lz1OhfXPEkOH2uAvVTKqsRK-VFmSXCC2WfepdUDrOqfr92cdjkwVjSSh1qlr1n3BexsB0fAUD56dUfmLGl12WuDQXfq35w2XL1yCSF2219iegV09mQ6Y50KzNcmhMcpTv8XnAMUYcVddjBTLHatJLHb4mpYGCjHCQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="This figure shows 3σ confidence levels in the statefinders: (a) , (b) , (c) {r0, s0} and (d) {q0, s0}. The fiducial model is assumed to be LCDM and, as in the previous figure, the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35) is used to reconstruct the statefinder pairs. All notations are as in the previous figure. The current observational uncertainty in the value of the matter density is incorporated by marginalizing over the value ofΩm. The dark grey outer contour shows results for the Gaussian prior Ωm= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour is when Ωm= 0.3 exactly. Comparing (a)–(d) we find that {s0, q0} is an excellent diagnostic of quintessence models that can be used to rule out a constant equation of state w≥−0.9 and tracker potentials V(φ) ∝φ−α, α≥ 1, at the 3σ level even if Ωm is known to an accuracy of only ∼17 per cent. It is important to note that of all statefinder pairs {s0, q0} is the least sensitive to the uncertainty in the value of Ωm. This is reflected in the fact that the 3σ confidence contour for {s0, q0} with Ωm= 0.3 ± 0.05 is not very much larger than the 3σ confidence level obtained if Ωm is known exactly (Ωm= 0.3). On the other hand, the averaged statefinder pair  is a very good diagnostic of Chaplygin gas models and rules out models with κ≤ 7 at the 3σ level if Ωm= 0.3 ± 0.05. (The braneworld model marked by the cross can be ruled out by {s0, q0} as well as .)" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig005.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661750/344-4-1057-fig005.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig005.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661750" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-eq092.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&Signature=LqOhFG~slK6jfzWCYXtZNzLqLvO-Ow2Pcl48fiOK7GsPoDn0wBXhjkbzRMQ3r8yxl42TlhP5Inyu8sRoiWRV4MyUbubyAo37~rMdygQXmIUpObscAE2HdwHx4Z1myY0-IyzTsx3OiPCUakrUYYiTWkKOWyRjvJz6YmwKhOBQihD6u02ps44ZTDKFFmiDqy~-4g5uGQKHlCI3uZtH0vKHacxLhJGH2Ua5r501pVYVL7LslQOgvz4AuWaIy8BL25lsY1I7w1fmQMxhSICsnsQCJUBcOwr9H~BxJVNgqO9vpgI5sa3r2W7dcYopa36z5rG05k4aV7GO0IMOebf43AYnEg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661750&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig005.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">This figure shows 3σ confidence levels in the statefinders: (a) <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq092.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=cZQ3iqxp9VT2s8HmL7m8If2R0w9NTjG5pYKcOs5fzXtH2Y-edUCOhEunTWqArr6-kdXBbKGvES4g5H7zA4nZ2TpImzoF8DU7jl5et7kbLqLUbPHJK8KAsRYJ67wxcylMHU6wJ1F9P4lMeGKpjQ5sONFgo4GMi3kxAzrOgBbuyY~xiXt6gUEFHBT~fPlyDXfoTgERBoBjP6w~qKKRAA6IzWeda5NzeILUTT8WRvaVA2hmoOxyzdPtB8jthPdntifhq0av8AdkdSNr9lYbOisyos~v48E4up~iO6nm6rsHc2x9wyUW75Bwu~yqKnnCZZfFJ0m8ka8ga-jHD9