r pairs {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>} is the least sensitive to the uncertainty in the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>. This is reflected in the fact that the 3σ confidence contour for {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>} with Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05 is not very much larger than the 3σ confidence level obtained if Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known exactly (Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3). On the other hand, the averaged statefinder pair <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq094.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=FwtnUS1D8rbOXqTQwQ8Yb5qeJQId9lWLzsQGXVY7drYzd32pBHs3UcPqDxr8574fej6OePlDsH7QPwTMC~ypiCqraKwHiGYThljMkzWT5gz7jLwb~wxBz6dDszL9752JgrBcGbGEWExesiRvSkuyZZyGMDpZiZkK5xkFHlHH0sLhtPnc9z0Ni39QDcA1ZNDMbN-hw0jE6EYsa6nwY31Kqhh2ef8HUo8X5FL61ZIQT5l8WsvLZ4CA5VUoSwpdUdJzX9MZdsrhVTm~EROBH1u6eyoYMxdc1EfNzivdu9EXAwNTT72R2MGK7jmhWcBbx2IPuDs2lWPiXf6yNZApcM3GkQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq094.jpeg" /> is a very good diagnostic of Chaplygin gas models and rules out models with κ≤ 7 at the 3σ level if Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05. (The braneworld model marked by the cross can be ruled out by {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>} as well as <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq095.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=liQLV8lPhnGCfIfLzt8tosp0XaNjoMXSmru-027oZwmbMyHJCu89-rnVrRBHn7Oe0PduBW-VR0pBGVi11pPFdBf6uK5IO34ipQS44QY4vOub2NKvKW9XE7MA76Y6xqwK6qMJbbxLXE31LEgSLZab5zou4Fkb5H0eXtzhgcJIeQwC6HnXXegLp3R0o06bAYrAgM4Bp1525Zyq7fUF~Oweu3xuo6L~PGhqNtbibkDJpL~baqPP-R6rjgik3bH~7PuG4u7PU2lHFrYUAf010UKXcWwnbwRYLhL8BPKpvM~-3twAncFOXtcvKlBIvmwpSnm~VG0P805lxfT9NiMY2T6UYw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq095.jpeg" />.)</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para">The situation can be dramatically improved if, instead of working with <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq096.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=hhOZpZVVbNAVDDku~1~cTlCHSEm2f03lO0St~4zZs5sAug1ZC~uk-Ti8t~O7qla75OK5~CEip5YVK~43Xj0YZIiqRxCGYYRkiIIsuKvQo8n2oM53WluNK4sGGiqcsmng~E74gWQqNKZYzdunew3roDSNnN0A19oenTAhmrBcCl5m384Elzon1fBhesNIjan8AtDVbb~P-YG3hf44fdTNQVgC9dB7XcdohEyUI5CGJchaY5Bdw6kd32BTmMR8e5jklr-hy8HKmqv3OfrmEqJzOJlPOaiK8UsJcH3tc2MDosDNDjJiflTQU4oP79PT0DaddXBY8-k8q5-~q~Zl7iV44A__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq096.jpeg" /> we use the diagnostic <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq097.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=K0OfAFueqMVRzHMJKHY3coZpLwUGC-bJ1Xxm~0CeVTm5x1o72ML9OpPt7X~JV3FJSs~~k73LxbFEfm8A8y5t7AY4MHLZlU7HqlZVrwWZk9xlcto7eBm3k2YKIKFZnBVSIP150UYDTDxZHKMYBG8CPDBwksURDPBEamZ9iOdTdfMrCMoJ7IFvsMz~9yReX9SCH96wKOuSYRDkRqXMwGNkiuh4QFRYAgN4HJil8xAw7332972swDBA7F4vXoUt8m5IvCtO8k3cGTDLf9SRhXqTI4G5cS1DbOVZcojjk5~0ImflSBnu~PK6nEKBmYjUFqlWUmMVpGuCmQmILCzWqgBf-g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq097.jpeg" /> (see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig5"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig5" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 5b</a>). We find in this case that the fiducial LCDM model can be distinguished from quiessence with <em>w</em>≳−0.85 and the braneworld model at the 99.73 per cent confidence level <em>even for</em> the weak prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05. In <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig5"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig5" class="link xref-fig">Figs 5(c) and (d)</a> we plot the confidence levels for <em>current values</em> of the pair {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>r</em><sub>0</sub>} and {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>}. A few important points need to be noted here.</p><p class="chapter-para"></p><ul class="list-simple"><li><span class="label title-label">(i)</span><p class="chapter-para">The semimajor axis of the confidence ellipse for {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} is tilted away from the dashed curve, representing constant-<em>w</em> models (quiessence). This enables the second statefinder pair {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} to be somewhat better at discriminating between LCDM and quintessence models than {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>}. For instance, the current value {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>} can discriminate the cosmological constant model from quiessence models having <em>w</em>≳−0.9, kinessence models with α≥ 1, Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 2 and the braneworld model <em>even after applying the weak Gaussian prior</em>Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05.</p></li><li><span class="label title-label">(ii)</span><p class="chapter-para">For Chaplygin gas models averaging over redshift considerably enhances the discriminatory prowess of both <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq098.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=4ZOrrNd2ZNj1Iifjq0CEGvIKLzQxsddiqlxUVo3gFyQn3WPb3PI~Ygnj~Zq7nnaXJYoEysa~jB0~z~3iD1LehHj9MaEGozE-7vmsN9tBV3EDupQQTt08JOU4YctCJqXjm1sCET4ma92XjLi~agHFix078nL49xfJ90iKIz0Qb-FMS0bhAYfjt4-oxoNEgMQi9LvjKrg098Dj0c5AqzNxDP~hdNH~~yayhMot-wTJvXYHzIbxiilgrC8YhvzJUD-sWJ7OklWBMJvlp1EVmB7e1u5GqjqpXPHTCVPGPK1RKk5237mKVLFzdPuEc2Tep5STl7mTPRGdOTD7ib0JfL2FcQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq098.jpeg" /> and <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq099.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=X-Y80CB~oXv9iC7tKeSITCe-oJqzWxKM7zG0PV-9EeXoBOeUOTb9epXlpcJGJ8rpdhukPO94Y1-ei-N5GPRuYMuIJ4HR4h01kKdiXqE88H8kvQF6W38V-cs-hz0WziD8YRF4XalFgF1vhtBkCy4J3ybr-pJLNYFTh3MAE7T09qrU3J-xWY28jRf1yte0GIzB-7WGzQ~wefDcekyy0H6ug0H-eHVtwJNeM07PRbs7yOMq0EaIiLacLH0Dn~ct343BuK6QyBp0MuLtqm6kZORPktiphl9AkRHbTIYX0qlCmHRk85Jmjq~5wXb46WfKWa6DkwaTJBj98BJC2g0GuDf2qw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq099.jpeg" />.</p></li><li><span class="label title-label">(iii)</span><p class="chapter-para">From <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig5"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig5" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 5(d)</a> we find that marginalization over Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> has only a small effect on the diagnostic {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>}, which contributes to making this statefinder pair a much better discriminator of dark energy than {<em>r</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>s</em><sub>0</sub>} if the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is uncertain.</p></li></ul><p class="chapter-para">Our results shown in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig4"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig4" class="link xref-fig">Figs 4</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig5"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig5" class="link xref-fig">5</a> clearly demonstrate that both {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>} as well as {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} are excellent diagnostics of dark energy with the latter being somewhat more sensitive than the former.</p><p class="chapter-para">We now proceed to examine the information content in the cosmological parameters when examined individually. In <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig6"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig6" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 6</a>, we plot the variation of the ensemble-averaged value 〈<em>r</em>(<em>z</em>)〉 with redshift. The 1σ error bounds are shown for two different priors on Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> and for the case when the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known exactly. This figure shows that <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) is a good diagnostic of dark energy and allows us to discriminate (at the 68.3 per cent confidence level, CL) between different dark energy models and LCDM. The discrimination improves at higher redshifts (<em>z</em>≳ 0.8), especially if the uncertainty in the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is small. The sweet spot for this parameter, i.e. the point at which <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) is most accurately determined, is at <em>z</em>∼ 1.4. (For earlier work on the sweet spot see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib27"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib27" data-open="bib27" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Huterer &amp; Turner 1999</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib52"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib52" data-open="bib52" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Weller &amp; Albrecht 2002</a>; <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib26"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib26" data-open="bib26" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Huterer &amp; Starkman 2003</a>.)</p>                    <a id="16661777" scrollto-destination="16661777"></a>
<div data-id="fig6" data-content-id="fig6" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 6.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig006.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=J21R5r0khWjuIVweGIfBzcWSLz9Jj5I2rGTpi~IwN9EllinWiLJFteWyoplRadwCj5gLg-cS7h02FjyG03XS1HrYc3b8rJwwn8Rm-9SnKCFhQy6MZmBigM55Yb75lN8-b64H5pQ2iR8IPiHF-MUgQwHdTyDRu67mYRtpEOyVGQLKhB5i4tDPxB-kMSgg01MlOeU62oE2BcwIv3Aar0YQo85Z9dAx6JhFswEj9bv3lM62EKYUV6kIdot5Bku4RSMa8WDGdXwXagyp99tpe~P4TP3cBiZLLHNdopu2Ss0zQwD1yHi-JMgl4fD5339bQfs5cwTH7k8epAL0g9PuZJVzKA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Variation of 〈r(z)〉 with z for the cosmological constant model. The solid line shows best-fitting 〈r(z)〉 averaged over all realizations calculated with the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35), for the prior Ωm= 0.3 exactly. The triple-dot-dashed line represents the exact value of 〈r〉= 1 for the cosmological constant model. Shaded regions represent the 1σ confidence levels for 〈r(z)〉. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior Ωm= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ωm= 0.3 exactly. The dotted, dashed and dot-dashed lines represent the exact values of r(z) for different constant-w quiessence models, for kinessence models with the tracker potential V(φ) =V0/φα for different values of α, and for Chaplygin gas models with different κ, respectively. We see that all the model values plotted lie outside the 1σ confidence level even for the most conservative prior of σ= 0.05 at redshifts ≳0.3." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig006.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661777/344-4-1057-fig006.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig006.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661777" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-fig006.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&Signature=NTgkB669weXEkB4KPXBMDmA2FYcm0sAja0P~9cLyigBRISV-35kVD-d-LTbM3rnBv8fNqgr22QLqH6pswOTjulWjUr4iO7u2IOdCL0ixkFwnWuIN0fXch3le1ViGuoTxLM-JfbSNoUGI4PRDLoSkcUYCzpGi0yBL6jQR4F2Ecn5Uam0Qge7Ad8Q5KA3Zs05PWJ91vKlZs4J5o5zTu5kHrVnXracTvDQMrgo9sisOGhaOdrRKpVoc2S1rPVlXzzwY6o6bWmiu616ZXdywkKxB-hiSFVHD0MfIGnzrWbcLp5kG2G~c6VfCD7XD-ip0GSa3--3ugTYl4iVjsZUpFgfA~A__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661777&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig006.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">Variation of 〈<em>r</em>(<em>z</em>)〉 with <em>z</em> for the cosmological constant model. The solid line shows best-fitting 〈<em>r</em>(<em>z</em>)〉 averaged over all realizations calculated with the <em>polynomial fit to dark energy</em>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (35)</a>, for the prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 exactly. The triple-dot-dashed line represents the exact value of 〈<em>r</em>〉= 1 for the cosmological constant model. Shaded regions represent the 1σ confidence levels for 〈<em>r</em>(<em>z</em>)〉. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 exactly. The dotted, dashed and dot-dashed lines represent the exact values of <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) for different constant-<em>w</em> quiessence models, for kinessence models with the tracker potential <em>V</em>(φ) =<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>α</sup> for different values of α, and for Chaplygin gas models with different κ, respectively. We see that all the model values plotted lie outside the 1σ confidence level even for the most conservative prior of σ= 0.05 at redshifts ≳0.3.</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para"><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig7"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig7" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 7</a> shows the variation of the ensemble-averaged value of the second statefinder 〈<em>s</em>(<em>z</em>)〉 with redshift. Again 1σ errors for the two priors Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05, 0.3 ± 0.015 and when the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known exactly (Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3) are shown. We see that <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) is determined even more accurately than <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>), and therefore can serve as a better diagnostic of dark energy. For the strong Gaussian prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.015 (or when Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known exactly) the value of <em>s</em> is very well determined even at higher redshifts, its sweet spot being at <em>z</em>∼ 1.4. For the weak prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05, <em>s</em> is not so well determined at high redshifts, but it is still accurate enough to distinguish between rival models of dark energy. Two points are of interest here. First, <em>r</em> and <em>s</em> are both much more accurately determined at higher redshifts if the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is accurately known. This explains why the parameters <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq100.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=XboG2aO7x-DzHCevuHgxi8QXtejYEzqp2AavdLuwvBlygf2u8j2N6kFtIlAH~E4MCnrAMluVLeXJMH39lMHmflg~17k-VW1IrCecjH3X4J0JGMXewRcUXnAOOZGhxphwFLmIMLbVoVtKq2DWYueg0aDs5eeijHw1a6IGx0H-31MyqND9v8Mzf9U432v-nofs8hfMZz~M1qq1UQJ8CEO5AY4IBbSADlLQviFO9hty5MV6pWuqjEUOeagKSc6F~dCf1IrtQSHr1cdUNySvWdvvFjt-S8r4Wq-s8LOSq93rGSSM0EjN3TeerFAXOx42xNCqF-5Yw5I5WLWWFgSHnmS05w__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq100.jpeg" /> perform better as discriminators than {<em>r</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>s</em><sub>0</sub>}. Secondly, the sweet spot for both of these parameters appears at <em>z</em>∼ 1.4, <em>only if the value of</em>Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub><em>is accurately known</em>. Upon marginalizing over Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> the sweet spot disappears both in the case of <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) as well as in the case of <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>). Another point worth mentioning is that Chaplygin gas models are much easier to rule out at high <em>z</em> than at low <em>z</em>, using either <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) or <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>). As an illustration, neither <em>r</em><sub>0</sub> nor <em>s</em><sub>0</sub> can distinguish a κ= 2 Chaplygin gas model from LCDM (with identical Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>) at the 1σ level. However, the <em>averaged-over-redshift</em> statefinders <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq101.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=fsEoFGIhEd3aJf6efbZKxtljiA2ZSwhXo0Q1dZGoOPOiY5b7HnJXVNcdv0q4X3pYt8xhVv8sc89hu0g9nE-Vsu99TTr3oBIg7W8RcIzUWm6bV7BgSa7OwTlEEQG3JfPuhvgdAjzKfJmBzNHbJHhQlSXiNFeHTa6ExmEoGQEzVPDGxcv73NnlyjyRHq6wipeZRfCTMMkPHa4stPlGMzrt3LZ9Hff~Y9B2-d6NN1SU8ZPoPGzcwR-H-l~ZCeqiYCwHxLwETBT32RGxxY3nYPc1KvIp2QWi7vLguzd-1ZzVOm0uwXkWR~9H0hn-C78FASWNSWhiulYydLNMand8gHmO5g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq101.jpeg" /> can do so quite easily even at the 3σ level, as demonstrated in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig4"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig4" class="link xref-fig">Figs 4</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig5"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig5" class="link xref-fig">5</a>.</p>                    <a id="16661779" scrollto-destination="16661779"></a>
<div data-id="fig7" data-content-id="fig7" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 7.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig007.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=CrgOOhAf1BBilG17KBe5go4PQUdh6pXLZ0HkttFnRfhLP5T5ih66JWWZjC8HrLBVyNuUeLmoll1maCqTMMFAXjEQS6W2x9J7G9NQg2CQlVonlJN1~ssy53jNL9XlLeHrMyY~EgdKFBQiFnryC4uR4YEteWcAZAdJeXVkj-INEvX8aE-x9vrkbfuBQHdG4n7StmmNsazYxQK4XGs47Xk1G65gcGQ6-Pa-SuSt77zydC2mXlF4zAG86tLt01gS-3nmj-na6vjX2CGU91GjtvpwmobkPDYzVhtqzAHIElP12js2zBLRTbIHUvUd43CuU~UzeyFRy-lIqV6ZaQTCrRiPag__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Variation of 〈s(z)〉 with z for the cosmological constant model. The solid line shows best-fitting 〈s(z)〉 averaged over all realizations calculated with the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35), for the prior Ωm = 0.3 exactly. The triple-dot-dashed line represents the exact value of 〈s〉= 0 for the cosmological constant model. Shaded regions represent the 1σ confidence levels for 〈s(z)〉. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior Ωm= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ωm= 0.3 exactly. The dotted, dashed and dot-dashed lines represent the exact values of s(z) for different constant-w quiessence models, for kinessence models with the tracker potential V(φ) =V0/φα for different values of α, and for Chaplygin gas models with different κ, respectively. We see that all the model values plotted lie outside the 1σ confidence level even for the most conservative prior of σ= 0.05." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig007.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661779/344-4-1057-fig007.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="34