ues of α, and for Chaplygin gas models with different κ, respectively. We see that all the model values plotted lie outside the 1σ confidence level even for the most conservative prior of σ= 0.05.</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para"><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig8"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig8" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 8</a> shows how sweet spot information can be used to improve the statefinders as a diagnostic tool. For both <em>r</em> and <em>s</em> the sweet spot appears at high redshifts. Therefore, one expects that the discriminatory prowess of the statefinders will improve considerably if only data at <em>z</em>≥ 1 is considered. This is indeed the case. <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig8"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig8" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 8</a> shows 3σ confidence levels in <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq102.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=gIkHqo7SB91NYui6Sqg1Zwb9AQZKfLoopEdkbY-m72q5BMhUHoTc0h5jf8n6qn6nPcePRgmrnKLIhzalwPy8JlGr37yw26h2yIA6lomJruLX-y6rm49UBZmTiaKWzu5XjhlF7yrlsRiPzPOVBIO0JPQP12~rk7Ikprx7ol~w8eFLe6YYAcfrTeLxu1Dmdp3Z5if9w0DSnNMYiEVPxmMfK4JIbCcLRaRDHMak--BRs5qlK1hhnbx~vbjXZDPvzEcblLUfd8FWA7PEN~NikRmkKWd1ShxcZTE9QyOrza14NKqL75TgN2G9gPNKdFiySmMhdQek9Yk3YdLZUXOn7~A7ZQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq102.jpeg" /> for two cases: (a) the statefinder pair is averaged over the full redshift range 0 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 1.7, (b) the statefinder pair is averaged over the high-redshift range 1 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 1.7; Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 for both cases. The dark grey ellipses represent the confidence level for the LCDM model, and the light grey ellipses represent the confidence level for the α= 1 kinessence model. We see that there is a dramatic improvement in the determination of the statefinder pair in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig8"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig8" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 8(b)</a>, where the statefinders have been averaged only for <em>z</em>≥ 1. From <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig8"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig8" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 8(a)</a> we see that <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq103.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=nzi2k6T7OyryPHUuTzUN9hJZRP8ipdIJg9mV8J7R3gEPQ8qsW53a75CNQCuaCraVWo3awcZRqYCyui9rXFiMyti276hJt~J~PFB3NbG9tuDr~WJGv43WKwP6dfEpAin8rYw-uNUna2lnVYaOL96ou-mO45dfn0Bd1lzU6panaDx-Du7-mRBffw1VFzWTpGbpE9nihYKs~RnFI5yGNjFEad2RkOOlfXBc2NVliHarRlozgMuEtjOtaduoOMFdzUSR~WXZ-GQPgnA8oC-x4GizKLsIC1vezIn4wC7ULxI4Ls7vHv9ycLCYyeNYvMn7iZzeq~LIYIRnKGMFQjUDI5zg5g__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq103.jpeg" /> can discriminate between LCDM and quiessence models with <em>w</em>≳−0.90 and Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 15, whereas <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig8"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig8" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 8(b)</a> shows that <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq104.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=U0SbCz-isasQs-k7rRGNcCMoITtv~3Eh730Zz4JMdlh0NPIjRqc-r5f7H6ZH~4N1~bTkeD1B6YxQa8GyR4M1iBq-hJB0kjmcWjCBBl-eg0ui6ohTMH-Kd3aVsaVj7jBNxfa5XxRSegcqA4hRTHBu5loKu3Zwwz3CdfXawqjopwBexBTi7T6MVqQZkRLqrhruCqWmnFgALfYBfwQ-QDnVAiNObiA5RJT3dYQbN39FPlUUfcOztzK6pUcHyBs7ADgJjD5yBUemFBQvRJe1OnQpC-shcF02FIOM1wgqA7F-BAUKPe0KQKfcrmqgtqhJHi9g1~fjEnFODPsnB6XDR6bUzg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq104.jpeg" /> can discriminate between LCDM and quiessence models with <em>w</em>≳−0.95 and Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 24! We therefore conclude that high-redshift supernovae can play a crucial role in constraining properties of dark energy and our results support the views expressed in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib29"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib29" data-open="bib29" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Linder &amp; Huterer (2003)</a>. We must, however, note that in order to use sweet spot information optimally the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> must be known to very high accuracy. Indeed, for the Gaussian prior of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05, a consideration of only high-redshift supernovae does not lead to any improvement in the results. This is because, as seen from <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig6"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig6" class="link xref-fig">Figs 6</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig7"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig7" class="link xref-fig">7</a>, after marginalization over Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>, the sweet spot for both <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) and <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) disappears. The second point to note is that the angle of inclination of the semimajor axis of the ellipse to the <em>w</em>= constant curve (quiessence) appears to depend upon the redshift range over which the statefinder pair is being averaged.</p>                    <a id="16661781" scrollto-destination="16661781"></a>
<div data-id="fig8" data-content-id="fig8" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 8.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig008.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=HWngf43B~p8jksayxHPCVEll8XHdU6lsS5WBHOyjtXZjuYHjgoCoCUb2gqwKGm~WC0S1~~8tLC1C0xxLByCKeUUzX~Av5z5oMP08w7ohpk2EON2TJQZw0gwjl4ucW~sIsZ5~UjpU1mydEp8V3kzhiHzznAhjwOBTJk4ke~s0X663F7vAdYLYyvyvlfXnCyzEx3TeS0TTPbuu2hmUFKsi6K24Ut5kNubSZok2-Uv-cAXJ5E4iVVlgXWi6INk4nJXlpt2WMCSZA5x5hwcimYM3VHEK5IKDOEMx9aOwdCyXVNuR3qpnlSV3U8mCNftwnxYcLJFYerG8koPdYrOacgzDkA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="3σ confidence levels in the parameter space  are shown for the cosmological constant model and the α= 1 tracker model using the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35). The solid stars represent the model value of the parameter pair for the cosmological constant model and the α= 1 tracker kinessence models. The dashed line above the LCDM point represents the quiessence models, and that below the LCDM point represents different Chaplygin gas models. The solid triangles represent model values for constant-w quiessence models, and the solid hexagons represent Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. Only those Chaplygin gas models with κ≥Ωm/(1 −Ωm) are allowed. For all the dark energy models, Ωm= 0.3 is used. The ellipses represent the 3σ confidence levels in the  space for the exact prior Ωm= 0.3. In (a), the dark grey contour in solid outline represents the confidence level for the cosmological constant fiducial model obtained when r, s are averaged over the redshift range z= 0–1.7. The light grey contour with dotted outline is the confidence level for the α= 1 tracker kinessence model obtained when the averaging is over the entire redshift range. In (b), we show confidence levels for the cosmological constant model (dark grey contour) and for the α= 1 tracker model (light grey contour) with the averaging done from z= 1 to 1.7. Remarkably, using the statefinders  one can rule out quintessence models with w≳−0.95 and Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 24 at 3σ if only very high-redshift supernovae belonging to the redshift interval 1 ≤z≤ 1.7 are considered. The reason for this is that both r(z) and s(z) are determined to increasing accuracy at z≳ 1. Indeed, a ‘sweet spot’ at zs≃ 1.4 ensures that both r(zs) and s(zs) are known with great accuracy at that point — see Figs 6 and 7." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig008.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661781/344-4-1057-fig008.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig008.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661781" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-eq105.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&Signature=SAylspvCeoCjI6hYrYQ7VmDy92TOfmCSjVxVx~6JTInY~jfTgVmYNd-YQMfxY76XlGgk8ESW6X~3LDO3DgI8pDy~YZPDD61GGmI~nHoU6QkTEJ8tkALnHWl7Bl98-ap4FZ4tTd3WjTlIfktYZRa2vSSKcHpyPBQcdeTIqe~IF3Voh242pdEu6OVIPr-N4DjUrUwPCSZmYZzJF3qhrCwLAZZ-B5lgW11NByPww~qoF6S0Q8rRcEz0R6ssGZ0b-mGQoECFdV4mzWAiBLw2kFCVLUoPxkjIIPGOS3u-pni1nNJgCUJUBvB5WidcYwmj1gH3LdyT6UE2dLQDybNoSA0lvw__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661781&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig008.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">3σ confidence levels in the parameter space <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq105.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=aVXxKBtrGuz-D-5g-sz2yq