for the exact prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3. In (a), the dark grey contour in solid outline represents the confidence level for the cosmological constant fiducial model obtained when <em>r</em>, <em>s</em> are averaged over the redshift range <em>z</em>= 0–1.7. The light grey contour with dotted outline is the confidence level for the α= 1 tracker kinessence model obtained when the averaging is over the entire redshift range. In (b), we show confidence levels for the cosmological constant model (dark grey contour) and for the α= 1 tracker model (light grey contour) with the averaging done from <em>z</em>= 1 to 1.7. Remarkably, using the statefinders <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq107.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=BwFV3JjNbFUxg8o-mi2Jczq9Nz5Yy~Va~-ABgO0U~w3zYVWiojaxFStSz5fItqml19qYyyFCHtVFqhpFIsU1X5iMM-SHRkBIoEzdYdTt-7U-xPGXpL90qjKNOfIMETgJQ3Xf5lpJrYGBMzdEIJJRC65c~rLoRUwreZQS47eB0fW1T49w6YLcAOK3WslzAhfAxpj6juol2fa7a6Xc3wyuulhuC6iRZ1yzG3ttiJAGn11g-JEIw9bBID7rEqb3w8mKIVWiRKp9KmgOonLSgbHgB~iDRNA2z2AnPl2Nbh3pzHqI28zlc5NZYkIaolLk-vVXdUBEt7jxxNLS1UGPn0cgZw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq107.jpeg" /> one can rule out quintessence models with <em>w</em>≳−0.95 and Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 24 at 3σ if only very high-redshift supernovae belonging to the redshift interval 1 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 1.7 are considered. The reason for this is that both <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) and <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) are determined to increasing accuracy at <em>z</em>≳ 1. Indeed, a ‘sweet spot’ at <em>z</em><sub>s</sub>≃ 1.4 ensures that both <em>r</em>(<em>z<sub>s</sub></em>) and <em>s</em>(<em>z<sub>s</sub></em>) are known with great accuracy at that point — see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig6"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig6" class="link xref-fig">Figs 6</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig7"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig7" class="link xref-fig">7</a>.</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para"><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig9"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig9" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 9</a> shows the variation of the mean deceleration parameter <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) with redshift. We see that <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) is very well determined over the entire range 0 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 1.7. This justifies our choice of {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} as the second statefinder pair. Indeed, the behaviour of <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) and <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>), on one hand, and <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>), on the other hand, is in some ways complementary. While both <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) and <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) are determined to increasing accuracy at <em>higher redshifts</em>, the deceleration parameter is very well determined at <em>lower redshifts</em> and the sweet spot for this parameter appears at the redshift <em>z</em><sub>s</sub>≃ 0.25. It is interesting that, in sharp contrast to what was earlier observed for <em>r</em> and <em>s</em>, the sweet spot in <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) persists <em>even after we marginalize over</em>Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>! From <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig9"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig9" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 9</a> we can also determine the value of the acceleration epoch (the redshift at which the Universe began accelerating). We find that the acceleration epoch is determined quite accurately: <em>z</em>(<em>q</em>= 0) = 0.66 ± 0.06.</p><p class="chapter-para"><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig10"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig10" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 10</a> shows maximum-likelihood contours for the pair <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq108.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=jvsofw7cCFyI7bRc37GRxKbnv2ZsHOZ-qOUbjcfNZIzaHFk~xqZgyAZ5amfkT08otbsyFsuzoHoUn9~vQDR9l57VAIOIR2sUhg0ljxc1iOviuwCy31AIcnYkbdcCiQ6GLoloNQ2aNZk6WGN4dYFH50plNTwSont654vh9FJHDlG9Xu4emL~p2jg9EUR0cIWk39h1x89VynAMrk3ZYkbdbmrW1ZycE5OVTyU6Qtc~Ic5CTB1SpAZvRQydMv5FkqO~xH-52ZQTG9CIkTlmdNJZ9zRHq2iPnvEJlITxZtJxJJAihaGO09H4pYG4BRoHnLLvbUSeq8wgeVORaF5XJQ69bA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq108.jpeg" />, where <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq109.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=fcVsRfS5kXMfCeix2DeNWWTacatFh0NiG14w6nlbRe-oronQLFZ3q8XqP3laNkTbodMWPS9UUt1YOmQQasKoGdonb9C6zJJn3EFugn0HcSWCtzQs1xdL3I225ikp~s0hDkk0RbtO3F2wG62zEwzAvPJrkIvS0gr3ELc47P0jzqluj-igbnnKy90k5ajuxNVkQDCiIYPhgC6NN8OttzKrRWd9QVgvfUd0PmzpHrdLiKPvEUr8qcnis5Qp~CiQBoKkzOgKHEqTK-qg2Sak8nG1nDyXzmyHK5pvboJPP33zbU2nv6O~oAL-ERpbmlWqgayv1X7DqEGHGoENFneJkceeBg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq109.jpeg" /> has been averaged over the redshift interval 0 &lt; <em>z</em>≤ 0.4 while <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq110.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=MYXAJF8O35yJ8wY5LMK3llE0jqCpsIe-7xyR2sEHXPUUXuM3ztLOZDLtvx~RjshPnqQkW-6NQDSMKS2BFKzbMoQYfsMFTbpZXD1znScBJRjQNw13HdltMOEf9JXIvaaXExiTSqIrxdCtQAPejqejcJjsK5sR1901b~XLF2u4cPiSG9Fq4KKAzGkSH6yeczDvYeD~X4zXN02~-2-tVIs4zDVUZ85PPlgqoyLTR~4w0TCrfrz4G3yqhC8NgBdhNXITdkFSCZXuMrjw923jnVc6Rfqsb0q6~IZGSpNKTjCw3MS9q82bi1JS4hV-sH6B~IBnvGAmSg-ARBknedl3atMgMQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq110.jpeg" /> has been averaged over 1 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 1.7. This figure clearly demonstrates that <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq111.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=gr0JoZk3veB9z4RuCpNlYK4-qt2uJOCcmtSsmpkufRciSMgRyuxDpwU0sYwEsp~Cb6lRsDP8-uvPIgfEQIP~op-dWZhXUDfiLIbdrYSdBFZ3LqKXRtziPL3Ngm-cTTBX4M6ih1THe5zS9xDeyjYqcXrJARd~vz8WZVuELrGsRif8BfKNtZpp02I5HFtbKPPbPKJgkQ1vDC0Vm-bAB5OeF0xAjaDvcQZf5doRl1OQXjYrc735HH4unby62klHdrpR6iBEg8HEbKh0rRsy3PLrQs~2PwLyLdhhu4P05HwWnzBWRiukBnVIWBYYk3YYFyJcuXEJQEvYBYG6q-srTdZ4fA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq111.jpeg" /> is an excellent diagnostic of dark energy since it can distinguish LCDM from quiessence models with <em>w</em>≥−0.95, on the one hand, and from Chaplygin gas models with κ≤ 25, on the other hand (both at the 99.73 per cent CL). <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig8"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig8" class="link xref-fig">Figs 8</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig10"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig10" class="link xref-fig">10</a> show that the ability of the averaged statefinder pairs <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq112.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=yblfIoaljdLHD~vr91KAykXFVVdIAPXGfhw8jqqKHxK~ilMAfuX6fKT5L7FbyAiu-Nc3JHnN7FlplQS74nsOreX9uN4sqWfNvsGCHOImg-PohNAFbP~TsusZYgvc8jmlMtWa2SkRQ9C8qwcOi~I0sx~wFSGAYXV6bmbZWIzAaYzND7EijgQgqRGW8LOfz2t8Q6p~4cGU0-snvVRZotfeT8Kco6N78loPSZrEMFyQT~V2BTbPuw9mCl7yXCwJ17KUTCLHKKM~WLilOFvNLTAZn2B07BBUIR5glc10MAbqZV8wuWsw-l8M3IiiL5q8iK9aURLeYLdAp9Kj~Yj7knexIw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq112.jpeg" /> and <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq113.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=0YFGBc~o337UvT5EunzYkdDFwvwh8ydea2LgfR5GI9zGOAlykzBviSU0kkX6b~5--udhH9-zDHAv4K0EmjV8qzW58k5wc40bgSjlQ-GFU8snrYJJ-1ipAhp1BKn1lOI~2lJIKrS9cPg23WyIYOPxIvpPRCnQgNQjOaNg7noLWEmIULwnJVkXlV~75PNXgw3MUQHrMbpLqzltjO97811AbdxXDu5HIMQd1NimbpU2GUmxVdMVrEl53b6dMvG8GxjC5g2xSflbjlZn1YEHn2KfNSDTHYDalaHmkh~kEMTZTuZf7rFw~qukgxbbSIz9D62yxG5WF3bapPWGpmxeVnkpPw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq113.jpeg" /> to discriminate between dark energy models is comparable if the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known exactly. (As demonstrated earlier in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig5"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig5" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 5</a>, {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} is a more sensitive diagnostic than {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>} if we marginalize over Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>.)</p>                    <a id="16661784" scrollto-destination="16661784"></a>
<div data-id="fig10" data-content-id="fig10" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 10.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig010.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=xdHP3iIS1mBdQlAFmQo9UO6itzHgNdOYpUur13l1TZknucYTx9f2wT6JhnL4SZHgOWGNPjRUv2srDYoIggERbcWlEhT0HNvvCITCg~Uq516KbRYuNDa8j6PRVYMJNmyas~~wzy2lZdbYpXd7w55-VWj7VWnlVKEAyYcMeE3YIykGPI1AGoEdgv1I1jzxb-rqnCnh2kBeLGYOlt7Yey-tB8lFmBaWcOKFJw~78oeLsZvO3uqP~~PevDJlRUUykXJtqRKQojAGm9Z0Tdn1On0~THtXHfpDyLtMKXczQ6ECTv17V9cvuSCgtiJJoyuFnM9P6p6vptG2f7dzbfKwxfn79A__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="3σ confidence levels in the parameter space  are shown for the cosmological constant model and the α= 1 tracker model using the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35). The solid stars represent the model value of the parameter pair for the cosmological constant model and the α= 1 tracker kinessence models. The dashed line above the LCDM point represents the quiessence models, and that below the LCDM point represents different Chaplygin gas models. The solid triangles represent model values for constant-w quiessence models, and the solid hexagons represent Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. Only those Chaplygin gas models with κ≥Ωm/(1 −Ωm) are allowed. For all the dark energy models, Ωm= 0.3 is used. The ellipses represent the 3σ confidence levels in the  space for the exact prior Ωm= 0.3. In (a), the dark grey contour in solid outline represents the confidence level for the cosmological constant fiducial model obtained when q, s are averaged in the redshift range z= 0 to z= 1.7. The light grey contour with dotted outline is the confidence level for the α= 1 tracker kinessence model obtained when the averaging is over the entire redshift range. In (b), we show confidence levels for the cosmological constant model (dark grey contour) and for the α= 1 tracker model (light grey contour) with the averaging done from z= 0 to 0.4 for q and from z= 1 to 1.7 for s. The reason for choosing these ranges is that q is extremely well-determined at low redshifts, with a sweet spot at zs≃ 0.25, and s is accurately determined at high redshifts with a sweet spot at zs≃ 1.4– see Figs 9 and 7. Using the second statefinder pair  one can rule out quintessence models with w≳−0.95 and Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 25 at 3σ if only very high-redshift supernovae belonging to the redshift interval 1 ≤z≤ 1.7 are considered for s and low-redshift supernovae in the interval 0 ≤z≤ 0.4 are considered for q." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig010.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661784/344-4-1057-fig010.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig010.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661784" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-eq114.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&Signature=yk6jQ1ObOeHWcxdIjNEHesgCwTpo8zJh4Qd~uAu18~8MIyFC7u47lPRpf2RqhErKuID9YG9uQ9j3KOBE0PiAr2yZNacOko15Cb8UyG46F3r4ok8fBDmsYQJfVrdZieY7hOeR~IqQ0UGupnkGlwXvXAqpJrz9sc9Q~6w35C2JHjnhzJCmXQkFiW6QeuWw3~LOMgAb0HyudtZxbX0-DYS2Jkx7FwOjjULNfBkRYDPlv0eD6xks2mBFZbgBURPfsInEGuvq-BPXhxMa-iVEyaMTb2E~Vwqw9fsPMGtrsb2S-Egkd0NIx0GlbaN6LpdCLVu8QPvH795vuLaFY8Sb8mNW7Q__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661784&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig010.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">3σ confidence levels in the parameter space <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq114.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=mNCNIUJ2pbdC~HanOj9yduM6MK6RqgWU9zoWgUyhctRWgC0ZZsL-QBprdc~JsNhzXofBGVBTh94vdh7pVEdz~dZSdMz52ryG4isYPuNk1B~98NSnExJxYT6ud6UB9G9xV2PBm1qnzjy3XI6D~X1oZZvp73NDp1WVOBgE4HFc7QeRExFZh-8A~9072jx4Enpai6GwIMHUh7AWORITCrh7ZDPVw7hnmBqalVSAFfPhNMCKx~fm7LadNviLONf66bwN~Mvre9mIWJCs7aQLGbes~WkEZ7O5rhxZT986oZEEDt1jt5WvVDyI~0yozmQIrnLUVuhawI2ol83raCmqR-pDeg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq114.jpeg" /> are shown for the cosmological constant model and the α= 1 tracker model using the <em>polynomial fit to dark energy</em>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (35)</a>. The solid stars represent the model value of the parameter pair for the cosmological constant model and the α= 1 tracker kinessence models. The dashed line above the LCDM point represents the quiessence models, and that below the LCDM point represents different Chaplygin gas models. The solid triangles represent model values for constant-<em>w</em> quiessence models, and the solid hexagons represent Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. Only those Chaplygin gas models with κ≥Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>/(1 −Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>) are allowed. For all the dark energy models, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 is used. The ellipses represent the 3σ confidence levels in the <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq115.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=f2m81al92YTBeqXZU4poBE95FWZKuPGeREkrYV7gOMqFc7LbvITfM~j8qdZWRyH9-1WVoYnmtCt7y4u-TUOBRnPruxloiuLfbURT8nGzbbbHtaJ6FlJtUBMJ-0qDreP9lhmp4p8c7p5jvOs60usRTdbSOH6eVgTjiXHw7ktYc6FI4gfqCSjQfls8MI6P-qWatKYFCON0DOSewmJPcOqOts3nGlg2E3rH~anYKcEgBx5y4DkfrpN6bae41veyT~E7urnXyKTAPe-XC1f-Uw4an9OPMu-JR~cYS15xb7wIBuIOSIwN6dF5dFeuFpPjqcXg1LaWQl1ppPWhuvrIOgmbdw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq115.jpeg" /> space for the exact prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3. In (a), the dark grey contour in solid outline represents the confidence level for the cosmological constant fiducial model obtained when <em>q</em>, <em>s</em> are averaged in the redshift range <em>z</em>= 0 to <em>z</em>= 1.7. The light grey contour with dotted outline is the confidence level for the α= 1 tracker kinessence model obtained when the averaging is over the entire redshift range. In (b), we show confidence levels for the cosmological constant model (dark grey contour) and for the α= 1 tracker model (light grey contour) with the averaging done from <em>z</em>= 0 to 0.4 for <em>q</em> and from <em>z</em>= 1 to 1.7 for <em>s</em>. The reason for choosing these ranges is that <em>q</em> is extremely well-determined at low redshifts, with a sweet spot at <em>z</em><sub>s</sub>≃ 0.25, and <em>s</em> is accurately determined at high redshifts with a sweet spot at <em>z</em><sub>s</sub>≃ 1.4– see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig9"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig9" class="link xref-fig">Figs 9</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig7"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig7" class="link xref-fig">7</a>. Using the second statefinder pair <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq116.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=ONcDvG7p6ReLtXk0vqdH5wLeUcdgJdyDe01bAD0d~6mpqJJmF-sV9CdXlkl6-EDj-vOicoK4IxwWuhqw8XajHydnH5XMpYVFyrD34JQwCn9-AbgIr~NiZ05hYKi9ap9MezTJEJuw1GGH4zsVIUFi0VkkweHFQPoZdHAOiD4jE305SkKULXxS0FtGJyM24ofgALvAsNNLqUSiRKV9-Ag4VtqHXK8gpyq6ArlwKZr5vWinZv70d~Ig0dztYZDMX8ODZX3SyYZmeTLEiUOwRYbDf-sXHvVVnAD3x2aiUMOaKgpt-6tAud-6FxyAUIgR6XBAJBfbTrOcvBNDWLtdFSZewg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq116.jpeg" /> one can rule out quintessence models with <em>w</em>≳−0.95 and Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 25 at 3σ if only very high-redshift supernovae belonging to the redshift interval 1 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 1.7 are considered for <em>s</em> and low-redshift supernovae in the interval 0 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 0.4 are considered for <em>q</em>.</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para"><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig11"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig11" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 11</a> shows how the equation of state <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>) varies with redshift. We see that, although the equation of state is determined remarkably well at small redshifts, cosmological reconstruction of <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>) steadily worsens with <em>z</em> and deteriorates rapidly beyond <em>z</em>≃ 1. With the most conservative prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05, the Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> can distinguish between the cosmological constant model and the quiessence model with <em>w</em>=−0.96 at the 3σ level provided we restrict ourselves to low redshifts <em>z</em>≲ 0.4. For higher redshifts, the LCDM model cannot be distinguished from the <em>w</em>=−0.8 model beyond <em>z</em>≃ 1.1 (after marginalizing over Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> with the prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05). In the ideal case when Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 exactly, LCDM and the <em>w</em>=−0.8 model can be distinguished up to <em>z</em>∼ 1.3 but not beyond. [In this case the best-fitting <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>) is biased beyond <em>z</em>≃ 0.7 and takes on a lower value than the fiducial value <em>w</em>=−1.] Somewhat surprisingly, although <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>) and <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) are related through <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m6"></span><a href="#m6" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(6)</a> and therefore carry essentially the same information, even a cursory examination of <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig9"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig9" class="link xref-fig">Figs 9</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig11"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig11" class="link xref-fig">11</a> reveals that the Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> does not reconstruct <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>) to the same accuracy as it reconstructs <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>). However, like <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>), <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>) is reasonably well determined at low redshifts, having a sweet spot at <em>z</em>∼ 0.25. The sweet spot persists when we marginalize over Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> using the Gaussian prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.015 but disappears when the uncertainty in Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is increased using the prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05.</p>                    <a id="16661786" scrollto-destination="16661786"></a>
<div data-id="fig11" data-content-id="fig11" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 11.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig011.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=SkMYeAvYO74vhDFkpd965qqWGtwRaibHOScUvWjWRUKZmvj4Wiv9Zp54hVmnpLtgRaOhLT3zj5I1Eu~bZI2Cdt2S25dnnswXysSkQg5RJf3ZPTXgw~u4MvY2xffzUtC6RWIZ5OAXQlFzaS~vAzNsHpnfU1hByPa2jg~sszrrqqo1AL5NWMW9OI94eWIwnZ0U11aYmQyDGxxiI6r2Tm4W84Ki55~Bdn~a80c2R7Mvx7rJ~x5~xMERxUX-lRW7Ss~ATUnGrR7h3lYOvkAx742Hf6j6KhdBzhMWOJuImmarPz97vKn~BX6T57mgMpE~5R5X6X8dLyVYr9FZ4XEaFYuZWw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Variation of 〈w(z)〉 with z for the cosmological constant model. The solid line shows best-fitting 〈w(z)〉 averaged over all realizations calculated with the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35), for the prior Ωm= 0.3 exactly. The dot-dashed line represents the exact value of 〈w〉=−1 for the cosmological constant model. Shaded regions represent the 1σ confidence levels for 〈w〉. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior Ωm= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ωm= 0.3 exactly. The dotted and dashed lines represent the model values of 〈w〉 for different constant-w quiessence models and for kinessence models with the tracker potential V(φ) =V0/φα for different values of α, respectively. We see that w can distinguish between the cosmological constant model and other dark energy models only at z≲ 1." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig011.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661786/344-4-1057-fig011.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig011.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661786" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-fig011.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&Signature=Z2cj6Z1dNl-e4fx03fwpKFxLLv3J3-NUMAmQ8d7Wv8w81Do7JMaJuEG8d5qdknpWoeVu02pYPWKKz7CsuAilYWklaIGSXLBwJnTrXhm~lyixU2-r7xgEZ8QRhGQsTihPONNkOwJbXn2qg3dfLK~GMkWPEnORVVxvWza758fkRb0O7-MFMp6Husm8vZheNXMEpu3HShwETlxOxOOcYcpYK7PAn21iJgHlf74mZi6UP0RTXT1AhiNOT~M39pCMx9f8f7Z2GRtXVvRTBE4FdI69R1LdfwzNMCffOhEeCTyLkaSILilGLDVj0DA1wpT2pYvm30xFpGJMwCHao0qJnWlTKQ__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661786&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig011.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">Variation of 〈<em>w</em>(<em>z</em>)〉 with <em>z</em> for the cosmological constant model. The solid line shows best-fitting 〈<em>w</em>(<em>z</em>)〉 averaged over all realizations calculated with the <em>polynomial fit to dark energy</em>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (35)</a>, for the prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 exactly. The dot-dashed line represents the exact value of 〈<em>w</em>〉=−1 for the cosmological constant model. Shaded regions represent the 1σ confidence levels for 〈<em>w</em>〉. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 exactly. The dotted and dashed lines represent the model values of 〈<em>w</em>〉 for different constant-<em>w</em> quiessence models and for kinessence models with the tracker potential <em>V</em>(φ) =<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>α</sup> for different values of α, respectively. We see that <em>w</em> can distinguish between the cosmological constant model and other dark energy models only at <em>z</em>≲ 1.</p></div></div>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=16661787 id="16661787" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss5-2>5.2 Cosmological reconstruction for a tracker model</h3>
<p class="chapter-para">We now briefly examine the accuracy of the statefinder pair and the Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> in determining the statefinder pair for a fiducial model other than LCDM. We know that the Ansatz returns exact values for the cosmological constant <em>w</em>=−1 as well as for quiessence having the constant equation of state <em>w</em>=−2/3 and −1/3 (see <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig3"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig3" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 3</a>). It is therefore important to study the accuracy of the statefinder in reconstructing the properties of dark energy in models in which both the dark energy density as well as the equation of state vary with time and for which the Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> is approximate. For this purpose we shall work with a fiducial dark energy model that evolves under the influence of the tracker potential <em>V</em>=<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ and use the Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> in tandem with the statefinders <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m32"></span><a href="#m32" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(32)</a> to reconstruct the properties of dark energy.</p><p class="chapter-para"><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig12"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig12" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 12</a> shows our results in terms of 3σ confidence levels in <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq117.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=kydhpYRNL~Owo7bhy0PAEb9Fnw6xDLMrAnrrh3L9niHIC41xBHYutAnc6fXZwk~JOH42shWWvypgG8JrSc6i7IWVrHoz5bgJ7uc1wZvmN8raCLE7BgFXKjfrhjlvC7nDkTNonUha~hP9yIDcU1wFFYoM34N4JVwNC9PNEXyNoZHXQt2rRWdfodArYP3w68Pj1Q128G73sIZtpJweEbO0dYX2gcsZ~WUg8FZzTVEkZf0wdLw1L0kzup2v2ycU3M8d-ejIbtQKCXccGOls8ImswXErxXyJ5B6Yf~OgzonhNO2mjY~hGjvbhWBuj0cW8JN3OkhYXX6mn~CjqGDSEFMyjw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq117.jpeg" />. We find that, if the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known to reasonable accuracy (Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.015) then the averaged statefinder pair <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq118.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=Sh2tyJPYStzWAHUGg1HmDz1uSH2Ug3-3K6b9iHkIaeq5F36tYm1P59HUCj0Qjp6l75wCClOWL-ZZiy8sHqRFksiUbz1~eodlyg00K-tXKtKozZYnwiU49Qy8QFwuOgATXHvBkIedekL3oKCmHAsMuISNR96~fYjhkh~9dW~5sAY4jCrc5hw7sIg-Ua6y~atMLe0Oo6nkygKTCXQT8cEy-lsoQqEpxp6a0rFa-k1CuYgwKGKLAlf4Ok-DoC7aQlX8eHrqoNTvqkJVjVhrU4jgGUzH4-38aOkMap1bUQ9fXlKGtNz7HWDf3Cs-XnC2QX3aouLgOUQWJxvvlpT~vcDdow__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq118.jpeg" /> is able to distinguish the model <em>V</em>=<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ from the model <em>V</em>=<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>2</sup> at the 3σ level. As expected, a large uncertainty in the current value of the matter density reduces the efficiency of this diagnostic and the two models <em>V</em>=<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ and <em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>2</sup> cannot be clearly distinguished if the uncertainty in Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is increased to Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05.</p>                    <a id="16661793" scrollto-destination="16661793"></a>
<div data-id="fig12" data-content-id="fig12" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 12.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig012.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=ur6f4X4Hn4W1dgfJ9jExlGZ8jooJSQiAraMjrwH14YTbB2-Sg2fduc370SusPqh3V9QOC6mIYkWatnPeMpjFSLA20VNlu66KeAsg1nvmL11ZoWdM2KEf3BEhUb~T8hKOHx9dSq5fTrl~UM~2c~fbREN4Vlj5M9-UBu0nGzVNPGJ18QN~SIP3zVa5S5MD8i8s50mqZpd-LPEUiTupv9877NED-Fx8Ob052zeSeZqD81-1rKj2b0rnw4u5U4kTqCCyF9a1ip~wUR8qxIlBEE7M~OVsQLxpIUaWDHGIOeP7g7GaHHV6Hc0keRDiu9pXfHegmGDexUAadbL~--DF1Q4UIQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="3σ confidence levels in the parameter space  are shown for the kinessence model with tracker potential V=V0/φα for α= 1, for the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35). The solid star represents the model value of the parameter pair for the cosmological constant model. The dashed line above the LCDM point represents the quiessence models, and that below the LCDM point represents different Chaplygin gas models. The solid rhombi represent tracker kinessence models with different α, the solid triangles represent the constant-w quiessence models, and the solid hexagons represent Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. Only those Chaplygin gas models with κ≥Ωm/(1 −Ωm) are allowed. For all the dark energy models, Ωm= 0.3 is used. The square represents the best fit for the α= 1 fiducial model. The shaded ellipses represent the 3σ confidence levels in the  space. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ωm= 0.3 exactly." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig012.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661793/344-4-1057-fig012.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig012.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661793" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-eq119.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&Signature=GTVGzMXi4yAtMcFa7~oH~EpaGMLI3Zef78KjmKnyaMniPDLS26ukplwURCm2Qudx1V00L4taajKjnWIzC2I3Hl9UZyCjneYucOVOXHOeFr~jiGrI9VKZIUAK8AkFubyfryROEkIBAcIMltn9y0lCwX8nzPkhl2lBYM5BqbXPtM6V2zMTI0v~IgBIdsqqb0IpVG8l6DOQsd5wsHOAOFdi1J2N4oxt4o7VoBPbb1imoU1KM3j5C3i2TOGe6D579rmGaJdwQhH~A4hX3EB5PJWwh1zPa03h3dCKKr3q2N7Vuw7F9H6XLgv2gRpWHLOHF1QQR9wWn1OnlEYSGpw~xr4-PA__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661793&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig012.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">3σ confidence levels in the parameter space <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq119.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=5GxEGq~ghHjTC35a057HP3aej6mGvP0jpGaCBN-OqvuDMLyh3fvb8WPQIZ3bbUjL26A0WKxscY-gw4jzDiWkNN3D1GbPJoo2NQJTDpLgmHpSCLX9Br0cJypsfE3vSHQN7g-OBupnLW2Jh22OGBEhPrhRatoWHm0pmT3uIIynsvIzaJpoQmSKm2Ht7gKIs6qPHwcAzoq8RfBocMdLLSRxv1ywygAYXNHNwSqGnwcHlCW--PPJcwaeaEz1Zjpb5uPNrKDCeNeI6c9hrmazwwYBExzs~sSsd215HCPRAgb1UgIi9kGYqRdsX66Dp5yAeZbIKr28rZnl3YvPEP5mXcpjhw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq119.jpeg" /> are shown for the kinessence model with tracker potential <em>V</em>=<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>α</sup> for α= 1, for the <em>polynomial fit to dark energy</em>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (35)</a>. The solid star represents the model value of the parameter pair for the cosmological constant model. The dashed line above the LCDM point represents the quiessence models, and that below the LCDM point represents different Chaplygin gas models. The solid rhombi represent tracker kinessence models with different α, the solid triangles represent the constant-<em>w</em> quiessence models, and the solid hexagons represent Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. Only those Chaplygin gas models with κ≥Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>/(1 −Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>) are allowed. For all the dark energy models, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 is used. The square represents the best fit for the α= 1 fiducial model. The shaded ellipses represent the 3σ confidence levels in the <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq120.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=Co3zlRHc9kJxfej5KOJUi1rwBiNu8R-AE4XsROsrgo6V5uWJWsVMYn505wd2wp~XiK9d1U1AyN75XnqGoZOxW1IWAClpcI-QIi1r77TbzO1cjraOtI0HFaXiOEoiZWdrA0jhwrir2M8KmdTyZtRUpUvZFkJ3nlOGFBInMFjg0YjSOespfAJND-p8-eXSr3e7ZhgVRd4bHXsRIIrP~xCI8lXl~xauK8i8h~pKZ1JPsDGf5OXGczAviFnNsVBY4Kp-ZdkjTS40BM~kGWK6kUSzk66lmck~CDyJc1nZ0v8E~2VHXDSf4d8YFH3sCCH7CwX3TlWfPeslDDkW1lR6qLhlBw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq120.jpeg" /> space. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 exactly.</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para"><span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig13"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig13" class="link xref-fig">Figs 13</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig14"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig14" class="link xref-fig">14</a> show the performance of the ensemble-averaged statefinders 〈<em>r</em>(<em>z</em>)〉 and 〈<em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) 〉. As in the earlier case when our fiducial model was assumed to be LCDM, we find that the errors in <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) and <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) are small. However, a slight bias in the determination of the statefinders exists at low redshifts so that for <em>z</em>≲ 0.4 the value of the best fit 〈<em>r</em>〉 (〈<em>s</em>〉) is larger (smaller) than the exact fiducial value. Averaging over the entire redshift range can significantly reduce this bias and we conclude that the Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> works well even for those dark energy models for which it does not return exact values. One should also note the reappearance of the sweet spot for the statefinders <em>r</em> and <em>s</em> in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig13"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig13" class="link xref-fig">Figs 13</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig14"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig14" class="link xref-fig">14</a>. For the statefinder <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) the sweet spot appears at <em>z</em>≃ 1.6, while for <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) the sweet spot is at <em>z</em>≃ 1.2. As in the case of the LCDM model, one can try and constrain the properties of dark energy further by evaluating the averaged statefinders using supernovae data only from <em>z</em>≥ 1. Our results shown in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig8"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig8" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 8</a> demonstrate that the confidence ellipse for <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq121.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=jXOspjseWtanxU970cLTE-qZgzi9iL9j83C6bVdilQQ-X5I1qr-j-GSiurJXMf12faxf6NhnC-IgdD4RdsjNJa0MamYFxO-0ndwpX8HOtelwp8cbRQ2KuShQYstB25Z8YCy02iAc5G54zuKfcu2wVjFy~6a5xZGgpGuwZKMkoM~FPldNAVQIwEkxxv1WQXMaFzTwxrJfYCj0ZWgU3d5JokX9cuPUKsFl3RXYlRPMeYAmYn1swYqaWXbeiDNJw4DSQesbrTODVzCOLFqArzVvKf14m02ESNOwyV1wjVUQDP6O3Voxlqx2sEjsx9V~zlhTElfhrKF0J1fFNwgVV~ohzw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq121.jpeg" /> becomes much smaller when the averaging is done over the redshift range 1 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 1.7 than when the averaging is over the entire redshift range.</p>                    <a id="16661795" scrollto-destination="16661795"></a>
<div data-id="fig13" data-content-id="fig13" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 13.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig013.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=dKObwTE9q1B73fiIdXfrmV38-w0oMR0bsBremJ8mfKmPC4yU4vxWPc~8oErkOa8MhnWSmfEghl~rKxQqrLqjpW8jKRnwchsMJvWu35Gf8Jo9y09h3e78CQEGBHWx-VHoGE~pESLTQZiM3fJQ-tgM7jt9vcG6NE9G7lb60Ia2hSe3utaZT3G51XfvpQXdRbNl8zaL-SDlByAeVboCghwPI0P~yX~8zVzEE-sKe2v5Xi07EgtY1Ju6tp10YjnrPGCWZvmp8Idfrr~vG8UVZ3BfD8w8LDb8i4UZuTLYZaKjbE5~PTqLnVkTAWWc5~fKxd8zD~PqS6V-LzaWndgPQ9-7eQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Variation of 〈r(z)〉 with z for the kinessence model with the tracker potential V(φ) =V0/φα for α= 1. The solid line shows best-fitting 〈r(z)〉 averaged over all realizations calculated with the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35), for the prior Ωm= 0.3 exactly. Shaded regions represent the 1σ confidence levels for 〈r〉. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior Ωm= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ωm= 0.3 exactly. The dotted, dashed and dot-dashed lines represent the model values of 〈r〉 for different constant-w quiessence models, for tracker kinessence models for different values of α, and for Chaplygin gas models with different κ, respectively. The thick solid line represents LCDM." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig013.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661795/344-4-1057-fig013.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig013.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661795" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_pub