><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig15" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 15</a>. We see that the deceleration parameter is very accurately determined. The sweet spot for the deceleration parameter occurs at lower redshifts, at <em>z</em>≃ 0.2, and by combining higher-redshift data in determining <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq122.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=eAdpUUI2bsHTgG14VSP78UTt59x-PA61UFyf5I07S7Cvwq51dGlmN~RUoEVfB7~l4DDlwQKjBG9hEqhXyldMMBwsC2MMH4Y2-yING45vCOX5C4npS7HYz-CSU68CLHUr8KuKoqR7UKhZN93H~o2Dp6naQ4F6lsFZsbMbyg2dbRLFOkyruKOPCfWMmp7jfSXJzo7JKHWF09rD6KOeXzysj59K4Yxf6P9TXuV55EDs9BVldhUMKLgYZsnFsvHydou-GiSCgYjnwq76pydumGIATosUsF~chp5g5rW0g0~nvGKch4D0M4YWj-P5B5aX84MyV2HKys8S8sf-KFMXXZtgWg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq122.jpeg" /> with lower-redshift data for determining <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq123.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=LhFi7PK5D6JgbVMmp-nqzOmfpaqho9nYu2xY~k7Vkk1E6P2CVwO1SOfE3R1q4~qOoTJ5lkOJNF1ST-VnaRVyZ1sYK6rcrvIQl1f~kDyhsumonAKfwABeWTpwomrE-LeSCIzTWmnS~WDjFoebPMuSO846a7UmJlE3pWUzHNYrHMPywGz2BU8jIClvpyoJrxZ5vYh4tb8HQSscNanyssfLZ8-MSSDuGy65KM6o-xyyHGNBuaV0VYlSqPfRM~uwfqLPyyOhARGhYVG-c2WbPIF-EcPEzX21LdOcRd~IBJurfoLwedOuyAR8xXFdo~MdIE1oFUMKXugAlPCcehy32n~eDA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq123.jpeg" /> we can significantly improve the errors on the second statefinder pair {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>}, as demonstrated in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig10"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig10" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 10</a>. As was the case for the LCDM model, the sweet spot gradually disappears if we incorporate the prevailing uncertainty in the value of the matter density by marginalizing over large values of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>.</p>                    <a id="16661798" scrollto-destination="16661798"></a>
<div data-id="fig15" data-content-id="fig15" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 15.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig015.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=f517qhhCgZJ4uU-qTR85VE5KSVUd80EJM6~sJ3DVBb5qTjbdVdrf787GJNQXXDojyIN0kgCbuygBhIDBoCFjwApLvReh2C3MjSHYIBLAqq~F8FhwmImzt0AKxT23teMXeUxbaJg9xIK2cAuyiBB7Pg-JUnJyQA5cbOlB6sa-MMubBVQwe-X2gSS263AJcreqOQ~AiME3DWVUOGclsJPI5Ywx4c-FLq1Bz~iNENJQWiLIyOJJqucZuzWqaUF3708jzlV2GTs1uclW8VFyd~Atjezkht0CnhjcnkqZojLuxiDerJPUf7Lfafebd~L~TtKZLBI1zGpXVQlgZwaJK-XNHw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="Variation of 〈q(z)〉 with z for the kinessence model with the tracker potential V(φ) =V0/φα for α= 1. The solid line shows best-fitting 〈q(z)〉 averaged over all realizations calculated with the polynomial fit to dark energy, equation (35), for the prior Ωm= 0.3 exactly. Shaded regions represent the 1σ confidence levels for 〈q〉. We find here that the use of exact Ωm= 0.3 and the Gaussian prior Ωm= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.015 gives us almost the same bounds, represented by the light grey contour, the dark grey outer contour uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.05. The dashed and dot-dashed lines represent the model values of 〈s〉 for tracker kinessence models for different values of α, and for Chaplygin gas models with different κ, respectively. The thick solid line represents LCDM." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig015.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661798/344-4-1057-fig015.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig015.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661798" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-fig015.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&Signature=lrAZt04LcjeBcV4Yt9vvSqFi8Varhv35B49ADA61s~DJvybQe~Ucr6xNdUt8DyoHSJ3cmGYTICfA9Fc2Ipi2g8CZCpeTU~6-aVp233PwBZXHeNPQvD-rpyvJBl8jhWn2q0We1HWSgdLVKBVtW4IyxnW~n7yWOBxfbE0nQqzpOdXUR7KaGOrWKmXbAirjvYKhapbmdEz9UnP2OBgk7FhjjzS~cl0PB9tk7pN~92UlG0DP~uf8971FJGnMjU~8GG1zDohSzetefh5TtfVFudPVKTgv7xVc8tmpfhp76HjsrWmKdxyebDtFSQc4swzwA9xDvtb28l6X1GCVyLHOLFKbYg__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661798&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig015.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">Variation of 〈<em>q</em>(<em>z</em>)〉 with <em>z</em> for the kinessence model with the tracker potential <em>V</em>(φ) =<em>V</em><sub>0</sub>/φ<sup>α</sup> for α= 1. The solid line shows best-fitting 〈<em>q</em>(<em>z</em>)〉 averaged over all realizations calculated with the <em>polynomial fit to dark energy</em>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (35)</a>, for the prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 exactly. Shaded regions represent the 1σ confidence levels for 〈<em>q</em>〉. We find here that the use of exact Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 and the Gaussian prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.015 gives us almost the same bounds, represented by the light grey contour, the dark grey outer contour uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.05. The dashed and dot-dashed lines represent the model values of 〈<em>s</em>〉 for tracker kinessence models for different values of α, and for Chaplygin gas models with different κ, respectively. The thick solid line represents LCDM.</p></div></div>                    <h3 scrollto-destination=16661799 id="16661799" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss5-3>5.3 Cosmological reconstruction using other fitting functions</h3>
<p class="chapter-para">For comparison, we also carry out the reconstruction exercise using two of the fitting functions described in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-ss4-1"></span><a href="#ss4-1" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">Section 4.1</a>. In <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig16"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig16" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 16</a> we show the results for <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq124.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=dJIjymjJvHSqPvplFSo0v7XIhNYMGhzWiouq89bd47zToshBG0wpor4rurqcv3HxhPP4k4gnmZJ6lmYPATInVagbZ1Z67aFJbxtqKU-X09n87s-rNmOqBH3qFKF5oXERZH3wOX~Z9Db1wkSVFse4QMbdy5txjg-q6XBYzW6~iKn-I719kLw6xrULYMLwb50Td6Yp3HiuLSYkRfP-c8Ex6fMTxTzAhE-gGdzQT8unhru3MJY2fjDnYGA-EOM4AU4VBkSJuh7XkOuv2c30o3FZSN6tkRCcVNaFJ2ocxbIyGa01AC1~jjdt2nz~agPutomHC6rXaE22Q-3YNiOcHGzNjA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq124.jpeg" /> using the polynomial fit to the luminosity distance <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m39"></span><a href="#m39" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(39)</a> with <em>N</em>= 5. In this case, because of the nature of the Ansatz, it is not possible to place any priors on Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>. We find that this Ansatz does not perform well for the statefinder pair. First, it does not determine <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq125.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=HwBGgoLsJxG6nknREJkcB5nifk3TFJLU18zamKH0S5kcIQgF4QY5TPmHBKHTnLvegqUp-P~kGG1OATp~P0OgdlxdBRSUk9~NroC5Gnglo0moEbvtrxHfWS7gPpznjzgQ7~RTRe66WXVmS0ILg-hsU2RV56OzxHjSdDDgWCBE2TVMhdoX22aHuBD7wRxF6EFwwIeLlZAjYdZ6hOm-4svG6QHRg0SfJZVy9OJieXrZEAFxP~3OjZUMc4AtD-adEN0Sl0KiJq831~sQm9k-iMKJeQ2BoQNrTEbmRUA9NgOaj~FA7J9~K12JyMnLziUL~uCvdUbBsFZ5eWd0MHDO4YZqkQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq125.jpeg" /> with the accuracy seen in the case of the polynomial fit to dark energy. Secondly, the best-fitting value for <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq126.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=Qg6mfzCR3UsvNuvDBeDHQkOZBCcStu4nO~b8K-JbFAUFv7DJIHLGJNzSI4Bn~Nr6t3~BTwPYleApyLUAIJOpOetEhsTM3uZXPwcIdQAo2GB6h58nS2d4RMkXRGMce4RjBlJLYTQQ7QRSFYxjb1pR0qATIplW6nxUQsn-CCIT3Tby0id2FxtZLnUyv-PG0HFQFAOOb18GKlYek~W4P-3EzLbdbRZswAlNLNCUsTBSc3yy59w8iQ6hQ2zp1LNH-kWFYxC1yyukisqBUbqxpzhKVNAxnjtCSRf-IQjqgjyV3Ij8HGR8nYOl5MQ7zhzXpXG-M~xyuU0pDISaUzUCGSKvhQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq126.jpeg" /> is biased with respect to the fiducial LCDM value. Additionally, the errors on both <em>r</em> and <em>s</em> are unacceptably large due to which one cannot distinguish between the cosmological constant model and kinessence models with α &lt; 6, quiessence models with <em>w</em>≲−0.4 and Chaplygin gas models with κ≳ 2 at the 3σ confidence level. Even at 1σ (68.3 per cent CL), one can only discriminate LCDM from kinessence models with α≥ 3, quiessence models with <em>w</em>≳−0.6, and Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 3. We therefore conclude that the polynomial fit to the luminosity distance <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m39"></span><a href="#m39" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(39)</a> is not very useful for the reconstruction of the statefinders.</p>                    <a id="16661801" scrollto-destination="16661801"></a>
<div data-id="fig16" data-content-id="fig16" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 16.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig016.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=1VfexhMSN6sGYVuGR8Hud~HECpjRwsCSs~waqu9S3Nj94sAJ0vvwiKYcNrQAYLydhS0n2A7bSQ0vKtSNfBs7dwH8s7WnV-nPuQ9kmwyJodrMYInsDdYVpv85vWnd773xJ5HKvSKx5qWZ0RvTgNRRLoRnIY~jnp3APgNDyJ7XvnDrpkUZw3SPd6wf~iJaN4ZpWCdPXdmBkv~wavUu2LdxhXA-xYjO6joZ7JGiVXU9r-ZAzNNooNkZLJQiUw3EOqOrJjhXnvHFOmSwWnJZ87Sz0xU-cxedZ73c39HxyL-EmLA2blB-g1rovh8tcyeb7aDrGYkJ2FS18knRzKSysdWNEA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="3σ confidence levels in the parameter space  are shown for the cosmological constant model using the polynomial fit to luminosity distance, equation (39). The solid star represents the model value of the parameter pair for the cosmological constant model. The dashed line above the LCDM point represents the quiessence models, and that below the LCDM point represents different Chaplygin gas models. The solid rhombi represent tracker kinessence models with different α, the solid triangles represent model values for constant-w quiessence models, and the solid hexagons represent Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. Only those Chaplygin gas models with κ≥Ωm/(1 −Ωm) are allowed. For all the dark energy models, Ωm= 0.3 is used. The best-fitting point for the reconstruction is represented by the solid square. The ellipses represent the 1σ, 2σ, 3σ confidence levels in the – space." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig016.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661801/344-4-1057-fig016.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig016.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661801" 