ent tracker kinessence models with different α, the solid triangles represent model values for constant-<em>w</em> quiessence models, and the solid hexagons represent Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. Only those Chaplygin gas models with κ≥Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>/(1 −Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>) are allowed. For all the dark energy models, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 is used. The best-fitting point for the reconstruction is represented by the solid square. The ellipses represent the 1σ, 2σ, 3σ confidence levels in the <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq128.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=RIix9T8njE8rXa~nCX3kW5tZEDXZ9jk0hYzyTDeyHQ1bfpMR-5vKqgKPAoxUeRluF0miSlUVtz2Yv3mekyNV6jn4ulnqDRDKjtmgGe~njpy7pdelRbYAD5sbbWuAGtgGQ1khOtt8CJKdWmRlFh5Xed1w70JgIvM-EsefFWWygjHWfUodJ2cXY4UL99hXoOY8o43rZOrKSD~BlUN~24XSn1KuUEHpTkJTAvCSOp8GOH1MvCaSx1O9QNP76WmlCVATEtoP8SNq8LX267mDBCepMG0Sp~bKj5EBJ8bCcHbuPFwSO~NUizSuKWj~s-Ng0jWGlCZr-o9lfFUvo2f2cirkUA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq128.jpeg" />–<img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq129.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=YejzL28qKQBDcFOvEmiexC7RrGgWSHEuVc9OavLlzxnpsmGFEkWsOrjHI-HCqRobSWdCJra3vR4RRRc6iLX7ncWSwtqmftlugOOLZVHq-fqpaeSK32W0qeeoMfm3zjsyXcyJ-k218JW3W3cUILJ3e7VIkrujIN~fhmflZdkIRZo4U8IigO3dgMV11sM-MGt2s9ezyZXkgrAUJ95vP29LbeOshRhN3vS8NcW97NYNJ~a6GNFXl33kjFtaDZJdD1I3a3ijxGSfBgKD0qbd-xwAi1ExDGL4UHE62heu5knolJovYFVmJmz7prCFl56t0A72hdMT7ngYYaU~hRT7I3iSDA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq129.jpeg" /> space.</p></div></div><p class="chapter-para">We also carry out a similar reconstruction exercise using the polynomial fit to the equation of state <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m41"></span><a href="#m41" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(41)</a> with <em>N</em>= 1. This Ansatz can accommodate priors on Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> and we expect it to perform better than the polynomial fit to the luminosity distance. Indeed, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig17"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig17" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 17</a> clearly demonstrates that a two-parameter Taylor expansion in the equation of state is better than a five-parameter expansion in the luminosity distance (Our results in this context support the earlier observations of <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib52"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib52" data-open="bib52" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Weller &amp; Albrecht 2002.</a>) From <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig17"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig17" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 17</a> we find that the Ansatz <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m41"></span><a href="#m41" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(41)</a> can distinguish the cosmological constant model from quiessence models with <em>w</em>≳−0.6, kinessence models with α≥ 3 and Chaplygin gas models with κ≲ 3 at the 99.73 per cent confidence limit after we have marginalized over Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> with a Gaussian prior of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05. However, a comparison of <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig17"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig17" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 17</a> with <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig5"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig5" class="link xref-fig">Fig. 5</a> shows that the equation of state expansion <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m41"></span><a href="#m41" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(41)</a> is not quite as accurate as the polynomial fit to dark energy <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a> in reconstructing the statefinder pair <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq130.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=2xOK0SK1t5k87OBlVqGOrd5OyUukC9qBoBNCxjxcb0hmx71npTCQyuQ1AYpyO9O-KhnVVMo3UOSyBOZRXLBhAZhmARDvpcCFWVprPoGn8I8y0HoUlgxIeSd2OavwfLqIDUqnBz-412cWokdeb5JqzKCLD9meD03bTTTYuKSgDotDqm8BN~1rBjMfMFkbVaVVUadxNPJc~NnLrBuC933vQdDYQHZPRmaTnbnm8r0AI-6ddqOz-d~H1FQRWYj5KTPg5OojkTxLMT3aTvBYbpHwK2MPftlLJAe93iZahgahIwVq4VNWQ1Hbdvw0Uea0VrVmSygyIC6PglikG-pzYgleqA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq130.jpeg" />. We therefore conclude that the statefinders can be reconstructed using several complementary methods. The polynomial fit for dark energy <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m35"></span><a href="#m35" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">(35)</a>, by providing a good reconstruction of the parameters <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq131.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=ndlQ9DjZrSQukZfkilYqhP3J7rtKKBm0CwJaLqp9tUhNdgReJ5kpkzx9F8dSE~3UO0k3Tn7Iu8j1dqPWl-sNX97A9-NRXRlZmzDhT8KKHHHZD2HPB7mFE3FDrxSAi3NYegEBpt1sz0RiFHrqHm5MlSsvvjJpuvPxi3n-CWtZpizipOOwFV1epVCnjMYgt3K-h6ff0OnzVETHC6zyqvZdxE-Xfc0uylldTE6CsyRwkIBtbLrHbrn6WZp1eHWGUHsKSuNOkvDlGTSFfCpzmg3Ejk8oHlwHiAIwiuiMl~lopyFwtfqvg9Oke8EDAGDnorDp5yhEv9djiOFObaPLEvjsoQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq131.jpeg" />, can successfully be used for the model-independent reconstruction of dark energy.</p>                    <a id="16661803" scrollto-destination="16661803"></a>
<div data-id="fig17" data-content-id="fig17" class="fig fig-section js-fig-section" swap-content-for-modal="true"><div class="label fig-label">Figure 17.</div><div class="graphic-wrap"><img class="content-image" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-fig017.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=tm29BvsIyJOGXhBs7txOl~tj8QT1SRSIuhYbAAoljvG83K6tRyxuHG9Y3PeyAoH~FmFWeu6e7ih~UekipQSz138YmWKLeG9TDOHZYOaYy8SwJ19ynZcNZpUPCTn14IhpDfEGeJQVGZTeoq1uqTg7Q~0mIve7AyOkNy0UFL3JxEiOp-y0gav5l8~kfwtM6Ks-2fHuQ~-cpM1lBKc~nOZZWoriu9ev~3cLzFrqi6PiHTKHpGkklWiSEXYbMjSWHEys4WR1AiBAp2BgmdNank9LVn5pCW4viemA4S7TPLxc8A2eTr3ZOb0PYudf9-7zbWFMusLB~3kOXpvs~17PLSTC1w__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="3σ confidence levels in the parameter space  are shown for the cosmological constant model using the polynomial fit to the equation of state, equation (41). The solid star represents the model value of the parameter pair for the cosmological constant model. The dashed line above the LCDM point represents the quiessence models, and that below the LCDM point represents different Chaplygin gas models. The solid rhombi represent tracker kinessence models with different α, the solid triangles represent model values for constant-w quiessence models, and the solid hexagons represent Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. Only those Chaplygin gas models with κ≥Ωm/(1 −Ωm) are allowed. For all the dark energy models, Ωm= 0.3 is used. The best-fitting point lies on the LCDM point for this reconstruction. The shaded ellipses represent the 3σ confidence levels in the  space. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior Ωm= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ωm= 0.3 exactly." data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig017.jpeg" /><div class="fig-orig original-slide"><a class="fig-view-orig js-view-large at-figureViewLarge openInAnotherWindow" href="/view-large/figure/16661803/344-4-1057-fig017.jpeg" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig017.jpeg" target="_blank">Open in new tab</a><a data-section="16661803" href="/DownloadFile/DownloadImage.aspx?image=https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/344-4-1057-eq132.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&Signature=vffOdJoyVp6x5FY4AaabmUt3zHdVjFlRv4u4ma39XMkMP-6vfeIWIoi5v6yadqueb6TjzCHtncjdMdtEMMuEOGGTeDneCnPlCZIl0JlhvQ~WsErKQLSGd~Vh5H4GcZRCN8EQivyHhq~tXlnPH18xwAkIOlu5I3Pm~D7-uH8RBBGlTfOLk5JxwjE~zs04wFixIB~lu3XHfj6OgsXnRhEsvnhJAAgo74WTFvbq9rW90yBq9cXdelpLnpI42FEHWINE0zquNE-QJMyW2dDDOyBwY5NXUcB4HT6hFnnTpA8C8ECFtEsZnxuJm1m8qS-CefVD62marKqPmBMWiPKHsjXbhw__&Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA&sec=16661803&ar=969326&xsltPath=~/UI/app/XSLT&imagename=&siteId=5326" class="download-slide" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-fig017.jpeg">Download slide</a></div></div><div class="caption fig-caption"><p class="chapter-para">3σ confidence levels in the parameter space <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq132.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=QLx5C0H4JnjJRdPKgmarQU7sdxlUElMUxuzFrdw51mTVLJIKwnyf8Nn9qycRXP-92Uo92JUIZI6yGro0MXmPdW0dDU9x2gsbqxQ~spdMnBC0D5CtsC5e4Yor1KPsIBDl1SnvTxABsyrS9dQgu4Wx7rGX~kHpdIN4~5rXMJGv7EAzHgJ25UYxGIfUPxl9~RNbjhMeCSidGj1jOJagwXEI1ZrlImXOqE1on~e~R-3f-6ET8AojO9PVe7vVmjHAtdrHYl~XmFlKvFIodJpEudzKfBSYCFE4eKnx7u6UEhbftZgnFqjGX3~OmzSsdtjTgo8RoGpI5KKFLxgb3ubXejH~uw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq132.jpeg" /> are shown for the cosmological constant model using the <em>polynomial fit to the equation of state</em>, <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-m41"></span><a href="#m41" class="sectionLink xref-sec js-xref-sec">equation (41)</a>. The solid star represents the model value of the parameter pair for the cosmological constant model. The dashed line above the LCDM point represents the quiessence models, and that below the LCDM point represents different Chaplygin gas models. The solid rhombi represent tracker kinessence models with different α, the solid triangles represent model values for constant-<em>w</em> quiessence models, and the solid hexagons represent Chaplygin gas models with different values of κ. Only those Chaplygin gas models with κ≥Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>/(1 −Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>) are allowed. For all the dark energy models, Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 is used. The best-fitting point lies on the LCDM point for this reconstruction. The shaded ellipses represent the 3σ confidence levels in the <img class="contentFigures" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq133.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=irPyeC1vaOYr5AW7Mgn9eO0Jj~AdHB0WD4Aosg-HhK1pW-GLtUldjhvRB~Oo7h80ShQjcFo66TSvP6NplDXtjInvDoleJsuuzRoa-EeQNOtYYaCAPUmli7OjvhzVjZMT~XA~3CrVTvXR9wSzmT1h-OzJtGbzwsQMIV1t0D7Ow2qGp5tDYdqpb1PeXbk903aXbLDYbYZeeMh3cIIn8fFWILLxdqcO0n29Xpq-z75AIv5HUnuqO7foRL1JUhgMOYSME7cUvfVCK1NYVwU4BGFjiVqk84f~kK3IlZ9v-Ex~lr4jtrPwhpIGKdpU0tkxf0Yr~BWOMfru0FkUZ2aF~NsUSw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq133.jpeg" /> space. The dark grey outer contour is for the Gaussian prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ±σ with σ= 0.05, the grey contour in the middle uses the Gaussian prior σ= 0.015 and the light grey contour uses Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 exactly.</p></div></div>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=16661804 id="16661804" class="section-title js-splitscreen-section-title" data-legacy-id=ss6>6 Conclusions and Discussion</h2>
<p class="chapter-para">This paper contains an in-depth study of properties of the statefinder diagnostic introduced in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib46"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib46" data-open="bib46" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Sahni et al. (2003)</a>. The statefinder pairs {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>} and {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} have the potential to successfully discriminate between a wide variety of dark energy models, including the cosmological constant, quintessence, the Chaplygin gas and braneworld models. The statefinders play a particularly important role in the case of modified gravity theories such as string/M-theory-inspired scalar–tensor models and braneworld models of dark energy, for which the equation of state is not a fundamental physical entity and therefore does not provide us with an adequate description of the accelerating Universe. Our results, summarized in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig1"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig1" class="link xref-fig">Figs 1</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig2"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig2" class="link xref-fig">2</a>, show that the statefinders <em>r</em>, <em>s</em> considerably extend and supplement traditional measures of cosmological dynamics such as the deceleration parameter <em>q</em>. To give a concrete example of how this can happen consider two (or more) cosmological dark energy models that have identical (hence degenerate) values of <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>. Although such models will have the same current value of <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq134.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=iU83SzAafjNQ1haJg5IcowGYYhTwI9NUliV1zZCuUO6jvpbqMpY3u~OwSmV~bL7kUbN3TKygVtIYq1LG7NLtm3GDFKgSU2vXMrkMgUsJD7TS7nqKo0AvB1gQrHisCjE5D4gBg2MKwbQpXI~DYDo8tWspzQTPe~vDAHwM3-V6K2tFZ0~wEJSMk7bla~aLDSXumOjT2VlZTafvv982n~k0rrF3ujGuLRlmYoPikqj7pEuUYMvfAOMqoGFWtb~t1lNXHiLlL--R0U6TZs5iMkEusMchpLPHBlVVmlsAh~EjeNETuHrmzGqU9UL0zWfCezINRTIBD0Yg1yYDAUs2iewzJA__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq134.jpeg" />, the value of the third derivative <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq135.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=OkQK38DY2fy1e4k6cWM0qEVd0QZr-8yMl5zWNkRTzTllhRWG81862gMz0E3kKjuCqUENZWUsc8QQsp4P9nIVib4bzkcTQtD~u5TcH46llv1Hgfd-5sCCuXsgcI72u5n32b3zLspNVl-erWytzOQUSNC-yG633b57oJagNL1aRJHx8ujKlWDkaVfbt09LjVLIHqwyfnnc-8gQJFS4g6reXo83k~S~-z5atwsS-XjWtU8GB97spzFDOZRQqcrH1uJ1xkN16Q9B1~PglaDw4o-zNnQ2ogzfoHzSIoeOewy2gAMxY6JpMzOdhMhQ1ys1xhyyQayd1NFBRBddTmvgAojKJw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq135.jpeg" /> (hence <em>r</em> and <em>s</em>) will in general be different in both models. The statefinder pairs {<em>r</em>, <em>q</em>} and {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} therefore provide us with a ‘phase-space’ picture of dark energy that distinguishes dynamical dark energy models both from each other as well as from the cosmological constant and helps break cosmological degeneracies present in rival models of dark energy. The statefinder <em>s</em> is remarkably sensitive to the <em>total</em> pressure of <em>all</em> forms of matter and radiation in the Universe. As a result <em>s</em> remains sensitive to the presence of dark energy even at moderately high redshifts <em>z</em>∼ 10, when the Universe is matter-dominated.</p><p class="chapter-para">Forthcoming space-based missions such as <em>SNAP</em> are expected to greatly increase and improve the current Type Ia supernova inventory. Anticipating this development we have carried out a maximum-likelihood analysis that combines the statefinder diagnostic with realistic expectations from the <em>SNAP</em> experiment. Our results, summarized in <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig4  fig10"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig4  fig10" class="link xref-fig">Figs 4–10</a>, show that both {<em>r</em>, <em>s</em>} as well as {<em>s</em>, <em>q</em>} are excellent diagnostics of dark energy. If the value of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is known exactly, then the averaged-over-redshift statefinder pair <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq136.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=ozSPBs1D3xj~kdWmrjhRs5f-66pSx9-o6DTbt7xZ7jQ-OBW30PWEMf7s2lUBzsftA8rZm-pz~bOYzfDn1BWqaIkA9-RrQ6Dyn1jtUcpQqRQzIes6z02DnnfBgv~ibpmMbeC6jKfMknfC0lhwaokl0N-tDcpN~KJkEutzrwEkgBNT~V2WG5cL6jBZWcbUwwDBiwvw1rGutmpmqVJI6dCwkVLRnoLvGamdig4KqeM4Ky~y8nwRf4cwzEzXSbYRlKjlB19YuWbdqGIpJcPkdBuaz5fX7CnQ-IoG3Lvs87K6AA3vd~4FNnVhhVpPi2XlF74Jd5Q54V-oYzbicS28gQ3T-Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq136.jpeg" /> can distinguish between the cosmological constant model (<em>w</em>=−1) and a dark energy model having <em>w</em>=−0.9 at the 99.73 per cent CL. It can also distinguish (at the same level of confidence) the cosmological constant (LCDM) from Chaplygin gas models with κ≤ 7.</p><p class="chapter-para">Bearing in mind the fact that the current observational data determine Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> to a finite level of accuracy, we have probed how well the statefinder fares as a diagnostic after one incorporates the prevailing uncertainty in the value of the matter density by marginalizing over values of Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> that are uncertain. Somewhat surprisingly, the statefinder fares rather well even for the relatively weak prior Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub>= 0.3 ± 0.05. In this case, by employing the diagnostic {<em>s</em><sub>0</sub>, <em>q</em><sub>0</sub>}, the LCDM model can be differentiated from the <em>w</em>=−0.9 model on the one hand, and from the tracker potential <em>V</em>(φ) ∝φ<sup>−1</sup> and the DDG braneworld model (<span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-bib19"></span><a href="javascript:;" reveal-id="bib19" data-open="bib19" class="link link-ref link-reveal xref-bibr">Deffayet et al. 2002b</a>) on the other, at the 99.73 per cent CL.</p><p class="chapter-para">Finally, we should mention that of the two statefinders <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) appears to be better constrained by observations, especially if the uncertainty in Ω<sub><em>m</em></sub> is small. Interestingly both <em>r</em>(<em>z</em>) and <em>s</em>(<em>z</em>) show less scatter at higher redshifts (<em>z</em>≳ 1) and thereby complement the behaviour of the deceleration parameter <em>q</em>(<em>z</em>) and the cosmic equation of state <em>w</em>(<em>z</em>), which are better constrained at lower <em>z</em>(<em>z</em>≲ 0.4). One is therefore tempted to construct a new diagnostic <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq137.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=5CKLSG1HGxO-ZK9xacdwI7KYSBfx~W6V5vbVY-aRuu52XQg3k60d6nzVJwUACflRVmtYERCdNCr5LxgMRBXSn5xnTJsX-DKTuA19p7nIZSAec1ZEUFYWej-jYMj4xJIRI30v6H~5OXIKBdIEylnw8FfJHBhpfIGcid2zdgY3Cx64I1Ho0XLhsOKJYqgYIK-2QoLGX-rvQEercSNGcGa6lIDAtlmcZwp92DQnuCAYN6AXaeQx3hHpYTeOeem7YSK~cnRQVfsZH5SwPBJ-Ee4jGjAA66p6ksv8FOfNUTjFs6wLeS-61QKn-2gyIEtJYmN5ekJmbEjseMfQVjBIhnnXGw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq137.jpeg" />, where <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq138.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=i5Cci5esCV89Nzo7fTAb2NBsjLGHbHP8Yq5ZJHguj4-EsSAJMYFubUoofr55RYWuGST~H6eEsobwbEk2tHKbPcSn4Ey6XW7b0HttKrZRQRCnFQdVbC1Ha32gTiquvuhIC52p3fa7deQfLLp6rY0~gNATrk46yTP8xZJLk15PbQZoZb9OBAl2-~yhRsYeDXXDyld00xwiuBV92-8UYgTsqlT7QTcA1tIr7ESfyRU16EwvlV9xJUtc1D1oMYKNpSyl2ohwv3aroRVY88WAg9kIhxpa3xZpvvli52aE1hcleQYmoSpsq6WDVJlzC5-u35djgxB9sTMcq-83aDVmPTAy0Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq138.jpeg" /> is averaged over the redshift range 1 ≤<em>z</em>≤ 1.7, whereas <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq139.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=Fh7W7Qw7kkOnUK2Kkt-OYKYhHJARMHLEFXPs~WHP3UakTlCwrVHnqSHcaWpxiapEkmKNFhc8rmhp8xn5F3dLGrZD5xaSeGPjdvwldg5~VJRFjtw2rXi1sMKqIkW89Q-ZkeEUeGPE8GQuDgbQMmjfVPzdkoFiniIKhUimA9eQ3EqysiWK4zyJv70F4XScjWa8jKbH2sN1nvJmkel1~XWxgAjh9aGOoLrmBRQXjN5yB6WIp1F6ohGdP90m6RyagznVJFjLyccVQykEfZCY75TtKFQ4SqvdF2kH06nxxulnLu5f-IEEntc-pl~lNtGeUatMb3mLB-6mGg1U2NB08iTP-Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq139.jpeg" /> is averaged over the redshift range 0 &lt; <em>z</em>≤ 0.4. From <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig8"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig8" class="link xref-fig">Figs 8</a> and <span class="xrefLink" id="jumplink-fig10"></span><a href="javascript:;" data-modal-source-id="fig10" class="link xref-fig">10</a> we find that <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq140.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=rAS01smcCqm6fQlY7S9z5Fa6VJPVoq4K5Bw457rAMUsKn7gRYN4f6NQ4p7c316MWsKCjfpnaFlxiDbP9T7K~hqOep4hdKQo7R-u4kyFJXzHh4KPWr5iIHUDUEYDggfwLjo2baL5QqpwQ5Y1UlGgtlJuCynmOdhhuycCI9WTxbVfDD21~JkQxc7Q6gMEXQge~Y-kUROynRleUeMRAhxkyVaLzbVA~czynjDM~Gdd13PMAp6A8wRnZIOZqbjHlQ0j53P0aIdRJX4N9avIpQWjo1NDMifQo0NTGhYUlsl8pTLL6YRHscMyWaA3y53ZU2d-EyeuqdMWS-68k8vA46nMhCQ__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq140.jpeg" /> provides an extremely potent diagnostic of dark energy since it can distinguish a fiducial LCDM model from a dark energy model with <em>w</em>≥−0.95, on the one hand, and from a Chaplygin gas model with κ≤ 25, on the other hand, at the 99.73 per cent confidence level.</p><p class="chapter-para">We therefore believe we have convincingly demonstrated that the statefinder pair <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq141.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=dwMKI2r9bAbp33RUT48gyc4L8hSqzDAHQ0XiZq5qDY5syWsOQQfGve9zYdGHW23r1-VcDMx2UpwxMxb2CdGcDJBXYpc2xtQR5MNGfi~AR4s-eCEG7nVeN-Ig~k~54iAwHw2vbvDXayYjuIQCeDWpCEbL9a61lfch3OObArOs-K1aWKQJWpdTFQsIbjXYKWcrJNMg1HU64-CNBH59rBZyxm3-tojxeDNjHPqcM3GNeU-dEFuKomzmjSpfF1JQEEbt7F5ygwk-jiZQI7uVC21k2Hwc~It08z--TGGEdIbjodLKGXXCOAJKmLCNFXzm8H7xzwLMHGThUQICtD40qsOQ-Q__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq141.jpeg" /> and <img class="contentFigures lazy inline-graphic" src="https://oup.silverchair-cdn.com/oup/backfile/Content_public/Journal/mnras/344/4/10.1046/j.1365-8711.2003.06871.x/2/m_344-4-1057-eq142.jpeg?Expires=1712717370&amp;Signature=mt-RotXYNMCCE9tbmRYZtfhmJVukN4TP~WGHxYM8HJEGiQVpEF0y5Zup1RfdfFMo5ifgFugqaGQnwEKBoGB8C08ZazM7BkRFPiJlp2ZigM7FuN6zItigwianksaXOoqwU-SGceNekGgYKBzNdn1WgeVeuT4qwSrC9~5JGbKZyffEEw2NO3TEW5tYj9BMJWEHuAqJ3C7M6uoFTR~bTNeaKQOFjeygGxJX-KUEX6MNhT5c-Q63Esca8Qs-K2Hg8iVepCVYc9X5yMAd5NaDmzhNVjQ--GpD2DAy1pib3fMWWHdzH8NGoC9FS6bRo0urxWX-6uQqWeCYRhOZfXmuFZn9lw__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAIE5G5CRDK6RD3PGA" alt="graphic" data-path-from-xml="344-4-1057-eq142.jpeg" /> provides an excellent diagnostic of dark energy, which will be used to successfully differentiate between the cosmological constant and dynamical models of dark energy.</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=16661810 id="16661810" class="backacknowledgements-title js-splitscreen-backacknowledgements-title" data-legacy-id=ss7>Acknowledgments</h2>
<p class="chapter-para">We benefited from useful discussions with Dima Pogosyan. VS and AS acknowledge support from the ILTP programme of cooperation between India and Russia. AS acknowledges the hospitality of IUCAA where this work was completed. UA thanks the CSIR for providing support for this work. AS was partially supported by the Russian Foundation for Basic Research, grant 02-02-16817, and by the Research Programme ‘Astronomy’ of the Russian Academy of Sciences.</p>                    <h2 scrollto-destination=16661812 id="16661812" class="backreferences-title js-splitscreen-backreferences-title" >References</h2>
